<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-CHILD-SEATS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CHILD-SEATS-BOS
AIR ACCIDENTS SPUR MOVE TO ALTER RULES ON SEATING OF BABIES
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW BRELIS</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
    The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAir</ENAMEX> flight attendant in the rear of the plane making a
short flight to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charlotte</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.C.</ENAMEX>, kept peeking around the corner of
a seat in Row 21, making 9-month-old <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Danasia Brown</ENAMEX> laugh.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Like most of the two million infants under 2 who fly with their
parents every year, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Danasia</ENAMEX> was traveling for free, seated on her
mother's lap.
<p>
   As the DC-9 approached the airport on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 2, 1994</TIMEX>, wind shear
slammed the plane to the ground.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tywonda Brown</ENAMEX>'s daughter was flung out of her arms. ``I tried to
hold on to her,'' she told federal safety investigators. ``I tried
to hold her and I couldn't.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Danasia</ENAMEX> died of blunt force trauma after being hurled through
the plane at more than 120 miles per hour, battered by several
seats and parts of the cabin. She was one of 37 people to die in
the crash.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">For 16 years</TIMEX> the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> has tried
to get the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> to require that children
under 2 wear child-safety restraint systems, such as those in cars.
<p>
   In a letter <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last May</TIMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Hinson</ENAMEX>, the
board's chairman, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Hall</ENAMEX>, referred to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Danasia</ENAMEX>, saying, ``The
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Safety Board</ENAMEX> believes that if the child had been properly
restrained in a child restraint system, she might not have
sustained fatal injuries.''
<p>
   ``The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Safety Board</ENAMEX> is disappointed with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s inadequate
actions regarding the required use of child restraint systems,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hall</ENAMEX> wrote.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Association of Flight Attendants</ENAMEX>, a union representing more
than 36,000 flight attendants at 24 airlines, is even more
emphatic.
<p>
   ``It is inconceivable, given the strict rules of everything on
the aircraft  &MD;  from coffee pots to carry-on baggage  &MD;  that must be
tied down or securely stowed for takeoff and landing, or in flight
when the captain thinks it is necessary, that the same
consideration is not given to human beings, even though they are
under the age of 2,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Patricia Friend</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AFA</ENAMEX>, which
started a public education campaign <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this year</TIMEX> calling for
mandatory use of child restraint seats.
<p>
   So far, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, which regulates commercial aviation and ensures
the safety of the flying public, has refused to demand safety seats
for infants.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June</TIMEX> the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> released a report to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> that theorized
many families faced with purchasing a seat for an infant, estimated
to add <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$200</NUMEX> to the cost of the trip, would take to the highways
rather than fly. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Over 10 years</TIMEX>, some 82 children whose parents
decided to drive rather than fly, would die in traffic accidents,
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> predicted.
<p>
   At the same time, the number of infants killed in commercial air
crashes is extremely low. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> attributes the deaths of five
children in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last eight years</TIMEX> to lack of safety restraints.
<p>
   ``The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> wants to educate parents rather than mandate a rule,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> spokeswoman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alison Duquette</ENAMEX>. ``We would force many parents
with young children onto the road.''
<p>
   However, advocates for laws requiring child seats &UR;  &LR; note that the
airlines fight to keep customers and the industry devised frequent
flier rewards. Proponents of safety seats are confident the
industry would come up with a pricing scheme to keep the <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">one
percent</NUMEX> of all passengers who fly with infants.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Transport Association</ENAMEX>, representing 21 commercial
carriers, agreed.
<p>
   ``It is always difficult as an association to make comments
about pricing because of antitrust laws,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATA</ENAMEX> spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tim
Neale</ENAMEX>. ``But certainly, (they) make a good point.''
<p>
   While <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATA</ENAMEX> advocated mandates in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX>, it now wants the
government to determine which child seats perform well and which
ones do not before implementing regulations.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s civil aeromedical institute in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Oklahoma City</ENAMEX> studied
child restraint systems and found that infants under 20 pounds
should be in aft facing safety seats and children two or older, but
under 40 pounds, should be in front-facing safety seats. Some
safety seats, such as booster seats, belly belts, and normal seat
belts for children under 40 pounds, did not provide adequate
protection.
<p>
   ``If you don't have your child restrained, it really doesn't
much matter in a high-impact accident,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> investigator
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nora Marshall</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Henry Hughes</ENAMEX>, another <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> survival specialist investigator said
that even at slow speeds, a parent's arms are not
enough &UR;  &LR; to &UR;  &LR; restrain a child.
<p>
   ``I know it must be very frustrating for parents, particularly
in an emergency, but when it comes right down to it, if the child
is not restrained, there is very little protection,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marshall</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sylvia Tsao</ENAMEX> found that out with devastating results.
<p>
   She and her 22-month-old son, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Evan</ENAMEX>, were on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Airlines</ENAMEX>
Flight 232 from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Denver</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1989</TIMEX> when the tail engine blew
apart, resulting in a loss of all hydraulic power needed to control
the airplane.
<p>
   The 285 passengers and crew of 10 had more than 30 minutes to
prepare for an emergency landing at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sioux City</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iowa</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Flight attendants, including <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jan Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX>, instructed
passengers on the brace position and told the parents of the four
lap infants to follow a prescribed procedure of wrapping their
children in blankets and pillows, and placing them on the floor of
the DC-10.
<p>
   ``I remember being in the brace position with my son's head
tucked between my knees, my left hand holding his ankle, my face
pushing down on his head, my legs outside his legs,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tsao</ENAMEX> told
investigators.
<p>
   ``Suddenly, the world seemed to end. I saw for an instant my
son's body floating and flying at a very high rate of speed down
the right aisle towards the back of the plane, his head first, his
face away from me. He must have been traveling at an incredible
speed.''
<p>
   When the plane stopped cartwheeling, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tsao</ENAMEX> shouted for her son,
but could not go back to where she thought he was. Another
passenger convinced her to leave the plane, which was quickly
filling with a choking smoke. It was the smoke, an autopsy
revealed, that killed <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Evan</ENAMEX>, not injuries from the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manchester</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.H.</ENAMEX>, native stayed in the plane until
the smoke forced her out.
<p>
   ``When I left, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sylvia</ENAMEX> was the first person I saw in the
cornfield,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX> recalled in an interview. ``She was trying
to go back to the plane. I stood in front of her and said, `You
can't go back.' She said she had to get her son and then said, `You
told me to put my baby on the floor and I did and now he's gone.'
<p>
   ``At that point, I didn't have any feeling at all. The hair on
the back of my neck stood up and I knew that I would have to live
with that for the rest of my life.
<p>
   ``I know what my responsiblity is: to keep every passenger in
the cabin safe. I cannot do that if a child is sitting on a lap.
The agency with responsibility for airline safety is the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> and
they are not doing their job.''
<p>
   Since the crash, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX> has worked to have child seats
mandated, either by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> or through legislation. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Next month</TIMEX>, she
said she will come to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX> to give <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United</ENAMEX> crew members letters to
send to their representatives urging action.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX> has not spoken to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tsao</ENAMEX> since their encounter in the
cornfield. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tsao</ENAMEX>, who now lives in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Mexico</ENAMEX>, declined to comment
about the accident. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> says she hopes to speak with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tsao</ENAMEX> one
day.
<p>
   ``I am waiting until we succeed with this campaign. I couldn't
do anything for him that day, but this is what I can do and it
could give his life some meaning.''
<p>
   Some parents have voluntarily started buying seats for their
infants under two  &MD;  and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown-Lohr</ENAMEX> praises them every time she sees
one on a flight.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tywonda Brown</ENAMEX> was told it was not necessary.
<p>
   ``They told me I could hold her on my lap. I would have paid for
her to sit in a seat,'' she said. ``I would have given my life for
her. She wasn't here that long. She just turned nine months old.''
</TEXT>
