<DOCID> nyt960118.0717 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A6561 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tth-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-ENGINE-SPI </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">01-18</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX>-ENGINE-SPI
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BOEING</ENAMEX> DENIES MAGAZINE REPORT ON 777 CONCERNS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">KAREN WEST</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Seattle Post-Intelligencer</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SEATTLE</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Business Week</ENAMEX> report questions the safety of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s new 777 jetliner and says the company has been in a
``contentious debate'' with federal aviation officials over
possible design flaws.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> vigorously defended the company's newest
airplane and sharply criticized the magazine for publishing ``an
article with conclusions based on innuendo, hearsay and anonymous
sources.'' The company also said the magazine refused an invitation
for a briefing.
<p>
   In its latest edition out <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Business Week</ENAMEX> says senior
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> officials downplayed the safety
concerns of their own engineers in certification tests on the 777.
The story also says that <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for more than two years</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> officials have
been engaged in a debate with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> over possible design flaws in
the aircraft's engines.
<p>
   Quoting mostly unidentified sources, the article says <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
engineers feared that if a fan blade on one of the 777's engines
broke during flight, the engine would become unbalanced and produce
vibrations that could cause the aircraft to lose stability.
<p>
   ``It's an issue of safety,'' one unidentified <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> engine
specialist is quoted as saying. ``It could lead to catastrophe.''
<p>
   The magazine also quotes anonymous <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> sources who question
whether the airplane has been adequately tested.
<p>
   In reply, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> said: ``No one is more interested in building a
safe airplane than <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> and we stand behind the safety and
reliability of our products. No airplane in history has been tested
as thoroughly as the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 777.''
<p>
   The magazine says numerous sources told it during a four-month
investigation that pressure to meet <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s planned certification
date led the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> to overrule safety concerns.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Business Week</ENAMEX> reports that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> executives refused to comment
for the article, but <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> spokeswoman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Donna Mikov</ENAMEX> said the
magazine never acknowledged an offer for background briefings on
the certification process.
<p>
   She said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Business Week</ENAMEX> approached <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> with ``preconceived
data that had not been researched thoroughly.''
<p>
   ``It is clear to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Business Week</ENAMEX> only wanted answers
to specific speculative questions without prior knowledge and
background on the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 777 project or the certification
process,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mikov</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   In the article, senior <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> officials in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">D.C.</ENAMEX>, defend
the aircraft and the agency's safety review process.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sandra Allen</ENAMEX>, assistant <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> administrator for public affairs in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">D.C.</ENAMEX>, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that the agency had not yet read
the piece but that ``the record is clear that the testing and
analysis of the B-777 were unprecedented in their scope and
breadth.
<p>
   ``The certification process for this aircraft exceeded 125,000
staff hours by technical experts at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>. The agency maintains
complete confidence in the certification process.''
<p>
   The three makers of engines for the 777  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pratt &AMP; Whitney</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Electric</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rolls Royce</ENAMEX>  &MD;  also denied any problems, the
magazine says.
<p>
   But the magazine says there are serious concerns about the size
and weight of the fan blades in the 777 engines.
<p>
   Fan blade breaks have been reported in 24 other jet airliners
since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX>, the article said. Although no crashes have resulted
from such breaks, the magazine says <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> safety experts fear that
with the greater size and weight of the 777's blades, a break might
shake the cockpit so badly that pilots could not read the flight
instruments, increasing the risk of a crash. Despite the worries,
the FAA sources say <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> appears to have done only limited
testing to see how the 777 would react if a blade broke.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> officials maintain they cooperated fully with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
``in conducting the most rigorous laboratory, ground and flight
testing program in the history of commercial aviation.''
<p>
   The company added: ``We stand behind that process and fully
support the regulatory agencies in meeting the stringent
requirements for testing and certifying all versions of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>
777.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s 777, a <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4 billion</NUMEX> aircraft, is the world's largest
two-engine passenger jet. Its engines are the largest ever made for
a commercial airplane and have unusually heavy fan blades  &MD;  48
pounds in the largest configuration. The outer portions of 777
engines are so big that the body of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737 could fit inside
one.
<p>
   Because the 777 is equipped with two engines instead of four,
airline pilot and passenger groups initially voiced concerns about
flying the computer-designed aircraft on long-range, over-water
routes.
<p>
   But <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last May</TIMEX> when the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> gave the 777 unprecedented approval to
fly extended-range twin-engine operations, known as ETOPs, those
same groups praised it as one of the most technologically advanced
in aviation history.
<p>
   As a result of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>'s flight-test program  &MD;  which included
1,000 takeoffs and landings to simulate a year's worth of
commercial service for one plane  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> officials said the 777 would
be ``the finest, most reliable and safest airplane ever
delivered.''
<p>
   During its testing program, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> was required to prove that,
in the event of a single-engine failure, the 777 could safely
continue flying for up to three hours.
<p>
   The 777, which began commercial service <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last June</TIMEX> with a flight
from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">D.C.</ENAMEX>, has captured more than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">80 percent</NUMEX>
of the worldwide market for its class of aircraft since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX>,
according to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
