<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A4985 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITE-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">02-15</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0944 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX>-SATELLITE-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HUGHES</ENAMEX> DELAYS <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CHINA</ENAMEX> SATELLITE SHIPMENT AFTER EXPLOSION (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Updates with additional information about future launches,
crash failure.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 15</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Aircraft Corp.</ENAMEX>, the
satellite-making arm of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">General Motors</ENAMEX>, delayed shipment of a new
satellite to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> after <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">this morning</TIMEX>'s launch failure by a Chinese
rocket, a company official said.
<p>
   ``It's been delayed,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">K.C. Lang</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX> executive in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX>. ``It's been held off and we don't know when it's coming.''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">This morning</TIMEX>'s launch failure, in which a rocket exploded
shortly after lifting off, cast doubt on whether <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> will be able
to complete an ambitious schedule of satellite launches.
<p>
   ``There may be adjustments to our future plans because of the
accident,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zhang Lihui</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the rocketmaker,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall Industry Corp.</ENAMEX> ``I can't tell you anything about
the possible changes now.''
<p>
   The next launch -- of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes</ENAMEX>-built Apstar-1A communications
satellite -- is scheduled for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-March</TIMEX> aboard a Long March 3
rocket built by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The customer is the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">APT Satellite Co.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>, whose
shareholders include commercial arms of the Chinese army, space and
telecommunications authorities, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Singapore Telecom</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Thailand</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Charoen Pokhpand Group</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   A Long March 3-B rocket carrying an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX> satellite exploded
as it was being launched just after <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">3.00 a.m.</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, showering
debris on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> launch site in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION" MIN="China">southwest China</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sichuan</ENAMEX>
province.
<p>
   The rocket apparently exploded after rising just a few hundred
feet from its launch pad, crashing down on a road one mile away.
There are no reports of injuries.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall</ENAMEX> officials in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> said company executives
are locked in discussions in the capital and at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> space
base to determine what went wrong.
<p>
   It was the first launch for the heavy payload-carrying Long
March 3-B vehicle, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zhang Xiaolin</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Clean-up operations to contain the spillage of hazardous
chemical wastes have begun. Numerous calls to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX> failed to
reach any officials.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s satellite launch track record has been patchy. In
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January 1995</TIMEX>, a Long March 2-E rocket exploded one minute into its
flight, destroying the Apstar-2 satellite it carried.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> competes with American, European and Russian launchers on
the basis of price.
<p>
   An agreement <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX> between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> was to
have curtailed Chinese price cutting to a maximum of <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10 percent</NUMEX>
under <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> launch costs for proven vehicles.
<p>
   ``If the launch is successful, it will be terrific,'' the
official <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Beijing Youth Daily</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX> quoted <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Great Wall</ENAMEX>
senior engineer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Long Lehou</ENAMEX> as saying. ``However, if it fails, the
consequences will be disastrous.''
<p>
   The failure delivered a blow to a group including <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rupert
Murdoch</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">News Corp.</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tele-Communications Inc.</ENAMEX> that planned to
use the spacecraft to beam television signals to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX>. The
satellite was built by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Intelsat</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The explosion is likely to raise the cost of insuring future
launches, analysts said. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Shanghai</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Pacific Insurance Co.</ENAMEX>
insured the Apstar-1A satellite for <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">2.3 billion yuan</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$280 million</NUMEX>)
on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, the official <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Daily</ENAMEX> reported <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``Maybe the insurance policies will increase a lot for the Long
March family,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Li Ming</ENAMEX>, chief of the international business
department at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">China Pacific Insurance</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The 2-E and the untested 3-B versions of the Long March rockets
are considered by foreign analysts to be less reliable than the
Long March 3, which has had only one failure in more than 20
launches.
<p>
   The 2-E rockets are used to propel satellites into low orbits of
about 200 kilometers above the planet, while the 3-series rockets
can enable satellites to reach orbits out to 35,000 kilometers.
<p>
   This was to have been <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX>'s busiest year of satellite
launches.
<p>
   After <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next month</TIMEX>'s planned launch, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> plans to launch another
of its DongFangHong3 satellites on a Long March 3-A rocket in by
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May</TIMEX>.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May</TIMEX> or <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June</TIMEX>, a satellite for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">EchoStar
Communications Corp.</ENAMEX> is due to be launched on a Long March 2-E.
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last December</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> successfully launched an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Echostar</ENAMEX> satellite
from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Xichang</ENAMEX>, the most recent Chinese success.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX>, a Long March 3 rocket is to scheduled to carry a
ChinaSat-7 communications satellite for a Chinese-controlled
company. The satellite is to be built by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hughes Aircraft Co.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July-August</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> plans to launch a recoverable spy
satellite aboard a Long March 2-C rocket from its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jiuquan</ENAMEX> launch
base in northern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Gansu</ENAMEX> province.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Later in the year</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">China</ENAMEX> hopes to win a bid to launch the
Mabuhay communications satellite for a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX>-based consortium led
by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co.</ENAMEX> The satellite is to be
supplied by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loral Corp.</ENAMEX>
--<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Hannam</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beijing</ENAMEX> (8610) 532-4492 with reporting by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alec
D.B. McCabe</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Shanghai</ENAMEX> (8621) 6255-2634 through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hong Kong</ENAMEX>
newsroom (852) 2521-4500 jh
