<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A6882 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-LEGAL-AFFAIRS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-06</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-LEGAL-AFFAIRS-BLOOM
LEGAL AFFAIRS: COURT RULES <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LUFTHANSA</ENAMEX> SKIES AREN'T SO FRIENDLY
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 6</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> flight 463 was miles
above the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Georgia</ENAMEX> coast when <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leonard Krys</ENAMEX> had a heart attack.
<p>
   Nitroglycerine from the plane's medical kit didn't relieve the
passenger's severe chest pains. Yet, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> pilot, instead
of landing, kept the plane on course to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Frankfurt</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Eight hours later</TIMEX> when the plane landed, the 47-year-old <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX>
was rushed to a hospital. He survived -- and sued. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last month</TIMEX> a
federal judge in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> ordered the German airline, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Deutsche
Lufthansa AG</ENAMEX>, to pay <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$2.7 million</NUMEX> for, among other things, its
negligence on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX> flight.
<p>
   Judge <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Linnea Johnson</ENAMEX> noted <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> suffered permanent heart damage
and can expect a shorter life because he was denied prompt medical
care.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leonard Krys</ENAMEX> is a changed man,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> wrote.
<p>
   Such disregard for the health of its passengers isn't just a
public relations nightmare for carriers like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX>. It could
open airlines to the kind of liability they face when a plane
crashes and passengers are killed or hurt.
<p>
   ``This decision may act as the catalyst'' for people to file
similar lawsuits, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Howard Shafran</ENAMEX>, a lawyer specializing in
aviation wrongful death law.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gregg Bloche</ENAMEX>, an M.D. and professor at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Georgetown University Law
Center</ENAMEX> agrees. ``Certainly plaintiffs lawyers will pay attention,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bloche</ENAMEX> said. ``They are entrepreneurs and it's a well functioning
market.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bloche</ENAMEX> said he has been asked to help sick passengers on planes
four times and is ``amazed at how uninformed the flight attendants
seemed.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> case has prompted some carriers to reexamine
whether their aircraft and crews are equipped to deal with medical
emergencies.
<p>
   ``Airlines may be more inclined to turn around an airliner with
a sick passenger,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Columbia University Law School</ENAMEX> Professor
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Leebron</ENAMEX>, although so-called mercy landings aren't uncommon
now.
<p>
   And as part of a study, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> is
looking at whether airliners needed better medical equipment.
<p>
   Nonetheless, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chris Chiames</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Transport Association</ENAMEX>, an
industry trade group, said there is a limit to what airlines can
do. ``Our responsibility isn't to be a flying hospital,'' he said.
<p>
   Critics say the industry can do better. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> requires
airliners to have a first-aid kit on board, as well as a medical
bag with a stethoscope, syringes and other devices. The bag can be
used by a doctor -- if one is on board as a passenger.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joan Sullivan Garrett</ENAMEX>, founder of a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Phoenix</ENAMEX>-based company that
provides ground-to-air emergency medical advice, says <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> carriers
should train flight attendants in basic medical techniques and
equip planes with emergency oxygen tanks and heart monitors.
<p>
   While <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> airlines defend the current level of medical service,
some foreign carriers are doing more voluntarily.
<p>
   Eventually, lawyers say, if enough airlines install improved
equipment it creates a higher standard for the industry. Airlines
that don't keep up could face liability problems.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sydney</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Qantas Airlines</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Virgin Atlantic Airways</ENAMEX>, the
British carrier, equip their planes with automatic defibrillators.
The devices monitor a heart attack victim and provide a reviving
jolt when needed.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Airways Plc</ENAMEX> is in the process of installing equipment to
monitor a person's vital signs and send information to a medical
crew on the ground.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Qantas</ENAMEX>, which installed defibrillators in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX>, said they've
been used 50 times and saved two lives.
<p>
   But ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Qantas</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Virgin</ENAMEX> alone can't be considered a standard,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Daniel Cathcart</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX> attorney specializing in
representing victims of air crashes. ``You couldn't say the
standard in the industry is a defibrillator and that if you had one
my father would have lived.''
<p>
   Courts give pilots leeway in making judgments about mercy
landings. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northwest Orient Airlines</ENAMEX> -- now <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northwest Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX>
-- was sued in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1980s</TIMEX> after a 66-year-old woman had a heart
attack on a flight from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Anchorage</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alaska</ENAMEX>, and died in a hospital
shortly after reaching <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>. Her relatives said the pilot should
have landed earlier. The court ruled the pilot made a reasonable
decision, given that two doctors on board said the woman's
condition was stable.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> wasn't so lucky. Judge <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> concluded there were
more than enough red flags to warrant an emergency landing. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>
also took <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> to task for not asking ground personnel for
medical advice.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> travel agent, was flying to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX> at the
invitation and expense of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX>. Feeling pains shoot through
his chest and arm, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> began dripping with sweat about 90 minutes
after take-off, said his lawyer, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tod Aronovitz</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Soon he was short of breath and was having trouble speaking.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> walked the aisle with his arms raised above his head to ease
the pain. When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> went to the plane's galley to lie on the floor,
flight attendants made him return to his seat, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Aronovitz</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   A young German gynecologist returning from a vacation gave <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX>
nitroglycerine, but <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> continued to writhe in pain, according to
court testimony. The gynecologist periodically gave him oxygen.
<p>
   One passenger sitting near <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> testified she put a blanket over
her head so she wouldn't have to watch him die.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX>, which appealed the decision, declined to comment.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX>'s son, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alex Krys</ENAMEX>, flew to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX> and stayed with his
father <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for three weeks</TIMEX> while he recovered in a hospital. But their
nightmare with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX> wasn't over.
<p>
   Since <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Leonard Krys</ENAMEX>'s return ticket was on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX>, the father
and son decided to fly home on the carrier. But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lufthansa</ENAMEX>, knowing
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX>'s medical condition, wouldn't let him on board without a
doctor. So, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alex Krys</ENAMEX> said, he hired one.
<p>
   ``I expected them to extend a courtesy ticket (for the doctor)
after what had happened,'' the younger <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   No such luck -- <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Krys</ENAMEX> even had to pay a half-fare for his
father's oxygen tank.
<p>
   -- <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Bauers</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wilmington</ENAMEX> (302) 984-3372 with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Christian Plumb</ENAMEX>
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> through the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Princeton</ENAMEX> newsroom at (609) 279-4000
