<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">AZ</ENAMEX>-LOSTRING-AZR
LONG-LOST RING RAISES WORLD WAR II GHOST
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LINDA HELSER</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Arizona Republic</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   When a blackened sterling-silver ring popped up like a ghost
from the vintage debris, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Lasher</ENAMEX> was stunned.
<p>
   Poking around with a stick on his hands and knees, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> wasn't
expecting to uncover much more than a charred piece of radio in the
burned-out remains of a B-17.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Forty-nine years earlier</TIMEX>, the warplane had carried four young
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Army Air Force</ENAMEX> airmen to their deaths on the slopes of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San
Francisco Peaks</ENAMEX> near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Flagstaff</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX>, an avid hiker and aviation history buff, spotted
the ring, he could scarcely believe his eyes.
<p>
   ``Mostly what I felt was, well, it was a very humbling moment,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> said. ``I was a kid during World War II, and I was in awe of
the guys who flew these planes and this ring belonged to one of
those young airman who was alive one minute and dead the next.''
<p>
   Now, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX>, 60, a retired reproduction publishing manager for
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AlliedSignal Engines</ENAMEX>, wants to track down any family or friends of
the ring's rightful owner.
<p>
   It's not as if <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> doesn't know who the owner was.
<p>
   Through records provided by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Civil Air Patrol</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Phoenix</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> knew there had been a crash of a military aircraft at the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Flagstaff</ENAMEX> site in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1944</TIMEX>.
<p>
   In fact, with all the World War II training facilities in and
around the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Phoenix</ENAMEX> area, wreckage is reasonably common in the
mountains of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Arizona</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``They catalog crashes as far back as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1940</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> said,
``giving brief descriptions of the aircraft, the location where it
crashed and when it happened. And in those days, the military
didn't go in and clean up the sites like they do <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   Starting <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">seven years ago</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> began searching for the
wreckage. After three attempts over several years, he finally found
it.
<p>
   ``I knew a B-17 had crashed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sept. 17, 1944</TIMEX>, near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bear Jaw Canyon</ENAMEX>
but it's so overgrown that you could walk right past an engine and
not even see it,'' he said.
<p>
   He also knew that the B-17, assigned to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kingman Army Air
Field</ENAMEX> nearly 150 miles away, was on a night training flight. First
it was to visit <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Winslow</ENAMEX>, then <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tucson</ENAMEX> and back to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kingman</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   On board was Lt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard V. Howell</ENAMEX>, 24, the pilot, from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>;
Lt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard A. Davis</ENAMEX>, 22, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lincoln</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Neb.</ENAMEX>; Flight Warrant Officer
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lafayette R. Brown</ENAMEX>, 21, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New London</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Conn.</ENAMEX>; and Tech. Sgt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edmund
M. Sikora</ENAMEX>, 26, also of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   It was just at timberline where the bomber hit.
<p>
   ``Kind of a glancing blow,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> said. ``Another 100 feet
higher and they would have cleared the mountain. They came that
close.''
<p>
   After the plane hit, it broke apart, scattering debris over a
wide area.
<p>
   ``Three of the engines are still there on the ground,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX>
said, ``and the fourth is three or four feet off the ground,
embedded in a tree.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> said he returned to the crash site three or four times
after locating it and on his second visit, in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">August 1993</TIMEX>, he found
the ring.
<p>
   With the help of a friend, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Kropp</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mesa</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> obtained
not only an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> report of the accident but a newspaper story
briefly recounting the crash:
<p>
   ``After passing over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Flagstaff</ENAMEX>,'' the report said, ``the
aircraft made a 360 turn around the mountains located north of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Flagstaff</ENAMEX>. Shortly after, two fires broke out in the aircraft and a
minute later, another fire broke out at the rear of the aircraft.
The B-17 glided towards the earth. It hit the tops of trees at the
top of the peak, separating the tail assembly from the main part of
the airplane. The wreckage was completely burned. There were no
survivors.''
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sept. 23, 1944</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Arizona Republic</ENAMEX> reported: ``The bodies
of four airmen removed from a B-17 bomber, which crashed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>
near the top of 12,000 foot <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Francisco peaks</ENAMEX>, were brought out
of the wilderness to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kingman Army Airfield</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>.... A military
party reached the ship's burned wreckage <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last night</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   Once <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> unearthed the ring and wiped the years of soot and
dirt from it, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cottonwood</ENAMEX> man found the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAAF</ENAMEX>'s ``wings and
propeller'' insignia along with an eagle perched over sergeant's
chevrons.
<p>
   ``When I found out that this was an enlisted man's ring, I knew
who it belonged to,'' Lasher said. ``It had to be <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edmund Sikora</ENAMEX>'s,
the flight engineer or crew chief for that aircraft because he was
the only enlisted man aboard.''
<p>
   Checking further, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> discovered that young <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sikora</ENAMEX> was
unmarried and had listed his mother, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Josephine Sikora</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX> as
his next of kin.
<p>
   Searching a phone book, Lasher has found nearly 30 listings with
the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sikora</ENAMEX> surname.
<p>
   And now with more time on his hands, because of his recent
retirement, he intends to contact them.
<p>
   ``If I can find a relative of his that's still living, and they
have an interest,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX> said, ``I'd like to present the ring to
them.''
<p>
   For the moment, the silver ring rests in <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lasher</ENAMEX>'s jewelry box,
while a piece of the bomber's tail section sits in his yard.
<p>
   And if he fails to locate a suitable recipient in the next few
months, he'll loan the ring and the tailpiece to a new museum in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kingman</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``At least that way,'' he said, ``a part of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edmund Sikora</ENAMEX> will
finally get back to where he was trying to go.''
</TEXT>
