BC-PLANE-CRASH-BOS
4 KILLED AS PLANE HITS CAR IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MASS.</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATT BAI</ENAMEX> AND <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DAVID ARMSTRONG</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WAREHAM</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Four people, including a 4-year-old girl and
her mother, were killed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> when a single-engine airplane
trying to make an emergency landing touched down onto <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Interstate
495</ENAMEX> and collided head-on with a station wagon, officials said.
<p>
   The two people in the plane, who were not identified, and the
two passengers in the car  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karen Wilkinson</ENAMEX>, 22, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX> and
her daughter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany Karp</ENAMEX>  &MD;  died in the fiery crash, officials
said. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX> was taken by ambulance to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tobey Hospital</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wareham</ENAMEX>, where she died a short time later, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cynthia Outhouse</ENAMEX>,
a hospital spokeswoman.
<p>
   Her daughter apparently died at the scene of the accident, which
occurred at about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">12:45 p.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   The driver of the car, 31-year-old <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony Lobello</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wayland</ENAMEX>,
suffered head injuries and was evaluated at the hospital before
being airlifted to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Brigham and Women's Hospital</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late
Saturday afternoon</TIMEX>. He was in stable condition.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> that they were still trying to
identify the pilot and passenger in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Piper</ENAMEX> Arrow plane, who
apparently died instantly when the aircraft exploded on impact.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lobello</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX> were driving <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> back to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mashpee</ENAMEX>
home of her father, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edwin (Rusty) Karp</ENAMEX>, after spending the week
with her, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> lived with her father, who
dated <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for three years</TIMEX>, he said.
<p>
   ``This is the hardest day of my life,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX> said. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX>
was the best little thing in the world. She was my life. I'm just
trying now to survive.''
<p>
   Of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX>, a pharmacy technician at a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CVS</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX>
said, ``She loved <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> very much. She had a great sense of
humor.''
<p>
   At about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">12:45 p.m.</TIMEX> the plane, apparently with the engine not
working, slashed a tree next to the highway, bounced on the
northbound lane and swerved across the median, officials said. The
plane hit the white <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Chevrolet</ENAMEX> station wagon as it traveled south.
<p>
   ``It was unbelievable  &MD;  there were just flames and smoke
everywhere,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eddie Caprarella</ENAMEX>, who was driving by.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph Monteiro</ENAMEX>, who lives near the crash site just over the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Middleborough</ENAMEX> town line, said he was washing his car when he heard
the falling plane hit the highway and saw it lurch left, right and
left again. Then there were two loud crashes and an explosion that
sent flames shooting as high as 80 feet into the air, he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Monteiro</ENAMEX> said that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lobello</ENAMEX> got out of the car in a daze and was
pleading with other drivers to help <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX>, crying out: ``She's
choking! She's choking!''
<p>
   ``Definitely there was panic,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Monteiro</ENAMEX> said. ``People on the
highway were just shocked.''
<p>
   Police and aviation authorities had not determined <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> the
plane's point of origin or its intended destination. But a
spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">T.F. Green
State Airport</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Warwick</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">R.I.</ENAMEX>, said that the tower there had
received an emergency distress call from the plane saying that it
was having engine trouble.
<p>
   Controllers there tried to guide the plane to the nearest
airport, in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Bedford</ENAMEX>, but the pilot apparently attempted an
emergency landing either on the highway or in a bog next to it,
officials said.
<p>
   The plane was a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1973</TIMEX> model, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Merrill Cross</ENAMEX>, an investigator
on the scene from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>. An
investigator from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> was en
route from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, a spokesman from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   About a dozen grieving relatives of the victims arrived at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tobey
Hospital</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> in shock.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX>'s mother was told of the deaths of her daughter
and granddaughter by relatives outside the emergency room, she
collapsed instantly, wailing in agony.
<p>
   An aunt of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX>'s said, ``She was like a little flower that
was still blooming.''
<p>
   At the crash scene <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, where rescue crews continued the
grisly job of exploring the wreckage while traffic throughout the
region came to a halt, the twisted, burnt-out frame of the plane
lay stretched across <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Interstate 495</ENAMEX>. Only its wings, burnt to the
core, were recognizable.
<p>
   The station wagon, which had taken the most impact, was some 30
yards away, an empty baby seat in the front passenger side. A
child's bicycle appeared to have fallen out of the car and leaned
up against one side.
<p>
   State Trooper <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Serpa</ENAMEX>, the first trooper to arrive on the
scene, said the carnage left rescue crews shaken. ``It was a very
traumatic experience,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Serpa</ENAMEX> said. ``It wasn't something I'd want
to see every day.''
<p>
   Given the way in which the plane descended and swerved across a
major highway, it was amazing that more people were not hurt or
killed in the crash, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> Lt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ahmed Mustafa</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``Maybe everyone was already down at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape</ENAMEX>,'' he said,
alluding to the light <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX> traffic on one of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">spring</TIMEX>'s first
balmy days. ``Or maybe it was just a fluke.''
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Chacon</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> staff contributed to this story.)
</TEXT>
