<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-CRASH-BROTHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">03-31</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-BROTHERS-BOS
WORKERS REMEMBER OWNERS KILLED IN PLANE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MICHAEL GRUNWALD</ENAMEX>
AND <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">KATE ZERNIKE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  In era of corporate downsizing and labor-management
wars, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam and Jim Snyder</ENAMEX> were the kind of bosses workers dream of.
<p>
   At the brothers' plastics firm in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Rockland</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>, all 85
employees worked full time, for full benefits, and a pay scale they
helped set themselves. Every worker  &MD;  janitor or engineer,
machinist or manager  &MD;  got business cards emblazoned with the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design</ENAMEX> slogan: Together We Guarantee Success. And business
has boomed, through recessions and recoveries, up to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$8 million</NUMEX> in
annual sales.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX>' efforts in corporate responsibility came to a
disastrous end <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, when a single-engine plane they were
flying crash-landed into a station wagon on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Route 495</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wareham</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Samuel Snyder</ENAMEX>, 50, and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Snyder</ENAMEX>, 49, were killed, along with
a 4-year-old girl, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany Wilkinson-Karp</ENAMEX>, and her 23-year-old
mother, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karen Wilkinson</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Investigators who examined the wreckage <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> said they were
focusing on mechanical failure as the cause of the crash. They also
said it appears that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Snyder</ENAMEX> acted appropriately in trying to
emergency-land the plane, which was having engine trouble. A
preliminary report may be available from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">within several days</TIMEX>, but a final report
is expected to take much longer.
<p>
   Meanwhile, families, friends and employees are left to take
stock in the wake of the sudden loss of four lives.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX> had worked together since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1979</TIMEX>, when a coin toss
made <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam</ENAMEX> president and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim</ENAMEX> vice president of their new firm. They
had grown up together, and socialized together. But though both
loved to fly, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>'s ill-fated outing in a rented <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Piper</ENAMEX> Arrow
was the first time the brothers had flown together.
<p>
   ``They were a great team,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeffrey Esterman</ENAMEX>, a machinist
at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for five years</TIMEX>. ``They were always walking around
the factory, telling us how important we were to the company.
Everyone should have bosses like that.''
<p>
   Investigators believe <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Snyder</ENAMEX>, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Newton</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>, flew from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norwood Memorial Airport</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Plymouth Airport</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX> to
pick up <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hingham</ENAMEX> resident. The brothers then took off again,
headed to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Block Island</ENAMEX>, off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Rhode Island</ENAMEX>, investigators said.
<p>
   An air traffic control tower in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Warwick</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">R.I.</ENAMEX>, received the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX>' emergency distress call reporting engine trouble shortly
before <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">12:45 p.m.</TIMEX> The tower tried to guide the aircraft, a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1973</TIMEX>
model owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ADS Flight Center</ENAMEX>, to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Bedford</ENAMEX> airport.
<p>
   Minutes later, the plane bounced onto <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Route 495</ENAMEX>, swerved across
the median and crashed into a white Chevrolet Celebrity station
wagon heading south, about a mile south of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Exit 2</ENAMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX> were
trying to make an emergency landing, either on the road or in a
nearby cranberry bog.
<p>
   The plane exploded on impact, killing the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX> and little
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> instantly, officials said. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX>, who worked at a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CVS</ENAMEX>
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX>, died on the way to the hospital. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> was
supposed to attend a birthday party <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">that afternoon</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Officials at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ADS Flight Center</ENAMEX> declined to comment <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The only survivor of the crash was <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony Lobello</ENAMEX>, the driver
of the station wagon. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lobello</ENAMEX>, 31, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wayland</ENAMEX>, an unemployed auto
mechanic who had dated <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for several years</TIMEX>, was in stable
condition <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Brigham and Women's Hospital</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``He has no broken bones, only a broken heart,'' said his
mother, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marie Lobello</ENAMEX>. ``He feels like he should be dead, too. He
keeps saying, `They're dead, I should be dead.' ''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lobello</ENAMEX> told his family the plane swooped into his path out of
nowhere, giving him no chance to swerve out of the way. Witnesses
said the plane's engine appeared to be stalled and that its
propeller had stopped spinning.
<p>
   ``It was too quick, too fast  &MD;  there was nothing he could do,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marie Lobello</ENAMEX> said. ``He heard people screaming that they were on
fire, but he couldn't do anything. It was all in flames, it was
just too quick.''
<p>
   Friends and neighbors of the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX>, who both were married with
children, said the brothers were avid and reliable pilots. They
said that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam</ENAMEX> had considered a career in aviation, and that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim</ENAMEX>
also knew what he was doing.
<p>
   ``He loved flying, and he was very good at it,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew
Melton</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Snyder</ENAMEX>'s neighbor in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Newton</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   For the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX>, the fiery explosion ended a remarkable
entrepreneurial success story. Both were trained as engineers  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam</ENAMEX>
at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Naval Academy</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Columbia</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Northeastern
University</ENAMEX>  &MD;  but found their calling in the business world,
parlaying their technical knowledge about liquid resins into an
international moneymaker.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Over 17 years</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design Corp.</ENAMEX> carved a niche as a reliable
source for small but complex orders of custom-made plastic parts.
It supplies medical firms with arthro-scopes, heart pumps and
high-tech devices for spinal surgery. It makes protective suits for
helicopter crews and bomb disposal squads. It once replicated a
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1950s</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cadillac</ENAMEX> tail fin for a customer.
<p>
   With <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam Snyder</ENAMEX> overseeing the engineers and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Snyder</ENAMEX> in
charge of sales and administration, the firm has earned a
reputation as a pioneer in its field. It has grown almost every
year, and added 13,000 square feet of factory space at the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">start of
this decade</TIMEX>.
<p>
   But the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pleasant Street</ENAMEX> company is also known as a solid
corporate citizen. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1994</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX> donated a used machine-shop
lathe to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rockland High School</ENAMEX> shop department, saving the
cash-strapped school an estimated <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$30,000</NUMEX>.
<p>
   ``They were really unique,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Salto</ENAMEX>, an engineer at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design</ENAMEX>. ``I'll tell you, they always listened to what we
had to say, even if we disagreed with them. They always treated all
of us with respect. I just can't say enough about them.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design</ENAMEX> is a private firm, but the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Snyders</ENAMEX> regularly
opened their books to their employees. They also invited workers to
suggest pay structures that would reward teamwork and customer
service. And they often footed the bill for company outings, trying
to foster a sense of camaraderie and pride.
<p>
   There is no union at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Polymer Design</ENAMEX>, but every employee works
full-time, with health insurance and a 401K plan. Workers say it is
no accident that most of them have stayed with the company for
years.
<p>
   ``People just don't leave,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Esterman</ENAMEX> said. ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam</ENAMEX> were
tough businessmen, but they made sure we were all happy.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sam Snyder</ENAMEX> leaves his wife, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Marshfield</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>, schoolteacher,
and three children. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Snyder</ENAMEX> leaves his wife and two children.
<p>
   Meanwhile, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rusty Karp</ENAMEX> was preparing <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> to bury his daughter
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> next to her mother. The girl spent <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> at
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX>'s home in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX>, and was to have returned home
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX>'s home on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cape</ENAMEX>, where she has lived <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for
the past three years</TIMEX>. But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany</ENAMEX> had been ill, so <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX> agreed to
let <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wilkinson</ENAMEX> bring her back <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, as long as she returned in
time for a friend's birthday party.
<p>
   ``His whole life is dwindling,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karp</ENAMEX>'s sister, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Jane
Dyer</ENAMEX>. ``She was the center of his life, she was his everything.''
<p>
   A funeral will be held for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Karen Wilkinson</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brittany
Wilkinson-Karp</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Snyder</ENAMEX>'s funeral will be held
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>. Funeral arrangements for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Samuel Snyder</ENAMEX> were incomplete.
</TEXT>
