<DOCID> nyt960403.0713 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A8048 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BOS
TRADE MISSION TURNS TRAGIC
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">PAUL QUINN-JUDGE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ronald H. Brown</ENAMEX> and 32 others
are missing and believed dead after a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Air Force</ENAMEX> jetliner
carrying them from the Bosnian city of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tuzla</ENAMEX> to the Croatian port
of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> crashed in bad weather <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The plane hit a hillside 1.8 miles from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> airport as it
prepared to land in poor visibility, Lt. Gen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Howell M. Estes</ENAMEX> of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Joint Chiefs of Staff</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>. Croatian special police
had made their way up to the remote, cloud-covered site, Estes
said, and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> troops were on the way.
<p>
   Unconfirmed reports from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> included accounts of rescue
teams finding several bodies and one person, a woman, alive. The
woman was later reported to have died of her injuries on the way to
a local hospital. ``We have no confirmed reports of either
fatalities or survivors,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Estes</ENAMEX> said, although officials said they
were pessimistic.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> would be the first serving <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cabinet</ENAMEX> officer to die in the
line of duty in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="150 years">more than 150 years</TIMEX>. The plane was also carrying a
delegation of senior American business executives.
<p>
   Officials in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> appeared inclined to blame the weather
for the crash. They said there was no indication of hostile fire or
a suspicious explosion.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> was ``one of the best advisers and ablest people I ever
knew,'' President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> told staff at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce Department</ENAMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX> when it became clear that little hope remained
of finding any survivors.
<p>
   A consummate Washington insider and former staff director for
Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edward M. Kennedy</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> had been chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Democratic
Party</ENAMEX> before becoming <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> secretary in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX>.
<p>
   He was traveling in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Balkans</ENAMEX> with senior executives from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>
corporations in an effort to involve <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> business in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Balkans</ENAMEX>,
and particularly in the postwar reconstruction of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX>. <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Earlier
in the day</TIMEX>, he had spent time with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> troops in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tuzla</ENAMEX>, regaling
them with Big Macs and tapes of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NCAA</ENAMEX> basketball finals.
<p>
   Other passengers on the plane are thought to include members of
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s staff, senior officials of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Energy</ENAMEX>
departments, and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nathaniel Nash</ENAMEX>, a correspondent from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York
Times</ENAMEX>. Six of the missing are believed to have been the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX>
crew members of the T-43 aircraft, the military version of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>
737.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX>, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hillary Rodham
Clinton</ENAMEX> visited <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s wife, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alma</ENAMEX>, and son <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael</ENAMEX>, for 50 minutes
at the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Browns</ENAMEX>' <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> townhouse. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s daughter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tracey</ENAMEX>, was
flying in from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">California</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   After the visit, the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clintons</ENAMEX> and members of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cabinet</ENAMEX> went to
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce Department</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> addressed staff members, many of
whom wept.
<p>
   ``We do not know for sure what happened there,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said,
referring to the crash. But he paid tribute to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>, describing
him as ``a magnificent life force.''
<p>
   ``He was one of the best advisers and ablest people I ever knew.
And he was very, very good at everything he ever did. Whether he
was <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">commerce</ENAMEX> secretary or a civil rights leader or something else,
he was always out there just giving it his all,'' he said.
<p>
   ``This is a man whose multiple talents will not be easily
replaced,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eleanor Holmes Norton</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">District of Columbia</ENAMEX>'s
delegate to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>. ``For the African-American community, the
loss is into infinity.''
<p>
   After visiting the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> home <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kennedy</ENAMEX>
issued a statement saying, ``At a time of increasing polarization
and heightened voices and more intense rhetoric, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ron</ENAMEX> cut to the
core of an issue and was able to reconcile different viewpoints in
a way that established common ground. We need those talents much
more as a country.''
<p>
   Fears for the plane began to surface in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">late
Wednesday morning</TIMEX>. Well over three hours after the plane had been
due to land, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> put out a terse statement saying that
it was missing. By then, night was beginning to fall in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Croatia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   For a number of hours, the fact that the plane was missing was
the only confirmed piece of information. Confusion reigned, with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>
and Croatian officials offering differing locations for the crash
site.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> officials spoke of wreckage being seen in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Adriatic Sea</ENAMEX>
off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>, while Croatian officials, including President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Franjo
Tudjman</ENAMEX>, said the plane had crashed into a mountainside near the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> airport.
<p>
   Planes and helicopters searched the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Adriatic</ENAMEX> for signs of a
crash. But the Croatians, whose troops were scouring the mountains
around the airport, proved to be right. <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Later in the day</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Estes</ENAMEX> of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Joint Chiefs of Staff</ENAMEX> pieced together the chronology of the
tragedy at a press briefing in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s plane had left <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tuzla</ENAMEX>, the northern Bosnian city that is
the headquarters of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> military operations in the country, around <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2
p.m. local time</TIMEX> (<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7 a.m. EST</TIMEX>). The flight should have taken about 45
minutes.
<p>
   Because of bad weather around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>, the pilots used an
instrument approach, a standard procedure in poor weather, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Estes</ENAMEX>
said. The plane was in contact with the control tower in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>
when communications were suddenly lost at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:52 p.m. Croatian time</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The plane crashed into the top of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">St John's Hill</ENAMEX>, a 2,300-foot
hill about 1.8 miles northwest of the airport, he said. Officials
noted that the crash site put the plane well off course.
<p>
   The T-43, based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ramstein</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, had been used to transport
a number of VIPs around the region, officials said, including
Defense Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Willian Perry</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hillary Clinton</ENAMEX> and the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clintons</ENAMEX>' daughter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chelsea</ENAMEX>. It had undergone a ``total''
maintenance and inspection in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 1995</TIMEX> and run up a total of about
17,000 flying hours, a relatively modest amount, he said.
<p>
   Bad weather had not hindered other planes landing at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>
airport <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tudjman</ENAMEX> told <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CNN</ENAMEX> that three aircraft  &MD;  two
Croatian and one Swiss  &MD;  had landed there <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="``half an hour'' before">``half an hour'' before
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s plane was due to arrive</TIMEX>.
<p>
    &UR; el.5l &LR; 
<p>
   But conditions remained so bad that a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> military helicopter was
unable to land near the crash site and had to return to the
airport.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Air Force</ENAMEX> appointed Brig. Gen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Coolidge</ENAMEX> to lead
an inquiry into the crash. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Coolidge</ENAMEX> was to leave for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
night</TIMEX>, and will be assisted by members of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Officials said the plane lacked a flight recorder, which might
have helped determine the cause of the crash.
<p>
   Investigators will almost certainly be able to use less
conventional sources of information. These could include AWACS, or
airborne warning and control systems, aircraft and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Security Agency</ENAMEX>, the secretive communications intelligence
organization that is reported to be very active in monitoring the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Balkans</ENAMEX> peace process.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-03-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2345EST</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960404.0682 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=u> A9080 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX>-TRAGEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-04</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX>-TRAGEDY-BOS
BODY OF <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX> AMONG 33 RECOVERED
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">PAUL QUINN-JUDGE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Working in foul weather and hampered by the hazard
of mines, search parties on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Saint John's Hill</ENAMEX> just outside
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Croatia</ENAMEX>, recovered the remains of 33 people <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>
from the wreckage of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Air Force</ENAMEX> jet. Among them was the body of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ronald H. Brown</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> and his colleagues died on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> when their plane,
flying in heavy rain and near-zero visibility, apparently went off
course and crashed into the hillside, nearly 2 miles northwest of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> airport. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> was flying to the Croatian port city for
talks with government ministers after visiting <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> troops in the
northern Bosnian city of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tuzla</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   As investigators arrived to search for the causes of the
accident and military mortuary teams started work, confusion
remained on a number of key issues. Why was the plane off course?
Were there 33 people on board or 35, as a manifest released by the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">State Department</ENAMEX> indicated? Did the plane have a voice recorder and
so-called black box and if not, why not?
<p>
   Two things were clear, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> Ambassador to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Croatia</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Galbraith</ENAMEX>
said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> after he visited the crash site. One was
that the weather was terrible: ``In fact, people in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> said
this is the worst storm in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a decade</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   The other was that the plane ``was not where is should have
been.'' Instead of approaching the airport from the sea, it was
flying up a valley ``one ridge over'' from the airport, he said.
<p>
   Officials do, however, seem to be increasingly confident that
the plane was not attacked by renegade soldiers from any of the
armies operating in the region.
<p>
   While the area had once been on the front lines in the war
between Croat and Serb armies, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Perry</ENAMEX> said
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that potentially hostile forces were no longer in the
area. And, he added, ``you cannot direct ground fire against an
airplane if you can't see it.'' Visibility in the area was so bad
at the time of the crash, he said, that ``directing small arms fire
or directing a shoulder-fired rocket at the airplane would have
been almost impossible.''
<p>
   But, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perry</ENAMEX> added, it would take ``some days'' for investigators
to determine exactly what happened. Officials have declined to
speculate about the causes of the crash. But a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense Department</ENAMEX>
official said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, ``The most likely hypotheses are serious
pilot error or serious equipment malfunction.''
<p>
   In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, meanwhile, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> ordered all flags on
official buildings to be flown at half-staff until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 10</TIMEX>. After
a private memorial service at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">St John's Church</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, a
short distance from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> once again paid
tribute to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>, his government colleagues, the business
executives and others who died with him.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>'s spokesman, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael McCurry</ENAMEX>, described the president as
``in a very somber mood.''
<p>
   No date has yet been announced either for a funeral or for the
return of the bodies. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>'s family was to gather <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> to
discuss the funeral arrangements, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McCurry</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Earlier Thursday morning</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> said, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> broke
the news to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Alma Brown</ENAMEX> that her husband's body had been identified
by Brig. Gen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew Canavan</ENAMEX>, the senior <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> military officer on the
scene.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perry</ENAMEX>, reflecting on the death of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX> and of Deputy Assistant
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph Kruzel</ENAMEX>  &MD;  killed in an accident outside
Sarajevo, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia-Herzegovina</ENAMEX>, in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">August</TIMEX>  &MD;  said the tragedies
illustrated the risks involved in operations such as the one in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But, he told journalists, ``I believe our security interests are
worth risks.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Perry</ENAMEX> noted that he had in fact flown to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Egypt</ENAMEX> in
the same plane the day before it returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX> to collect
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brown</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   By <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">late Thursday</TIMEX>, remains of 14 people had been removed from the
crash site and taken to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense Department</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   An internal government memo described the scene at the crash
site. The memo said that the aircraft, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>-made T-43, was
lying in pieces, with fragments spread over a radius of 400 meters.
The plane showed some signs of fire, but there were no indications
that it had been struck by a projectile. The bodies were thrown
clear of the plane.
<p>
   Heavy rain, high winds, fog and wind chills in the low 30s
continued to make the retrieval work difficult. The bad weather, in
fact, seems to have played a role in diverting investigators flying
from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Vicenza</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX>. A <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> mortuary team has
arrived at the scene, and additional staff is on its way from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fort
Lee</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Virginia</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Croatian officials at the site continued to insist that black
boxes  &MD;  voice and data recorders built to withstand a crash and
help explain its causes  &MD;  had been found at the site.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Estes</ENAMEX> disputed this. ``The information we have is that this
aircraft was not equipped with what you would consider black
boxes,'' he said. Searchers may have recovered instruments in black
boxes, he said. But real black boxes are in fact colored bright
orange, to facilitate their retrieval.
<p>
   The T-43 is the military equivalent of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737. Most of
the 19 purchased by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> have been used to train aviators
in navigation.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Estes</ENAMEX> attributed the lack of a black box to the fact that the
plane had been acquired originally as a training aircraft.
</TEXT>
