<DOCID> nyt960411.0712 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A6394 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-CRASH-YOUNGPILOT-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-11</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-YOUNGPILOT-BOS
7-YEAR-OLD TRYING FOR PILOTING RECORD DIES IN CRASH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ADAM PERTMAN</ENAMEX> AND <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JANE MEREDITH ADAMS</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
    A 7-year-old girl, pursuing her dream of becoming the
youngest pilot to crisscross <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX>, died <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> when her plane
plummeted at the start of her journey's second leg.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica Dubroff</ENAMEX>'s body was found in the wreckage near the
municipal airport in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cheyenne</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyo.</ENAMEX> Her father, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lloyd</ENAMEX>, and her
flight instructor, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joe Reid</ENAMEX>, also died in the crash.
<p>
   The three left an airfield outside <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pescadero</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>,
spent the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cheyenne</ENAMEX> and planned to conclude their trip by
meeting the young girl's mother in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Falmouth</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> sent investigators to
the scene of the crash, and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>
said it would review its rules governing who may operate an
aircraft. The minimum age for taking a plane's controls alone is
16, but there's no restriction on anyone doing so alongside a
willing licensed pilot.
<p>
   ``I fly for joy. I'm going to fly till I fly solo. I'm going to
fly until I die,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> said before leaving here <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>. As
she climbed into her <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cessna</ENAMEX> 177B in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyoming</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, she expressed
just one fear: ``crashing.'' But she went on to say she did not
worry about it.
<p>
   At 4-foot-2, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> was too short to reach the plane's pedals,
so they were equipped with extenders for her. The craft had two
sets of controls, so <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reid</ENAMEX> could take over  &MD;  as he did over the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Rocky Mountains</ENAMEX> on the way to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyoming</ENAMEX>  &MD;  whenever he deemed it
necessary.
<p>
   Authorities said they were unsure who was guiding the plane when
it went down in driving rain and snow <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>, minutes
after attaining a height of only a few hundred feet. A witness, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom
Johnson</ENAMEX>, said he saw the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cessna</ENAMEX> stall over the building where he
worked and then nose-dive ``like a dart'' before smashing into the
ground near a driveway and scores of houses and cars.
<p>
   Why <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reid</ENAMEX> allowed the flight to take place <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> is a mystery.
Asked about his pending trip before leaving <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pescadero</ENAMEX>, he replied:
``Basically the only ground rule is good weather. ... If there's
any weather ahead of us that doesn't look good, we're either going
to wait it out or go around it.''
<p>
   The girl's parents, who did not live together, sought to give
her an untraditional upbringing. Her mother, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lisa Blair Hathaway</ENAMEX>,
taught <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> and her two other young children at home. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lloyd
Dubroff</ENAMEX> tried to provide what he described as a ``real world''
education  &MD;  for example, encouraging <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> to try and break the
record for youngest cross-country pilot.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hathaway</ENAMEX> told reporters in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Falmouth</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that she had no
second thoughts about how she was rearing her children and
suggested that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s death should not lead other parents to
impose undue restrictions on their own.
<p>
   ``I beg people to let children fly if they want to fly,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hathaway</ENAMEX> said, crying. ``Clearly I would want all my children to
die in a state of joy, but not at age 7 ... I know <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jess</ENAMEX> did her
best.''
<p>
   At <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan International Airport</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>, where <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hathaway</ENAMEX> left
for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyoming</ENAMEX>, she added that she just wanted to get to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cheyenne</ENAMEX> to
``hold my child, dead or alive.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joan Hathaway</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ashburnham</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mass.</ENAMEX>, who accompanied her sister
to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX>, defended <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s mother. ``She was just very
supportive; she wanted her children to experience different things,
so she supported them in doing those kinds of things,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joan
Hathaway</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> lived with her mother, 9-year-old brother <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joshua</ENAMEX>, and
3-year-old sister <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jasmine</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pescadero</ENAMEX>, a farming and fishing
community 50 miles south of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Francisco</ENAMEX>. Her father lived in the
nearby city of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Mateo</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Both parents thought their children should be educated through
unconventional means like flying  &MD;  to learn weather-forecasting,
geography and physics  &MD;  riding horses and building furniture. ``I'm
the culprit,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lloyd Dubroff</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier this week</TIMEX>, when he told
reporters he first suggested <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> try flying coast-to-coast.
<p>
   ``They're getting a tremendous education from having their lives
be in the real world,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hathaway</ENAMEX>, 41, told the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">San Francisco
Examiner</ENAMEX> before <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX> embarked on her attempt to set a record.
Had she succeeded, it wouldn't have been official because the
Guinness Book of World Records eliminated its ``youngest pilot''
category <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">several years ago</TIMEX> out of concern it might encourage unsafe
flying.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>, who would have turned 8 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next month</TIMEX>, had less than a
month to set the unofficial record. It was set in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX> by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Daniel
Shanklin</ENAMEX>, who was one day shy of 8 when he flew from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Diego</ENAMEX> to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kill Devil Hills</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.C.</ENAMEX>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>, along with her two siblings also took music lessons,
including piano and trumpet. All were encouraged to excel and take
risks, friends and neighbors said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pescadero</ENAMEX> community flag was lowered to half-staff in her
memory and a local florist hung out a sign that read, ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>,
you inspired all of us. Keep soaring.''
<p>
   For the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$50</NUMEX>-an-hour flying lessons, paid for by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lloyd Dubroff</ENAMEX>,
57, a corporate consultant in nearby <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Mateo</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s mother
would drive a white minivan to the hangar at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Half Moon Bay Airport</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael Benson</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX>, said, ``We will be
looking at everything related to this accident.'' He said crashes
involving child aviators are rare. ``Our initial search of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX>
records does not turn anything up.'' He said the safety board will
``look at any regulations or requirements that could have played a
factor in this.''
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Adams</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> correspondent, reported from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pescadero</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pertman</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>. Contributing were <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Patti Nealon</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Martin F.
Nolan</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Matthew Brelis</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> staff, along with wire
service material)
</TEXT>
