<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NAVY</ENAMEX>-PILOT-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-12</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NAVY</ENAMEX>-PILOT-CRASH-NYT
(ATTN: <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tenn.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX> ) 
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NAVY</ENAMEX> BLAMES SHOWING OFF FOR JET CRASH
(ll)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">TIM WEINER</ENAMEX> 
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> that a pilot was probably
showing off for his parents when he crashed an F-14A jet fighter in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nashville</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX>, killing himself, a fellow officer and three
people on the ground.
<p>
   The pilot, Lt. Comdr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Stacy Bates</ENAMEX>, had been grounded for a
month in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 1995</TIMEX> after he lost control of another F-14A after
taking off from the aircraft carrier USS Lincoln. The plane crashed
after the pilot and his crew ejected. The crew members were
rescued.
<p>
   Rear Adm. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bernard Smith</ENAMEX>, who investigated the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nashville</ENAMEX> crash,
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bates</ENAMEX>' judgment was influenced by his parents' presence at the
field'' and his desire to show them risky takeoff and flight
maneuvers.
<p>
   The admiral said that in taking off from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nashville</ENAMEX> airport
on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 29</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bates</ENAMEX> ascended at an angle steeper than 50 degrees,
violating <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> rules.
<p>
   After the near-perpendicular takeoff, in the clouds, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX> said,
the pilot became disoriented, and in all likelihood did not realize
that he was heading earthward until his jet pierced the clouds at
2,300 feet.
<p>
   By then, the admiral said, it was too late to prevent the plane
from smashing into the house of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Elmer and Ada Newsom</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   In addition to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bates</ENAMEX>, 33, and his radar intercept officer, Lt.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Graham Alden Higgins</ENAMEX>, 28, those killed were the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Newsoms</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ewing
Wair</ENAMEX>, who was visiting them.
<p>
   The crash would never have happened had the pilot made a normal
take-off or taken the cloudy weather into account, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Smith</ENAMEX> said after
an 11-week review of the incident.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-12-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2015EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960420.0155 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A6979 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-CHILD-PILOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-20</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CHILD-PILOTS-NYT
REACTIONS TO DEATH OF ONE CHILD PILOT MAY GROUND OTHERS
(bl)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DAVID M. HERSZENHORN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">PLAINVILLE</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Conn.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The boys, ages 12 to 14, peered intensely at
their instructor, their red textbooks open to Lesson 23:
``Emergency Procedures, Wind Shear, Turbulence.'' The instructor,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Calla</ENAMEX>, began. ``What are some types of emergencies?,'' he
asked. ``Engine failure,'' one student said. ``Electrical fire,''
said another. ``Ice,'' someone else piped in.
<p>
   The boys are students in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX>, a six-year-old nonprofit
program that seeks to build motivation and raise self-esteem by
teaching young people how to fly airplanes.
<p>
   Every <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX> they practice on the ground and in the
sky with instructors from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Robertson Airport</ENAMEX>, a tiny airstrip in
this tiny town just west of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hartford</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX> fly in planes with dual controls and with an
instructor in the next seat. They labor over pre-flight safety
checks. For practice, they simulate stalls in flight.
<p>
   They do not fly to break records. And they are all older than
7-year-old <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica Dubroff</ENAMEX>, who died, with her father and flight
instructor, in a crash <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX> as she tried to become the
youngest person to fly across the country.
<p>
   But the reaction to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s crash may ground these young
pilots sooner than any emergency for which they rehearse.
<p>
   Federal law requires student pilots to be at least 16 years old
before they are allowed to fly solo. Younger children can fly as
long as there is a licensed pilot sitting next to them at the
controls and acting as pilot in command.
<p>
   But since <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s crash, three Republican state senators from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Connecticut</ENAMEX> are seeking to ban children under the age of 16 from
flying.
<p>
   Sens. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kevin F. Rennie</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Rocky Hill</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Nielsen</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Danbury</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John A. Kissel</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Enfield</ENAMEX> proposed the ban, and on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> voted to add it to a bill dealing with child restraints
in automobiles. The amendment states: ``No person under the age of
16 shall engage in the operation of aircraft. No person shall aid a
person under the age of 16 in the operation of aircraft.'' The bill
itself must now go before the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> for ratification.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rennie</ENAMEX> said that he and his supporters considered the ban a
safety precaution that would close an inadvertent gap in the
federal law. He said the ban came at a time when the legislature
was also banning newly licensed drivers from the roads <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">between
midnight and 5 a.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   ``We're putting restrictions on driving a car for six months
after you get your license,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rennie</ENAMEX> said. ``At the same time we
will be debating whether or not someone younger than that can be
flying an airplane, and it strikes me as one of those <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kafka</ENAMEX> moments
in the legislature.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Calla</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX> instructor, sees the ban as
misguided.
<p>
   Federal safety investigators who looked into the crash said they
believed <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica</ENAMEX>'s instructor was in control of the airplane when
it went down just after takeoff.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Calla</ENAMEX> and others involved with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX> noted that the
responsibility for the flight  &MD;  and, they say, for any pilot error
that would have contributed to the crash  &MD;  lay with the pilot in
command, not with the 7-year-old.
<p>
   The ban, they say, would end one of the only programs in the
country dedicated specifically to teaching young people to fly
responsibly, and even worse, they say, would be the lost
opportunity to teach lessons about life through aviation.
<p>
   ``I am the adult,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Calla</ENAMEX> said. ``I am in control of the
aircraft. I am the sole person responsible for keeping us out of
harm's way. It really aggravates me that they want to throw it all
away when we could be educating the world in the correct procedures
in handling the safe operation of aircraft, making students more
knowledgeable about the world around them, opening up their eyes to
new horizons, all in an environment that has a safety net: the
flight instructor.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joe Tortorici</ENAMEX>, a public school art teacher who volunteers as the
director of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX>, said that students in the program would
have known better than to take off in a storm like the one in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyoming</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``This school is designed to raise self-esteem, to foster
decision-making, including the kind of decision that would have
kept that plane on the ground,'' he said.``We're not training
pilots. We are training mature adults.''
<p>
   Indeed, learning how to fly also involves learning more than a
smattering of physics, mathematics and meteorology, and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud
Chasers</ENAMEX> students portray a seriousness beyond their years.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Neil Brewer</ENAMEX>, 14, said he would not fly in bad weather. ``It's a
safe way to play it,'' he said. ``I think that a good portion of
things we learn here are how to make judgments. We learn the more
technical aspects of flying. We learn why stalls happen. We
practice stalls and go and actually do the maneuvers in the
plane.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nathan Sheely</ENAMEX>, 14, said he had been fascinated by planes since
birth. The hardest thing about learning to fly, he said, was
learning ``to always be a step ahead of the aircraft, to know
what's going to happen before it happens and to know what to do.''
<p>
   State Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rennie</ENAMEX> said he had not heard of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX>
program until his office received a call from <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Calla</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
But he said he remained firm in his belief that youngsters should
not fly.
<p>
   ``With <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cloud Chasers</ENAMEX> you may have found the best example, with
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jessica Dubroff</ENAMEX> you may have the worst, most egregious example,''
he said. ``Most of the examples probably fall in between. We make
public policy with a broader brush and so we have to make some
decisions that apply equally to both extremes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rennie</ENAMEX> also said he had received a call from a constituent who
lets his 9-year-old fly the family plane and who invited the
Senator to come up for a ride. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rennie</ENAMEX> begged off. ``I don't like
flying in big planes,'' the senator said, ``let alone in small
planes.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">04-20-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1547EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
