<DOCID> nyt960501.0018 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A9722 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttc-z> BC-EMERGENCY-LANDING-LAD </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-01</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0918 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-EMERGENCY-LANDING-LADN
(<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX> ATTN)
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SOUTHWEST</ENAMEX> JET BOUND FOR <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BURBANK</ENAMEX> MAKES EMERGENCY LANDING
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MARY SCHUBERT</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Los Angeles Daily News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LOS ANGELES</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest Airlines</ENAMEX> jetliner en route from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las
Vegas</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank</ENAMEX> made an emergency landing at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario International
Airport</ENAMEX> after the landing gear failed to fully lower, but none of
the 132 people aboard was hurt.
<p>
   The left landing gear of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737-300 failed to lower all
the way <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, so the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank</ENAMEX> tower diverted Flight 1767 to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario</ENAMEX>, which has longer runways.
<p>
   After several failed efforts to shake the stuck gear loose, the
pilot landed the plane in a lopsided position, with just the nose
wheel and right landing gear down.
<p>
   ``Everybody was really amazingly calm. I don't know whether it
was shock, but there didn't seem to be any sense of panic,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Larry Spears</ENAMEX>, 49, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">North Hollywood</ENAMEX>, who said he was on the
flight. ``I have been on much rougher landings with both sets of
landing gears. It was amazingly smooth.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said he was returning home from an overnight getaway to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The nearly full flight, with 127 passengers and five crew
members aboard, had left <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1 p.m.</TIMEX> and was due in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank</ENAMEX>
at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2 p.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   The pilot, an eight-year <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX> veteran, landed the jetliner
safely at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:40 p.m.</TIMEX> on the north runway, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Melanie Jones</ENAMEX>, a
spokeswoman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dallas</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX>. She refused to identify
the pilot, citing company policy.
<p>
   ``No passengers or crew were injured,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Maria Tesoro</ENAMEX>, a
spokeswoman for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ontario Airport</ENAMEX>. ``All the passengers are safe, and
the cause of the difficulty with the landing gear is unknown.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said passengers became aware of the problem when the jet
began its descent toward <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``As he was lowering the landing gear, there was a real loud
thump, much louder than normal. About 45 seconds later, there was
another loud thump,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> recounted.
<p>
   The pilot announced that a light on the instrument panel
indicated the landing gear hadn't engaged, and he would circle the
jet past the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank Airport</ENAMEX> tower to see if the controllers could
spot a malfunction, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   That strategy failed because the plane couldn't fly low enough
for the tower to see the wheel, so the flight was rerouted to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario</ENAMEX>, located 35 miles east of downtown <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The pilot did a low fly-by past the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario</ENAMEX> control tower, and
at that point airport officials verified the landing gear was
stuck, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The flight crew twice tried a maneuver to knock the landing gear
free: sharply climbing and accelerating, and then abruptly cutting
back the power. ``He called it a `maximum G-force maneuver,' and it
was basically (intended) to try to jolt it down by force of
gravity,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``It really was like a roller coaster. Our stomachs went up past
our throats and into our noses,'' he joked.
<p>
   When that technique didn't work, the pilot announced he would
try a hard touch-and-go landing on the one free wheel, in hopes the
hard impact would jolt the other wheel down, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``He told everybody: `There's no need to be alarmed. We do this
thing all the time  &MD;  in simulators,' and everybody groaned.''
<p>
   Again, the attempt failed. The pilot announced the only option
left was an emergency landing. Flight attendants began
demonstrating crash precautions as the plane circled to burn off
and dump excess fuel, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The crew asked younger, stronger passengers to sit near the
exits and help with evacuations, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Passengers were directed to take off their glasses and
high-heeled shoes. ``We started a really slow descent into the
airport,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``The captain came on and said we would only be going about 60
mph. They would try to set it down on the one wheel, and they would
try to ease it down really slowly,'' he said.
<p>
   As the jet landed, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said he could see ``the fire trucks
racing down the runway beside us.'' Firefighters sprayed
fire-retardant foam on the plane as a precaution.
<p>
   ``The captain said: `Stay in your seats. We're on the ground
safely,''' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spears</ENAMEX> said. ``At that point, everybody cheered.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> said the jetliner had just undergone a ``major maintenance
inspection'' <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 16</TIMEX>, but she wasn't sure whether the landing gear
was checked at that time. Such periodic inspections are required by
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>, she noted.
<p>
   ``We know that the landing gear wouldn't come down, (but) we
don't know the cause of the malfunction,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> said. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> sent aircraft mechanics out to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario</ENAMEX> to inspect the
plane, she said.
<p>
   ``We took it new from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">eight years ago</TIMEX>. That's very new
for an aircraft,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``We have a perfect safety record <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for 25 years</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX> said.
``Occasionally, we have things go wrong, as with any piece of
equipment with mechanical parts. But we think our crew did a
wonderful job of landing the airplane.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX> offered the stranded passengers an option: a ride to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Burbank Airport</ENAMEX> or a motel room near the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario Airport</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jones</ENAMEX>
said.
<p>
   ``The (north) runway was closed <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">five minutes prior to the
landing of the airplane</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tesoro</ENAMEX> noted, but she didn't know how
many landings and takeoffs were delayed or diverted while the north
runway was out of commission.
<p>
   The 737-300 was taken out of service to be repaired by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX>
crews at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ontario</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tesoro</ENAMEX> added.
</TEXT>
