<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-545(2TA </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-11</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0548 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-545(2TAKES)-NYT
(ATTN: <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ga.</ENAMEX>)
109 FEARED DEAD AS JETLINER CRASHES IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EVERGLADES</ENAMEX>
(Eds: This is a late addition to The New York Times front page.)
(ll)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ROBERT D. McFADDEN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> DC-9 jetliner with 109 people aboard crashed in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX> shortly after takeoff from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami International
Airport</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX>. Aviation and rescue officials found
widely scattered debris and said there were apparently no
survivors.
<p>
   Bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>, the twin-engine aircraft was about 30 miles
northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION" MIN="Miami">Miami airport</ENAMEX> when the pilot reported smoke in the
cockpit, a spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> said.
The plane was believed to be turning back to the airport when radar
contact was lost shortly after <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2 p.m.</TIMEX>
<p>
   ``We believe that the aircraft is down somewhere in the vicinity
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX>,'' the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> spokesman, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony Willett</ENAMEX>,
said.
<p>
   The cause of the crash was unclear. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX>, which
is based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX> and serves 26 cities in 17 states, began
operations in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX> with an old fleet that has grown to about 50
planes.
<p>
   It has experienced a number of problems, including several
aircraft that have run off runways and one that caught fire, but
never a crash.
<p>
   Television pictures from helicopters flying over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX>
at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">midafternoon</TIMEX> showed no shattered fuselage, tail assembly or
other large sections of the plane, only what appeared to be widely
scattered pieces of whitish debris that flecked the high grasses
and desolate swamps. It was unclear how deep the water was.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> said the crash site was 15 miles west of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Opa Locka</ENAMEX>, or
about 20 miles northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>. But it was unclear by <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">late
Saturday afternoon</TIMEX> whether the precise crash site had been located.
<p>
   One aerial picture showed a depression and what appeared to be
scorched earth, but rescue pilots found no clear signs of wreckage
or survivors from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s Flight 592, a daily two-hour flight
from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The crash site appeared to be inaccessible by road. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast
Guard</ENAMEX> dispatched rescue helicopters and aircraft to the site, and
airboats were being mustered to carry rescue and other emergency
personnel to the area.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> said in a statement that the plane was carrying 104
passengers and a crew of five. Earlier reports had said that as
many as 112 and as few as 90 were on board.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s fleet, said to be the oldest in the industry, has run
into a series of problems in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last two and a half years</TIMEX>, the
most serious being a fire on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 8 last year</TIMEX> that destroyed a DC-9
on a runway in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   A flight attendant was burned and six other injuries were
reported as 57 passengers and 5 crew members were evacuated.
<p>
   An <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> investigation in the wake of the fire found ``a
significant decrease in the experience level of new pilots being
hired by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> as well as other positions, such as mechanics and
dispatchers.''
<p>
   The inquiry said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s rapid expansion from two to 48 planes
had been accompanied by accidents and incidents involving
inexperienced pilots, inadequate maintenance and insufficiently
trained flight attendants.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-11-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1817EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
