<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-2NDTAKE </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-11</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0586 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-2NDTAKE-NYT
UNDATED: flight attendants.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>, which had proclaimed itself the fastest-growing airline
in history, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last month</TIMEX> that it would buy fewer airplanes than
it planned <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX> and would ``concentrate on its product
integrity'' in anticipation of the summer Olympic Games in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last Jan. 12</TIMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> DC-9 with 30 people aboard slid into a
snowbank after landing at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dulles International Airport</ENAMEX> outside
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, closing the airport for three hours.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Jan. 26</TIMEX>, another a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> DC-9 got stuck in the mud at
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport</ENAMEX> and 101 passengers had to
be bused back to the terminal.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Feb. 28</TIMEX>, another <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> plane ran off a runway in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Savannah</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ga.</ENAMEX> And on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Mar. 19</TIMEX>, an emergency chute inflated inside the cabin of
a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> plane in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tampa</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, slightly injuring a flight
attendant; the pilot had to crawl out a window, climb into the
plane through the tailcone and cut the chute with a knife to free
the attendant.
<p>
   Because of the inaccessibility of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>'s crash site, few
details were available in the hours immediately after the plane
went down. In its statement, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> said that Flight 592 had left
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> at about <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:15 p.m.</TIMEX>, more than 70 minutes after its regularly
scheduled departure time.
<p>
   It said the DC-9-32, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell-Douglas</ENAMEX> plane configured with
seats for 113 passengers, radioed at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:25 p.m.</TIMEX> that it was
returning to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> statement did not mention smoke in the cabin, but
other reports said the pilot had spoken to air-traffic controllers
of smoke in the cabin.
<p>
   The airline quoted preliminary reports as saying the plane went
down about 20 miles northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> ``in a dense area of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX>, making accessibility difficult.''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Three hours after the crash</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> reported that the jet had
been about 100 miles northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> when the pilot reported
smoke in the cockpit, and that after turning around had gone about
80 miles before crashing.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> report said the plane had apparently gone into a steep
dive and exploded on impact.
<p>
   A student pilot, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rick DeLisle</ENAMEX>, who was flying a small plane in
the area with an instructor, bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Naples</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla</ENAMEX>, told <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CNN</ENAMEX> of
witnessing the crash. After hearing his instructor yelling, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeLisle</ENAMEX>
said, ``I turned and saw an explosion.''
<p>
   ``There was nothing in the sense of fire,'' he said. ``It was
almost like what I would call a mushroom cloud. It went up 100
feet.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeLisle</ENAMEX> said he and his instructor flew closer and examined the
ground with binoculars. ``We got down to about 200 feet or so, and
with the binocs it looked like a large trash bag worth of debris.''
<p>
   As word of the crash was flashed over news reports, relatives of
people who had been on board went to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami International Airport</ENAMEX>,
seeking information on what had happened.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hernando Vergera</ENAMEX>, an airport spokesman, said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Office of Dade
County Aviation</ENAMEX> was bringing counselors to meet with family
members, about 50 of whom were at the airport. They were being
taken to an undisclosed location for privacy, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vergera</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> personnel at the airport declined to comment, and had
minimal contact with the families of the victims, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vergera</ENAMEX> said.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> did not immediately return telephone messages.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> told The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Associated Press</ENAMEX> that rescue aircraft
were helping to look for wreckage and survivors. But all that
rescue pilots could detect was scorched earth, Petty Officer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Angela
Weeks</ENAMEX> said.
</TEXT>
