<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-COLORADO-STOCKS-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-13</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0455 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">COLORADO</ENAMEX>-STOCKS-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">COLORADO</ENAMEX> STOCKS: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">UAL</ENAMEX> RISES <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2.8%</NUMEX> TO LEAD INDEX TO RECORD HIGH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeanie Stokes</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Denver</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 13</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado</ENAMEX> stocks climbed to a
record high as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">UAL Corp.</ENAMEX>, parent of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Airlines</ENAMEX>, rose in the
wake of the crash of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Inc.</ENAMEX> DC-9 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this weekend</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The Bloomberg Colorado Stock Index rose 0.86, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">0.61 percent</NUMEX>,
to 141.07. Advancers outnumbered decliners 48 to 35 in the
price-weighted index that tracks shares of companies with
operations in the state.
<p>
   In the broader <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> stock market, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
Index rose 9.42, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">1.44 percent</NUMEX>, to 661.51. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average climbed 64.46, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">1.17 percent</NUMEX>, to 5582.60.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">UAL</ENAMEX> rose 6, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">2.8 percent</NUMEX>, to 214, as the stocks of major <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
airlines registered their biggest one-day advance in almost a
month. The S&AMP;P airline index rose 12.37 to 344.53, with investors
favoring established carriers over recent start-ups.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">UAL</ENAMEX> is included in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado</ENAMEX>'s index because of its dominant
position in the state's economy.
<p>
   Investors said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>'s crash of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> DC-9 in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida
Everglades</ENAMEX> cast a pall over the ability of fledgling airlines to
raise sufficient capital to replace older jets. The crash killed
109 people. ``People have been able to get financing fairly
readily,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph Ray</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Gerald L. Ray &AMP; Associates</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dallas</ENAMEX>
money management firm that oversees <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$500 million</NUMEX> in assets. ``It
will be interesting to see what the capital markets say about all
this.''
<p>
   Among those carriers that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ray</ENAMEX> is watching is <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado
Springs</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Western Pacific Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX>, which fell 3/4 to 15
3/4 to lead the state's declining issues. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Western Pacific</ENAMEX> hopes to
add eight aircraft to its 14-plane fleet by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of 1996</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Denver</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Frontier Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX>, which fell 3/4 to 7 5/8, is
also growing. The airline, which marks its <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">second anniversary</TIMEX> in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July</TIMEX>, is putting its eighth and ninth aircraft into service <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
summer</TIMEX>, and hopes to add at least a couple more <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737s <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The state's other airline, cargo carrier <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Atlas Air Inc.</ENAMEX>, fell
7/16 to 53 13/16.
<p>
   Other advancing stocks included <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Lockheed Martin Corp.</ENAMEX>, up 2 n1/8
at 83 1/4; <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Amrion Inc.</ENAMEX>, up 1 1/2 at 18 5/8; <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Exabyte Corp.</ENAMEX>, up 5/8
at 20 5/8; and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Newmont Mining Corp.</ENAMEX>, up 5/8 at 59 1/8. Other
declining issues included <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boston Chicken Inc.</ENAMEX>, off 5/8 at 35 7/8,
even though it reported <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">first-quarter</TIMEX> profit doubled.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Adolph Coors Co.</ENAMEX> fell 7/16 to 17 13/16, while <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FirstMiss Gold
Corp.</ENAMEX>, dropped 3/8 to 37 5/8.
<p>
   The Colorado index has gained <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">18.62 percent</NUMEX> since the first of
the year, compared with the S&AMP;P 500's <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">7.40 percent</NUMEX> advance.
</TEXT>
