<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4284 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-CRASH-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-13</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0843 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-MAIN-COX
EDs: Will update with <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">8 p.m.</TIMEX> news conference.
CRASH INVESTIGATORS BRAVE ENVIRONMENT RECOVER `BLACK BOX,' BODY
PARTS; SEARCH CONTINUES FOR SECOND RECORDER, CAUSE
EDs: With CRASH-PILOT, CRASH-ID, CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>.
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">GARY KANE</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JOHN FERNANDEZ</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MIAMI</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Undaunted by a hostile environment, crash scene
investigators extracted a flight data recorder and dozens of body
parts <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> from the marshy grave of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592.
<p>
   The discovery marked the first real victory for recovery crews
since the aircraft nosedived into a desolate expanse of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida
Everglades</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two days ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> investigators said the
``black box,'' which was in the powder-blue tail of the DC-9
aircraft, was located during a plotted-grid search of the crash
site.
<p>
   The flight data recorder measures altitude, speed and
acceleration of the aircraft at the time of an accident. The device
will be taken to an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> laboratory in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> where it will be
analyzed for clues to the cause of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>'s crash.
<p>
   Search crews are still looking for a second recorder which is
designed to capture the conversations in the cockpit.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-bound plane crashed roughly nine minutes after
takeoff from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>'s airport with 104 passengers and five crew
members. The flight crew reported smoke in the cockpit and cabin
before the tower lost contact.
<p>
   While a marksman atop an airboat scanned for alligators and
poisonous water moccasins, five teams of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Metro-Dade police</ENAMEX> divers
took turns wading through the waist-deep soup of water and muck.
The walked gingerly, groping with their hands and feet for chucks
of debris or remains of victims.
<p>
   The six members of each crew were linked to each other with rope
 &MD;  muck beneath the surface water is soft enough in spots to swallow
trespassers. Gooey and black, the muck is full of decaying plant
material. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">South Florida Water Management District</ENAMEX> specialists at
the site measured muck at 3-5 feet deep with 12-18 inches of water
atop.
<p>
   Like archaeologists working a dig, the investigators marked the
search area in square plots.
<p>
   The site, sandwiched between two canals, is just east of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miccosukee Indian Reservation</ENAMEX> and nine miles from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Route 41</ENAMEX>. It is
roughly 16 miles northwest of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> airport runway.
<p>
   Helicopters shuttle searchers to the site, where they work in
shifts of about 20 minutes. They wear hazardous-material gear and
masks and tightly tape pant legs and shirt sleeves for added
protection against irritating jet fuel and bacteria in the water.
At the end of each shift, the teams remove their dive suits and
drop them in barrels of disinfectants.
<p>
   Investigators said they have little hope of finding any intact
bodies. The aircraft reportedly plunged into the marshland at a
75-degree angle at an estimated speed of 500 mph.
<p>
   About 40 body parts were recovered <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>  &MD;  nothing larger than
a knee. By <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">noon</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, seven body bags of remains were loaded onto
an airboat normally used for everglades tours and taken to a levee
where emergency vehicles and vans from the medical examiners office
assemble.
<p>
   As the grim search progressed, federal transportation officials
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> provided new details about the stepped-up scrutiny of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> had been reviewing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s
operations since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX> because of a series of problem flights.
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>'s crash prompted <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> officials to begin a month of
intensive inspections of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s maintenance plants and cockpit
procedures.
<p>
   Inspectors are visiting <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s 29 field maintenance
facilities where mechanics handle minor repairs and make sure
planes are ready for their next flight. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> also wants to check
work at six contractor maintenance facilities used by the airline.
Among them: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aero Thrust</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>, where engine repairs are made,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aero Corp.</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lake City</ENAMEX>, which handles airframe work, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sabre
Tech</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The crash has sparked questions about the age of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>'s
fleet. The DC-9 that crashed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> was 27 years old. But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
officials suggested <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> that older aircraft can be perfectly
safe because any plane 15 years or older is required to have
frequent inspections.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBS News</ENAMEX> reported that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> was to be investigated as part of
an overall probe being conducted in the wake of the crash by the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Transportation</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBS</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Transportation</ENAMEX> was looking into the
possibility the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> knew <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> was headed for trouble before the
crash. The network said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> declined to comment on the probe.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Airlines</ENAMEX> stock dropped sharply <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, the first day of
trading since the crash and also the first day of intensified
federal scrutiny of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-based carrier. It closed on the
Nasdaq Stock Market down <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$4.18</NUMEX>} a share at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$13.68</NUMEX>}. This story was
supplemented by wire service material.
<p>
   (Story Filed By <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Palm Beach Post</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">West Palm Beach</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>)
</TEXT>
