<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4312 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-CRASH-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-13</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-SCENE-BOS
IT'S INVESTIGATORS VERSUS NATURE AT <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EVERGLADES</ENAMEX> CRASH SCENE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MICHAEL REZENDES</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   THE <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EVERGLADES</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  With a government sniper patrolling for
alligators and snakes, 30 divers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> combed the mud and inky
waters of this vast swamp in a gruesome search that yielded one of
the two flight recorders from doomed Flight 592.
<p>
   Federal investigators are hoping the flight-data recorder, also
known as a ``black box,'' will offer clues about the cause of the
crash that took 109 lives <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX>, when a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> DC-9
nose-dived into a desolate stretch of saw grass, water and ooze
about 15 miles northwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``We're encouraged that we found it and hope we can find the
second one which recorded conversations in the cockpit,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike
Benson</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Rescuers also continued the grim search for bodies. By <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">midday</TIMEX>
seven body bags of remains had been removed.
<p>
   ``I don't hold any hope we'll find any recoverable large parts
of people,'' said retired <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dade County</ENAMEX> Medical Examiner <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph
Davis</ENAMEX>, who is taking part in the investigation.
<p>
   The flight-data recorder found <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> by divers measures
altitude, speed and acceleration of the aircraft at the time of an
accident. But some investigators believe more significant
information will be contained in the box that recorded the crew's
conversations.
<p>
   Meanwhile, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBS News</ENAMEX> reported that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX> was to be investigated as part of an overall probe
being conducted in the wake of the crash by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of
Transportation</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CBS</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX> was looking into the
possibility the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> knew <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> was headed for trouble before the
crash. The network said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> declined to comment on the probe.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> began an intensive review of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>, in which
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> inspectors were to ride in the cockpits and review the
company's maintenance facilities <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for the next month</TIMEX>.
<p>
   President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said he directed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation</ENAMEX> Secretary
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Federico Pena</ENAMEX> to report <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this week</TIMEX> on the additional measures the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> plan to take to ensure <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US</ENAMEX>
airlines ``continue to operate at the highest level of safety.''
<p>
   ``I'm determined to do everything I can to make sure American
aviation is the safest in the world,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Although officials were buoyed by retrieving the flight-data
recorder, officials from a widening array of civilian and military
agencies remained stymied about how to retrieve pieces of the
airliner from what one investigator called the most difficult scene
ever encountered for recovering a large passenger plane.
<p>
   ``We're going to have to be prepared for the fact that this may
take us some time,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, vice chairman of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> would not say whether investigators might ultimately
have to leave victims and large portions of the plane entombed in
the swamp, which sucked the entire airliner into its murky depths.
<p>
   But the problems associated with retrieving the submerged craft
from a site more than 300 yards from the nearest road mounted even
as new plans for recovery were considered.
<p>
   ``At any accident site you end up leaving something, you never
recover every single part,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said investigators and salvage crews haven't ruled out
any option for retreiving the wreckage. Nevertheless, an early plan
to build a new road to the scene of the crash has been frowned upon
because of environmental considerations.
<p>
   Although the federally protected <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades National Park</ENAMEX>  &MD;  home
to rare animals, birds and plants  &MD;  is posing unprecedented hurdles
to government salvage crews, it is considered environmentally
fragile due in part to pollution from nearby sugar cane farms.
<p>
   A plan to build an artificial dam around the crash site, so that
water can be drained from the area around the wreckage, has also
met with skeptisim. Local geologists say the rock underlying the
swamp is so porous that water would inevitably seep back into the
site.
<p>
   Other potential recovery plans include construction of a
floating staging area near the wreckage and the erection of
temporay bridging from the nearest roadways.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Navy</ENAMEX> salvage experts arrived began searching for the
flight-data recorder with an underwater listening device called a
hydrophone to try picking up radio signals emitted from the data
recorder.
<p>
   The box has a ``pinger'' that transmits a signal for 30 days.
But the signal would be activated only if the data recorder rests
in water and may be impossible to pick up if the box is covered in
mud.
<p>
   ``The equipment is designed for ocean operations, not for swamp
operations,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Greg Geisen</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> spokesman at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>.
He added that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> personnel on the scene ``don't know the terrain.
They're still trying to assess if they can even possibly assist.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> salvage experts include the head of diving and salvage
operations at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy Sea Systems Command</ENAMEX> and a civilian expert
from the firm of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Oceaneering Technologies</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maryland</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Federal officials <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> also continued to paint a harrowing
picture of the aircraft's passengers and crew, which encountered
smoke in both the cockpit and cabin before the plane plunged into
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX> at an estimated speed of more than 500 m.p.h.
<p>
   The crew, speaking with great urgency just minutes after leaving
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami International Airport</ENAMEX>, made its last transmission at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:13
p.m.</TIMEX>, asking air traffic controllers for the location of the
airport  &MD;  then failed to respond when the information was given.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> investigator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Greg Feith</ENAMEX> said it was impossible to say
whether the crew was conscious.
<p>
   Meanwhile, the recovery of human remains continued with urgency,
due to rapid decomposition caused by subtropical weather, swamp
bacteria and spilled fuel.
<p>
   Dr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Roger Mittelman</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dade County</ENAMEX> medical examiner, said the
largest remain recovered so far was a knee. He said his office
would rely on heart pacemakers, teeth, fingerprints, tatooed skin
and DNA tests to identify the bodies. He said officials also would
test for the presence of carbon dioxide in the remains, which could
indicate whether the cabin was on fire when the plane went down.
<p>
   Many high level officials were giving much credit to the divers
who, because of the jet fuel and other contaminants in the water,
taped themselves into airtight protective body wrap before donning
rubber suits to work 20-minute shifts in water with near-zero
visibility.
<p>
   For the most part, officials said, divers searched blindly for
bodies and wreckage using their hands, feet and long poles.
<p>
   ``It's not the most efficient of operations,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
``It's tough going.''
<p>
   (To read previous <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> coverage and related information on the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash, go to the Globe Online at http://www.boston.com. Use
the keyword: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>.)
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Matthew Brelis</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> staff in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX> contributed to this
report. Material from wire services also was included.)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-13-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2121EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960513.0579 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A4390 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttx-z> BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-13</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0787 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-TEX
PILOTS REMEMBERED AS `VERY SAFETY CONSCIOUS'
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fort Worth Star-Telegram</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Candalyn ``Candi'' Chamberlin Kubeck</ENAMEX> was apparently the first
female captain killed in a commercial airline crash, and one of
only a few female commercial pilots killed in a crash, other pilots
said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Pilots, friends and family praised <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> and her co-pilot,
First Officer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Sherrill Hazen</ENAMEX>, as experienced and ``very
safety conscious,'' with excellent flying records. They were among
the 109 killed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> when <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 592 plummeted
into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   One of the only other female pilots killed on duty in a
commercial crash was the co-pilot of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Airlines</ENAMEX> 737 that
crashed in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colorado Springs</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Colo.</ENAMEX>, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beverly Bass</ENAMEX>, an
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Airlines</ENAMEX> captain and founder of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">International Society
of Women Airline Pilots</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> had been involved in two previous aircraft incidents as
pilot, neither of them serious, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>
records show.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November 1991</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> was flying a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fairchild</ENAMEX> Metro 3
twin-engine turboprop for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Grand Airways Inc.</ENAMEX>, a now-defunct
sightseeing and commuter airline that operated between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX>
and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Grand Canyon Airport</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Arizona</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Upon landing at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Grand Canyon Airport</ENAMEX>, the propeller of the
aircraft's left engine struck a deer on the runway. There were no
injuries and no significant damage to the aircraft, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> records
show.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sept. 2, 1994</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> was piloting another <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX>
DC-9 for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> when the plane skidded sideways on a wet runway
during a landing in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>, records show.
<p>
   There were no injuries, but the jet had to be towed to the gate,
records show.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> records show that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> passed a checkride in a simulator
after the incident, scoring a ``high grade.'' No <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> enforcement
action was taken against her for her performance during the skid,
although the incident report indicated that she had failed to
maintain directional control of the aircraft.
<p>
   Each of the earlier events involving <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> was classified by
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> as an ``air carrier incident,'' rather than the more
serious ``accident.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX>, a 35-year-old <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Diego</ENAMEX> native, lived with her
airline-captain husband in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Phoenix</ENAMEX> and maintained an apartment in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bedford</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Texas</ENAMEX>, where she was based at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dallas/Fort Worth Airport</ENAMEX>.
She was first licensed as a pilot in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1978</TIMEX> at age 17 in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Encinitas</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">San Diego</ENAMEX> suburb.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February 1983</TIMEX>, in the wake of President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reagan</ENAMEX>'s firing of
striking air traffic controllers, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> became a controller in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">El Paso Airport</ENAMEX> control tower, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> said. She left that job in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1984</TIMEX> to pursue a career as a professional pilot.
<p>
   She had <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> licenses as an air-transport pilot, certificated
flight instructor (airplane and instrument) and control-tower
operator, and had ratings to fly single- and multiengine airplanes.
She was qualified to fly the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Beech</ENAMEX> 1900, DC-9 and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fairchild</ENAMEX> Metro 3 aircraft.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kubeck</ENAMEX> had 8,805 flight hours, including 5,388 hours as a
captain or pilot in command, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> officials reported. Since
joining <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1993</TIMEX>, she had accumulated 2,073 flight
hours with the airline, including 1,697 as a captain in the DC-9.
<p>
   She last passed the required annual first-class pilot's medical
exam <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 12</TIMEX>, records show.
<p>
   As a pilot, she was ``very experienced, very well-trained, very
competent,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lewis Jordan</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hazen</ENAMEX>, 52, was also assigned to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">D/FW</ENAMEX> base, from which
the airline operates as many as five daily round trips to its main
hub, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hartsfield Airport</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hazen</ENAMEX>, a retired <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> pilot, had 6,146 flight hours. He
lived in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mineola</ENAMEX>, a small city northeast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tyler</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">East Texas</ENAMEX>,
and had been flying for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX>, a family spokesman
said.
<p>
   He previously worked for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Express</ENAMEX> and for an airline
taking tourists to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mexico</ENAMEX>, said his stepdaughter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kimberly Reedy</ENAMEX> of
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Irving</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> records show that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hazen</ENAMEX> had an air-transport pilot's
license, as well as a flight engineer's certificate. His ratings
included single- and multiengine aircraft, and he passed the
first-class medical exam in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">September 1995</TIMEX>.
<p>
   As a pilot, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hazen</ENAMEX> was ``very safety conscious,'' son-in-law <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Marc
Reedy</ENAMEX> said. ``He was proud of his safety record and proud to be a
pilot.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kimberly Reedy</ENAMEX> said the tragedy is ``hard to believe.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hazen</ENAMEX>
used to take her for rides in his two-seat plane and ``just fly
around for fun.''
<p>
   ``He loved to fly,'' she said. ``That was what he always wanted
to do.''
<p>
   (Staff writers <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Andrew Backover</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dan Reed</ENAMEX> contributed to this
report.)
</TEXT>
