<DOCID> nyt960514.0451 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A5635 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-14</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-BOS
(Eds.: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AvAtlantic</ENAMEX> is cq)
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> SAFETY CHECK WEAKNESSES REPORTED BY PROBERS BEFORE CRASH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">AARON ZITNER</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Two weeks before <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592 carried its 109
passengers to their deaths in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX>, federal auditors
reported that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>'s airplane safety
checks lacked some of the basic elements of a common automobile
inspection.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, as the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> responded to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash with a plan
to hire more inspectors quickly, those same examiners cautioned
again that the agency should also change its inspection and
training procedures to make the skies safer. Congressional critics
echoed their remarks.
<p>
   During an aircraft check before a flight, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> inspectors are not
required to check vital equipment, such as the landing gear and
engine, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Raymond J. DeCarli</ENAMEX>, an assistant inspector general for
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">US Department of Transportation</ENAMEX>. ``Can you imagine taking your
car in for an inspection and having the brakes and tires checked <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">50
percent</NUMEX> of the time?'' he asked. ``There's no checklist of what
they have to inspect.'' An inspector ``can do virtually nothing and
it's considered an inspection.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeCarli</ENAMEX>'s spoke as some congressional lawmakers called for more
scrutiny of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> inspection procedures and questioned whether the
agency is too cozy with the industry it is assigned to watch. The
inspector general's office also said it would investigate reports,
first aired by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ABC News</ENAMEX>, that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> encouraged inspectors to ``go
soft'' on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Lawmakers said the various investigations of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
would bring new urgency to a debate over the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s structure and
funding. Some critics want to strip the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> of its mission of
promoting the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX> air travel industry, saying it cannot nurture
young airlines or aircraft manufacturers and ensure safety at the
same time.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeCarli</ENAMEX>'s comments, made in a phone interview, echoed his
testimony before a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> subcommittee <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 30</TIMEX>, in which he said
that training, personnel-testing and other <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> procedures were
inadequate.
<p>
   For example, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeCarli</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> failed to crack down on the
use of unapproved parts in airplane repair. Moreover, a study by
his office showed that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> workers checked landing gear in only <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">48
percent</NUMEX> of their preflight plane inspections. They checked the
engines <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">52 percent</NUMEX> of the time and engine controls a third of the
time.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DeCarli</ENAMEX>'s report was one basis for a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Newsweek</ENAMEX> magazine essay by
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Fackler Schiavo</ENAMEX>, inspector general for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation</ENAMEX>, in
which she said she has skipped conferences rather than fly on
``marginal airlines.'' She said she avoids flying on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>
because of a history of ``mishaps.''
<p>
   Those comments alarmed lawmakers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ron Wyden</ENAMEX>, a Democrat from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Oregon</ENAMEX>, called it ``troubling''
and ``bizarre situation when the inspector general says they don't
feel comfortable flying an airline that is out flying planes and
offering its services to the American public.''
<p>
   At a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> hearing on the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, scheduled long before the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash, other lawmakers said they were hesitant to comment
on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> procedures without knowing the cause of the accident. Sen.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ted Stevens</ENAMEX>, a Republican from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alaska</ENAMEX>, criticized <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> for
``destroying confidence'' in air safety. ``I suggest the president
has the right to remove an inspector general for dereliction of
duty,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stevens</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike McCurry</ENAMEX> said there was no talk of
removing <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> from her job.
<p>
   At the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate Transportation Committee</ENAMEX> hearing, top <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
officials said they would take three steps to improve safety:
<p>
    &MD; Speed the hiring of 91 inspectors by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of June</TIMEX> who were
due to be hired by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>. The agency has already hired 140
inspectors <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX> and has asked <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> for 150 more in its
next budget. It has about 2,500 inspectors.
<p>
    &MD;  Speeding up introduction of a system that tracks inspection
data and flags dangerous conditions.
<p>
    &MD;  Reviewing the work that inspectors do to make sure they focus
on top priorities.
<p>
   Separately, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> issued an emergency order <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> suspending
flight operations of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">HCL Aviation Inc.</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AvAtlantic</ENAMEX> because of
``discrepancies in the training, testing and qualifications of
flight attendants.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AvAtlantic</ENAMEX>, based in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Savannah</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ga.</ENAMEX>, leases
planes to the presidential campaign of Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Dole</ENAMEX>, which said it
expects no interruption in <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dole</ENAMEX>'s travel schedule.
<p>
   Even before the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash, lawmakers had been wrestling with
how to improve the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>. Plans to change the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s dual mission
could generate the biggest debate in the next few months.
<p>
   As part of the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> administration's efforts to boost <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>
exports, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Federico Pena</ENAMEX> and FAA
administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Hinson</ENAMEX> have traveled overseas to help sell
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">US</ENAMEX>-made airplanes. But the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> is also charged with making sure
those planes are safe.
<p>
   ``There is an inherent conflict in those two missions,'' said
Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William S. Cohen</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maine</ENAMEX> Republican.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> administrator, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that the air system
is safe and improving. If the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> had the same accident
rate today as in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1960</TIMEX>, he said, a fatal air crash would occur every
10 days. ``When we say an airline is safe to fly, it is safe to
fly,'' he said. ''There is no gray area.''
<p>
   At the same time, though, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> budget of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$8.6 billion</NUMEX> is down
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$600 million</NUMEX> from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX>, and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> has lost 5,100 workers, a cut
of about <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10 percent</NUMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony J. Broderick</ENAMEX>, associate administrator
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that the level of worker training has
decreased significantly, ``and quite frankly, I think it's too deep
a decrease.'' The agency has requested a <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">6 percent</NUMEX> increase in its
training budget for <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Complicating matters, the agency has lost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$550 million</NUMEX> in
monthly revenue because <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>, amid the impasse over the federal
budget, has not renewed a 20-year-old tax on airplane tickets and
cargo. Plans to revive the tax are tangled in a debate over the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s structure and a controversial plan to replace the tax with
user fees to be paid by airlines. Several big airlines favor user
fees, but low-fare carriers say it would force them to raise
prices.
</TEXT>
