<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A5679 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-CRASH-CONSUME-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-14</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0498 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-CONSUME-COX
NERVOUS FLYERS HAS MANY PLACES TO FIND OUT INFORMATION ON AIRLINE
FLIGHTS, PLANES
EDs: With CRASH-CONTACTBOX; CRASH-MAIN.
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MITCH McKENNEY</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WEST PALM BEACH</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  ``I'm traveling <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">next week</TIMEX> on a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Delta</ENAMEX>
flight with an extemely fearful flier,'' begins the note posted
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> in a computer forum on aviation safety.
<p>
   ``The ticket agent told me it was an MD-88 and I was hoping
someone here could provide us with a little info about exactly what
kind of aircraft that is and what its track record has been.''
<p>
   Relax, about two dozen people have since told the writer: the
planes have an outstanding safety record.
<p>
   ``Tell your friend to expect <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Delta</ENAMEX> to provide her with a safe
and on-time journey,'' one wrote.
<p>
   Places like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CompuServe</ENAMEX>'s Aviation Safety Interest Group, a
longtime gathering point for pilots and aviation buffs  &MD;  and
several sites on the Internet  &MD;  can arm you with a lot of
information about airplane models, crash records and other data.
<p>
   But can you find out if the plane you're catching <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">tomorrow</TIMEX> has
had a lot of maintenance problems? Or whether it's one of the
models for which the government, eager to prevent smoky fires, has
started requiring new cockpit wiring?
<p>
   A phone call to the airline can get you the model scheduled for
your flight and perhaps the age of the plane, but not much else.
<p>
   Even if you can extract the plane's tail number from a customer
service agent, searching aviation databases ``is not for someone
who doesn't have a lot of patience,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mike Overly</ENAMEX> (CQ) ,
research director for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aviation Safety Institute</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Columbus</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ohio</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   And once you had the records and are reassured your plane's in
fine shape, you could find the airline had to make a substitution.
<p>
   A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAir</ENAMEX> spokesman said a daily flight from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">West Palm Beach</ENAMEX> to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charlotte</ENAMEX>, for example, could get any of the airline's 34 757s,
depending on weather delays, scheduled maintenance and other
factors.
<p>
   ``The airline usually will fly the same type of plane,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steve Loucks</ENAMEX>, spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Society of Travel Agents</ENAMEX>.
``But there's no real way to pinpoint which piece of aircraft
you'll be traveling on.''
<p>
   If you're seeking information on the model, as the woman curious
about the MD-88 was, several sites on the World Wide Web can help.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> is a good starting point,
with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s weekly summary of airport and airline incidents,
known as service difficulty reports, and equipment notices called
airworthiness directives.
<p>
   And Internet news groups and aviation forums such as
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CompuServe</ENAMEX>'s can offer useful advice, such as thinking of
turbulence ``like the wake from a boat'' and comparing changes in
engine pitch with the sounds a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Greyhound</ENAMEX> bus moter makes while
climbing and descending hills.
<p>
   (Story Filed By <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Palm Beach Post</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">West Palm Beach</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>)
</TEXT>
