<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A5688 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-14</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-NYT
INVESTIGATORS BEGIN EXAMINING DATA FROM <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>'S `BLACK BOX'
(With <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-SAFETY, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-SEARCH)
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW L. WALD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MIAMI</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Crash investigators on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> began analyzing technical
information from the single ``black box'' recovered so far from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> DC-9 that crashed near here on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> and began
reassembling parts of the plane in a hangar at a small airport
nearby.
<p>
   Investigators are still searching for the second black box. In
addition, they are trying to figure out how to pull the wreckage
from the main crater the plane made in the mud under the shallow
water of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX>. They met here on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> to work on that
problem with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army Corps of Engineers</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Navy</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX>
officials and private engineering companies. The crater is about
130 feet long and 40 to 50 feet wide; no one knows its depth.
<p>
   In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> the secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">transportation</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Federico Pena</ENAMEX>,
reported to President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> on steps the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX> would take ``to insure that the nation's civil
aviation system remains the safest in the world.''
<p>
   He said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> would accelerate an existing plan to hire more
inspectors and would work harder to track the status of problems
its inspectors uncover. For years the agency has been criticized by
auditors from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX> for what
they call sloppy record keeping that makes it harder to spot
dangerous trends and for the agency's inspection procedures.
<p>
   But whether the steps <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pena</ENAMEX> discussed would have prevented the
crash is unclear because no one yet knows why the cockpit and cabin
filled with smoke and the plane crashed, killing all 109 people
aboard.
<p>
   At the crash scene, about 12 miles west of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>
metropolitan area, the searchers have been working
shoulder-to-shoulder in a carefully organized grid. Dressed in
special protective suits and slogging through several feet of water
and subsurface muck, they have been able to work only 20 to 30
minutes at a time in the 90-degree weather before coming out to
rest, cool off and be decontaminated from the jet fuel and possible
pathogens in the human remains in the water.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, the vice chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation
Safety Board</ENAMEX>, said at a <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">mid-day</TIMEX> briefing that most of the plane
parts found had originally been in the tail of the jet, but, like
the human remains, had been discovered south of the main crater,
farther along the route of flight. The tail is where both of the
black boxes were situated.
<p>
   The box that has been found was the flight-data recorder, which
collects information on altitude, heading, speed, horizontal and
vertical acceleration and engine function. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said that the
box was dented but that its magnetic tapes had recorded ``good
data.''
<p>
   But the box will not provide information on many individual
parts of the plane, and reading its information will be a little
like watching an opera in a foreign language, providing only a
gross approximation of what happened.
<p>
   On the other hand, the other box, the cockpit voice recorder,
could contain ``a magic bullet,'' a statement by the captain or
first officer that would make clear what happened, said one safety
board official. People at the safety board said they could not
remember a case in which one box had been recovered but the other
had not.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> also spoke about the reassembly of the plane in a hangar
nearby. In crash investigations, engineers often lay out on the
floor of a hangar the mechanical pieces of the plane they recover.
This helps them keep track of what has been found, what is missing
and how the plane has been damaged. In this inquiry, not enough
parts have yet been found to draw conclusions, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Of the aircraft parts found so far, none shows obvious signs of
fire or smoke, searchers said. The co-pilot of the plane reported
smoke in the cockpit and cabin shortly before the crash.
<p>
   Searchers have not found the air-conditioning packs, which are
devices powered by the jet engines that pressurize air for the
cabin and are one possible source of smoke. But there are many
other potential sources of smoke, experts say, including electrical
wiring. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said some wiring had been found and would be
closely scrutinized.
<p>
   Wiring in old planes like this one, built in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1969</TIMEX>, has long been
a concern, and in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> said on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that a new
rule would take effect on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> to require that DC-9's and
other planes made by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas Corp.</ENAMEX> be inspected for
chafed wiring in the cockpit. On some planes, but not DC-9's, that
condition has caused smoke.
<p>
   As salvage operations proceed, investigators will also be
looking for circuit breakers for the fuel pumps. A malfunction in
these circuit breakers caused a lengthy delay in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>, before
the plane took off for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> in its last successful flight. There
is no immediate indication that this problem had any relationship
to the crash when it took off for the return trip to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> continued to defer questions on the crash to
the safety board, an independent agency that takes charge of plane
accident investigations. The crash is a blow for the aviation
administration, which <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early this year</TIMEX> identified <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> as
requiring additional attention and blitzed the young airline with
hundreds of inspections in a one-week period in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
officials say they found no violations significant enough to
require enforcement action, but they did make numerous suggestions,
to which, they said, the airline voluntarily responded.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Schiavo</ENAMEX>, the inspector general of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of
Transportation</ENAMEX>, which is the parent agency of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>
that she would look into whether the investigators had been too
easy on the airline.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
