<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A6242 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-15</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> AIRLINE REGULATOR ANNOUNCES `INTENSIVE' REVIEW OF <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Vinson</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 15</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX> said it is launching an ``intensive 30-day review''
of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Airlines</ENAMEX> operations following the crash of the discount
airline's Flight 592 <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX>, which killed 109
people.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Hinson</ENAMEX>, who announced the review at a
news conference <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">this morning</TIMEX>, said the agency still considers
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> ``safe to fly.''
<p>
   ``The additional inspections we are doing are additional safety
margins and should be viewed as such.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tony Broderick</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>'s associate administrator for regulation
and certification, said the review would involve ``five specific
steps'' in which the agency would:
<p>
   -- Review all reports of mechanical problems filed within the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past 12 months</TIMEX> to insure they have been corrected.
<p>
   -- Inspect all aircraft the morning after they have undergone
overnight repairs.
<p>
   -- Put <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> inspectors on every <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> plane for weekly
in-flight inspections. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> has ``at least 350 flights weekly
and we'd like them on as many as possible,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Broderick</ENAMEX> said of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> inspectors.
<p>
   -- Reinspect all of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s maintenance stations at operations
centers away from the airline's main repair facilities.
<p>
   -- Conduct ``top to bottom inspections'' of every <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> plane
that has undergone heavy maintenance.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592 crashed as the pilot and first officer were
attempting an emergency landing of the 27-year-old, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell
Douglas</ENAMEX>-built DC-9 jetliner back to Mi
<p>
   QIreporting smoke in the cockpit and passenger cabin.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last night</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>, which is
directing the accident investigation, said an explosion could have
torn through the jetliner, triggering a sudden loss of speed and
altitude.
<p>
   A flight recorder recovered by police divers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> indicated
the DC-9 had a flight ``anomaly'' 3 1/2 minutes before the crash,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> vice chairman, said in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Additionally, two parts of the plane were discovered, marked
with ``apparent soot,'' and that suggested ``there could have been
an explosion,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   While no cause has been pinpointed, accident investigators were
studying the possibility that the blast may have been related to
50-60 surplus aircraft oxygen generators shipped in the aircraft's
cargo hold.
<p>
   The generators, which had exceeded their shelf life, were being
shipped to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s headquarters in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   It wasn't immediately clear <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last night</TIMEX> whether shipping the
generators was contrary to government regulations.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX> declined to answer a question on that point, although he
did say that ``some hazardous material is allowed on airplanes
under proper circumstances.''
<p>
   In trading <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> shares were at 14 5/8, down 3/8.
Shares had fallen as much as <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">27 percent</NUMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, the first
trading session after the crash, to 11 3/4.
<p>
   Following the crash, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> expanded a 120-day investigation of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s flight operations, training and maintenance procedures.
The inquiry was prompted by several mishaps, including a fire <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
year</TIMEX> that destroyed a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> DC-9 on a runway in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX> and
injured several people.
<p>
   The airline has one of the oldest jet fleets in the sky, and has
drawn criticism from the inspector general of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation
Department</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Schiavo</ENAMEX>. However, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lewis Jordan</ENAMEX>
has defended the airline's safety standards, saying: ``We cannot
put too much emphasis on safety --ever.''
</TEXT>
