<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A8506 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-16</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-AIRCRASH-ART-NYT
CLERK'S MISTAKE MAY HAVE PUT VOLATILE CHEMICALS ON <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX> PLANE
(ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX>
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.)
(HLW)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW L. WALD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MIAMI</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> Flight 592, which crashed here on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>
apparently after an explosion and fire on board, may have been
carrying highly reactive chemicals because an inexperienced
shipping clerk did not recognize them as hazardous materials,
according to people involved in the investigation.
<p>
   The chemicals were in canisters called oxygen generators, which
are used to supply emergency masks with oxygen. A maintenance
contractor had removed the canisters from another <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> plane at
the airline's request and delivered them back to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>. An
employee of the contractor packed the canisters in boxes and
labeled the boxes ``empty,'' a notation that ordinarily would refer
to the canisters, not the boxes.
<p>
   Investigators now believe that the canisters may have been full
and consider them a leading suspect in the crash. Even if the
canisters were empty, they still might have required more secure
packaging, according to aviation experts.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kenneth P. Quinn</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the maintenance contractor,
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX>, said: ``It is unclear whether the employee knew that the
substance in the canisters constituted a hazardous material, and if
so, whether the material had been discharged.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Quinn</ENAMEX> said that the cannisters, 50 to 60 in all, in five
cardboard boxes, ``were returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> for appropriate
disposal.'' He said a shipping tag on the boxes had two notations:
``empty'' and ``customer furnished material returned per customer
instructions.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Quinn</ENAMEX> said his company was now investigating
whether the canisters were still full.
<p>
   It is standard practice in the industry for such canisters, when
carried as cargo, to be emptied and packed in strong, airtight
boxes.
<p>
   The chief accident investigator, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gregory Feith</ENAMEX>, said at a
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">mid-day</TIMEX> briefing near the scene of the accident: ``We don't know
what experience the people that were handling these canisters
had.'' He added: ``If you pick up a one pound canister and somebody
says they're off an airplane, they're old, that may have been
interpreted by some to mean something else.''
<p>
   He said: ``There's a terminology problem here that we need to
clarify.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> added: ``We're going to try to identify who actually
handled it, what they saw, what they used to make the evaluation as
to whether they are actually full or not full.''
<p>
   The canisters are not used on DC-9s, the kind of the plane that
crashed. They are used on MD-80s, which <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> also flies, to make
oxygen for passenger emergency masks. They make oxygen with a
chemical reaction that generates tremendous heat but is safe when
the canisters are installed in a seatback or overhead compartment.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> has found strong
evidence of fire and explosion on the plane, and has found
paperwork on the ground indicating that the oxygen generators were
on board. It has not suggested a mechanism by which a generator or
generators became activated, though, and it is still looking at
wiring and other possible sources of explosion or fire.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX> said in a statement on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>: ``We agree with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lewis
Jordan</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>, that it is premature and
irresponsible to engage in speculation over the probable cause of
this tragic accident. We are cooperating fully with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX>.''
<p>
   Thus far, none of the generators has been recovered. The safety
board hopes to find some in the muck of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX> where the
plane crashed and check their serial numbers against maintenance
records to determine definitively if they were still potent when
shipped.
<p>
   Also on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> contradicted the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX> and said that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> could legally have carried the
generators even though it has chosen not to carry hazardous
materials for others and has not developed the procedures and
trained the personnel as required by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> for such work.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, senior officials of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, who refused to be
publicly named, said that if the airline was not authorized to
handle hazardous materials, then it could not carry the oxygen
generators even if they were what the industry calls ``company
materials.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> said: ``There are provisions that allow <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> to ship
hazardous material that is necessary for company business.'' He
said: ``This discussion needs to be expanded to find out if in fact
this was being done for company business, and then what regulations
and requirements does <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> have to follow when shipping
hazardous materials for their own benefit.''
<p>
   Investigators have recovered the flight data recorder, one of
the plane's ``black boxes,'' and found signs on it consistent with
an explosion on board. They have also found soot-covered wreckage.
In addition, before the plane crashed, the co-pilot reported to the
ground that the cockpit and cabin were filling with smoke. A
possible source of that smoke, according to investigators, was
three aircraft tires from an MD-80, carried with the generators in
the forward cargo compartment.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, searchers used a heavy-duty helicopter to lift
major pieces of the wreckage out of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX>, including two
tires, two major landing gear pieces, some pieces of wing and
fuselage, and ``a piece that looks like it's from the rear cargo
bay,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, vice chairman of the safety board.
Investigators are not sure whether the tires were cargo or in use
on the plane. Searchers have also recovered both engines, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX>
said.
<p>
   Illustrating the difficulty of recovery, he said that the
helicopter pulled at one engine with a force of 4,000 pounds before
freeing it from the muck; once airborne, it weighed less than
3,000, he said.
<p>
   For the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last two days</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> has been wearing a small green
ribbon marked ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> Flight 592, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11, 1996</TIMEX>.'' The ribbons
were given to dozens of relatives of the victims who have arrived
here to await recovery of body parts.
<p>
   Searchers have not found the cockpit voice recorder, which
investigators badly want.
<p>
   Support organizations, including the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Salvation Army</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fire
Department</ENAMEX>, plan now to be at the scene <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">at least three to four more
weeks</TIMEX>; the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Salvation Army</ENAMEX> said it was serving about 1,800 meals a
day.
</TEXT>
