<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1225 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-19</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0805 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CRASH-ART-NYT
(<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ga.</ENAMEX> ATTN)
MORE EVIDENCE POINTS TO OXYGEN DEVICES
(With <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-SAFETY)
(ART ADV: Graphic on airline accident rates has been sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX>
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW L. WALD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Federal crash investigators said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> that they
had found a partly burned aircraft tire that was carried as cargo
by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> DC-9 that crashed near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX>, a likely
source of the smoke that the co-pilot urgently reported just before
the crash. Embedded in the tire, the investigators said, were parts
from at least one oxygen generator, a device that can generate
tremendous heat.
<p>
   The discovery adds substantial weight to a leading theory in the
crash, that one or more generators, which were being carried as
cargo on the flight, somehow activated and ignited the tire.
<p>
   But the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>, following its
standard practice, will take months before it formally establishes
what caused the crash, which killed all 110 people aboard when it
slammed into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX> a few minutes after takeoff from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami
International Airport</ENAMEX>, bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The investigator in charge, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gregory Feith</ENAMEX>, said at a briefing
near the crash site that the safety board's staff had determined
through interviews of ground personnel that there were 119 of the
generators on board, double what had previously been suspected, and
that some were stacked on top of one of three tires in the forward
cargo hold.
<p>
   He said the generators, which are each a little bigger than a
coffee thermos, were in cardboard boxes. When carried as cargo they
are supposed to be in air-tight containers, and standard airline
practice is to transport them only after they have been activated
and allowed to run through their chemical reaction, thus
eliminating the possibility that they will produce heat, which can
start fires, and oxygen, which feeds fires, while in a cargo hold.
<p>
   But there is strong suspicion that at least some of the
generators were still potent. They had been removed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three months
earlier</TIMEX> from three other <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> aircraft, MD-80s being refurbished
for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>, and were being returned to the airline by a
maintenance contractor.
<p>
   On MD-80s the generators are used to provide oxygen to passenger
emergency masks, but because the chemicals they use can
deteriorate, each is given an expiration date, and these had
expired.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> personnel put them aboard the
DC-9 for shipment to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>, where the airline has its
headquarters. The distinction may be important because <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sabertech</ENAMEX>,
the maintenance contractor, contends that whether or not the
generators were hazardous cargo, the airline is responsible for
figuring out what it is loading on its planes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> officials assert that before the airline put the boxes
aboard the flight, 592, its personnel saw that the labels on the
boxes described the generators as empty.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sabertech</ENAMEX> have already begun pointing fingers at
each other, and may eventually do so in court. While the safety
board does not fix blame for accidents, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> has repeatedly used a
legal term in describing one of the chief areas of inquiry: what
the board wants to know about the oxygen generators, he said, is
the ``chain of custody.''
<p>
   The investigators have a lot of other work to do. Many
soot-covered parts have been discovered, and laboratory technicians
will examine the soot to see if it is from rubber or from
electrical wiring, which is another suspect in the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> said that the oxygen generators and the tires were ``a
main focus'' of the investigation, but that it was still too soon
to draw conclusions. ``We have <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">90 percent</NUMEX> of an airplane that is
unaccountable,'' he said, noting that most of it is still under
water or buried in mud.
<p>
   Most of the plane's parts have been found by police officers
wading through the area or by pairs of searchers who lash two
airboats together, about three feet apart, and reach down between
them with their hands, pulling up whatever they find.
<p>
   Investigators have begun using special radar that can see
through the mud, and hope to find the cockpit voice recorder.
<p>
   To look at the main crater dug by the plane when it crashed,
they recently received special diving suits that are designed for
use with hazardous materials. But then they found that the airboats
from which they have been working are too small to carry all the
required diving equipment. The investigators hope to begin the
dives on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Feith</ENAMEX> said that investigators had finished reviewing the
maintenance records of the plane and that ``the paperwork was in
order from what they could see.''
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-19-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1908EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
