<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CORRECT-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-21</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0930 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-CORRECT-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX> SHARES RISE AS <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SABRETECH</ENAMEX> ADMITS MISLABELING (CORRECT)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Adam Levy</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Carrick Mollenkamp</ENAMEX> 
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Corrects to say that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX> is an aircraft maintenance
company, not a shipping company.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 21</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Inc.</ENAMEX> shares ended a
five-day slide after an aircraft maintenance company said it
mislabeled as empty a box of oxygen generators that may have caused
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX>'s plane crash that killed 110.
<p>
   Shares in the no-frills airline rose 1 7/8, or <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">17 percent</NUMEX>, to 13
1/8 in trading of 6.8 million shares, making it the fifth
most-active <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> stock.
<p>
   Despite the rebound, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> shares are still down <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">27 percent</NUMEX>
from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 10</TIMEX>, the day before Flight 592 crashed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida
Everglades</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The maintenance company's admission won't completely repair
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s reputation with travelers, investors and analysts said.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s got to convince the public that its 27-year-old
planes are OK to fly,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Cabell</ENAMEX>, co-manager of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAA
Aggressive Growth Fund</ENAMEX>, which owns 150,000 shares of the airline's
stock. ``There's still a nagging credibility problem.''
<p>
   Attorneys also said the admission by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX>, the
aircraft maintenance firm, doesn't eliminate <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s legal
liability in the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> bonds traded as high as <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">85 cents</NUMEX> on the dollar <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>,
little changed from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>'s close of 85.25.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> also acknowledged <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> that co-founder <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Timothy Flynn</ENAMEX>
sold <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">25 percent</NUMEX> of his stake in the airline <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine days after the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash</TIMEX> to satisfy a margin call.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX>, a unit of closely held <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sabreliner Corp.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">St. Louis</ENAMEX>,
said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX> that five boxes containing 119 oxygen generators
were delivered to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> without federally required
labels identifying them as hazardous.
<p>
   Investigators found evidence that an explosion of one or more of
the canisters in the plane's cargo hold may have triggered the
crash.
<p>
   Showing that the canisters were mislabeled isn't enough to
convince consumers that the airline is safe, analysts said.
<p>
   ``That's just one issue out of many that has been raised about
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> since the crash,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vivian Lee</ENAMEX>, an analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">BT
Securities</ENAMEX>. ``Until there are more definitive answers, it's too
soon to guess about the company's future.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> has spent most of the year under intense regulatory
scrutiny after the airline had five minor accidents, including a
fire in one plane. Its planes had 11 serious mechanical problems
that disrupted flights in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last two years</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Also, it has been widely reported since the crash that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>
has the oldest fleet of any <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> airline. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Avitas Inc.</ENAMEX>, a consulting
firm, says <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s planes average 26.4 years old. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kiwi
International Airlines</ENAMEX> has the second-oldest fleet with jets
averaging 22.8 years.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> DC-9 that crashed was 27 years old.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s liability in connection with the crash is likely to be
diminished, but not eliminated by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX>'s admission, attorneys
said.
<p>
   ``This won't get <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> off the hook, but it may give them a
co-defendant,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lee Kreindler</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kreindler &AMP; Kreindler</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX>, whose firm represents plaintiffs in airline crash cases.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> was obligated to open the crate of oxygen canisters and
inspect at least some to determine whether they were empty, said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Wimsatt</ENAMEX>, a partner at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Magana, Cathcart &AMP;
McCarthy</ENAMEX>, a law firm specializing in aviation law.
<p>
   ``It certainly could be expected that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> wouldn't rely on
what someone told them about a potentially hazardous product that
would be put on their airplane,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wimsatt</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> has <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$750 million</NUMEX> liability insurance to cover the crash.
<p>
   Oxygen generators, if full, are considered hazardous materials
and aren't supposed to be shipped aboard commercial flights, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> has said.
<p>
   ``We acknowledge that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX> delivered to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> boxes
containing the canisters with a shipping ticket marked as
`empty','' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dave Reddick</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for the maintenance company's
parent. ``We're certainly concerned about this.''
<p>
   Still, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX> said it doesn't accept responsibility for the
crash.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> made an independent decision to ship their company
materials on board an aircraft, and apparently did not ensure that
they were properly labeled, packaged and stored,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kenneth P.
Quinn</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreTech</ENAMEX> spokesman.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Standard &AMP; Poor's</ENAMEX> said it's considering lowering the rating of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">SabreLiner</ENAMEX>'s bonds.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> co-founder <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Timothy Flynn</ENAMEX> sold <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">25 percent</NUMEX> of his stake in
the airline <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">nine days after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX>, one of four founders of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-based airline and a
board member, sold 1.5 million shares <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>, raising <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$16.9
million</NUMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX> still owns 4.5 million shares.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX> sold the shares to satisfy a margin call, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gregg
Kenyon</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> spokesman. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kenyon</ENAMEX> declined to say how much margin
debt was owed.
<p>
   A margin call is a broker's demand for additional cash or
securities so that an investor can continue to borrow from the
broker to buy securities.
<p>
   The shares <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX> sold -- worth <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$52 million</NUMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">November</TIMEX> --would
have been worth <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$19.5 million</NUMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, with the stock's rebound.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>'s stock isn't likely rebound to the upper teens, where
it traded before the crash, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steve Lewins</ENAMEX> an analyst at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Gruntal &AMP;
Co.</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``Probably because of all the publicity, it will take them a
year to grow out of this,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lewins</ENAMEX> said.
</TEXT>
