<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960521.0650 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A3939 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-AIRLINE-SHIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-21</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-AIRLINE-SHIFT-NYT
SMALL, LOW-FARE AIRLINES SHAKEN BY <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX> CRASH
(See also VALUJET-CRASH)
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ADAM BRYANT</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark McDonald</ENAMEX> has weathered almost every storm imaginable since
he started <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>. The small airline, which has
served <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philadelphia</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pittsburgh</ENAMEX>, was shut down <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for a
week</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last July</TIMEX> by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> for a
paperwork violation. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">A few months earlier</TIMEX>, a bank pulled its
commitment at the last minute to lend him <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1 million</NUMEX>. A company
that leased him a plane took it back in the middle of the night
because of a mix-up.
<p>
   But his airline could not withstand the impact of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet
Airlines</ENAMEX> crash <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">11 days ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX> is halting scheduled service and laying off a third
of its staff to go into the charter business, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McDonald</ENAMEX> said. He was
forced to make the decision after he saw reservations drop, and
drop some more, after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash because of travelers'
concerns about fledgling airlines like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   When a plane crashes, the airline that operates it usually sees
cancellations and a drop in bookings for anywhere from a week to a
few months. But the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX> has raised concerns
among travelers who have been flying increasingly on smaller and
younger airlines, with names that are less well known than
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Delta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX> may be an extreme example, but some other low-fare,
smaller airlines said that bookings had dropped since the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>
crash, and many more said they were fielding questions from scores
of anxious travelers about the safety of their aircraft.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jet Train</ENAMEX>, an airline that started serving <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Orlando</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Newark</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.J.</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pittsburgh</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">January</TIMEX>, said that although it has had few
cancellations, the number of its daily bookings dropped by <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">30
percent</NUMEX> in the days immediately after the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash. It has
also received hundreds of calls from travelers asking questions
about the age of its fleet.
<p>
   ``Certainly we have been impacted,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Davis</ENAMEX>, the
airline's president. ``But it appears to be returning to near
normal levels.''
<p>
   Other airlines like <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tower Air</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Reno Air</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kiwi Airlines</ENAMEX> said
that they had also received calls from passengers with questions
about their safety records and fleet age, but that they had seen
few cancellations. In fact, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kiwi</ENAMEX>, whose route network overlaps many
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> routes, has seen bookings rise by about <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">5 percent</NUMEX> since the
crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest Airlines</ENAMEX>, another low-fare airline, said it had seen
no drop in bookings, and only sporadic safety-related questions
from its customers. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Southwest</ENAMEX> is also better known than many
start-ups; it is the eighth-largest airline in the country, has
been in business <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">24 years</TIMEX> and has never had a crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McDonald</ENAMEX>, of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX>, said he felt blindsided. The day after
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McDonald</ENAMEX> said his bookings dropped <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">28 percent</NUMEX>.
On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, they dropped another <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">6 percent</NUMEX>. As the week wore on,
they remained at <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">40 percent</NUMEX> below earlier levels.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nations Air</ENAMEX>, which has never had an incident or accident, was
suddenly losing <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$100,000</NUMEX> a week with no certainty of when business
would bounce back. The airline had been hovering around break even.
It laid off 46 employees on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``We are not large enough to stand by and burn off that type of
money,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">McDonald</ENAMEX>, who decided to start flying charter service
because it is a more reliable source of income, though it has less
potential for profits and rapid growth.
<p>
   ``There's been an erosion of consumer confidence in the industry
and you don't know how long it's going to last,'' he said.
<p>
   Until the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash, the public confidence in such airlines
appeared to have been high. Airlines were being started at a rate
not seen since immediately after the industry was deregulated in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1978</TIMEX>. Since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX>, about 50 applications have been filed to start
new airlines, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX> said. It is a trend the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX> has applauded, stating recently that such
low-cost airlines saved consumers <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$6.3 billion</NUMEX> a year. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> has
said that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> crash was the first for a jet airline that
started after deregulation.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> has set the pace for the growth of such airlines,
expanding to 320 flights since it started in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October 1993</TIMEX>. It said
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last Friday</TIMEX> that it would cut its schedule in half.
<p>
   Officials of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX>, which has been highly profitable, are
expected to talk on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> with Wall Street analysts who follow
the airline industry about the effects of the crash on its
finances.
<p>
   The airline, an unusually strong performer in an industry where
profits have long been thin or nonexistent, has been as popular
with investors as it was with travelers, with its stock rising
quickly in anticipation of profitable growth.
<p>
   When the stock market opened on the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> after the crash,
shares in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> that had been trading at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$17.875</NUMEX> immediately lost
a third of their value. They have since rebounded somewhat, closing
on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$13.125</NUMEX>, up <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$1.875</NUMEX> from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>'s close.
<p>
   However, one investor who recently sold shares in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> was
also a founder of the airline. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Timothy Flynn</ENAMEX>, one of four founders,
sold 1.5 million hares on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>. But the airline said that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX>
sold the stock to pay off money that he borrowed for investment
purposes. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet</ENAMEX> said that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Flynn</ENAMEX> still owned 4.5 million shares of
the airline.
</TEXT>
