<DOCID> nyt960529.0708 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A3096 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=kan-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-CRITIC-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-29</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-CRITIC-KAN
INSPECTOR MAKES WAVES WITH IDEAS ON AIRLINE SAFETY
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DAVID GOLDSTEIN</ENAMEX>
c. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kansas City Star</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  She's been an organized-crime prosecutor in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas
City</ENAMEX>, and she's worked in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION"><ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reagan</ENAMEX> White House</ENAMEX>. She's had a top
post in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Labor Department</ENAMEX> and been featured as one of ``10
outstanding young working women'' in Glamour magazine.
<p>
   She can even fly a plane and throw her voice.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Fackler Schiavo</ENAMEX> has skipped from one high-profile job to
another like a stone dancing across a pond.
<p>
   Except now she has made a ripple, and a big one at that.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592 crashed into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX> on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX>, the issue of Newsweek on the stands <TIMEX TYPE="DATE" MIN="Saturday">that Saturday</TIMEX> carried a
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> column about airline safety.
<p>
   ``I go out of my way to stay off commuter planes,'' she wrote.
``... I would not fly on marginal airlines (and because of its many
mishaps, I also avoided flying <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>.)''
<p>
   But this was more than just a personal essay from a trained
pilot and frequent flier.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX>, known as <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Sterling</ENAMEX> when she lived in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX>,
is the inspector general for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Transportation</ENAMEX>. In
her words, she is ``helping to police the country's skies.''
<p>
   More succinctly, she's been one of the most outspoken
bureaucrats about aircraft safety, inspections and the problem of
faulty parts installed in planes.
<p>
   Her role as the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cassandra</ENAMEX> of the airways has put her on opposite
sides of others in federal airline regulation. But if <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> was a
flash point for criticism before her column and the crash, she's
now at the center of the controversy.
<p>
   Her superiors at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX>, where the party
line is always that the government has complete confidence in the
airline industry, blanched at her comments.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Hinson</ENAMEX>, head of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>, said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> was ``entitled to her opinion.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation</ENAMEX> Secretary
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Federico Pena</ENAMEX> has assured the public that <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> is safe.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX>'s critics in the industry say that, while she is smart
and aggressive, she is a media hound who has unnecessarily
frightened the traveling public.
<p>
   ``I think the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> needs to increase and enhance its training and
pay attention to things like unapproved parts and other issues she
has brought to the forefront,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sarah MacLeod</ENAMEX>, a lawyer and
executive director of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aeronautical Repair Station Association</ENAMEX>,
which represents companies that repair airline parts. ``I agree
with her on a lot of her points. I don't agree with how she is
going about her job and overstepping her boundaries, and I don't
agree with her grabbing headlines.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> could not be reached for comment. She has kept quiet
since the days immediately following the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crash, when she
was on national television saying that the low-budget carrier's
record was under review.
<p>
   The 40-year-old prosecutor-turned-political appointee became the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation Department</ENAMEX>'s inspector general in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1990</TIMEX> after a swift
rise in government and political circles.
<p>
   She grew up on a farm and attended school in a small town
outside of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Toledo</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ohio</ENAMEX>, where she was twirling champion. She also
taught herself ventriloquism as a hobby, was flying by the age of
10 and became a certified pilot at 18. She earned degrees from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ohio
State</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Harvard</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York University</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> joined the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> attorney's office in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1982</TIMEX>
at age 27. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Missouri Court of Appeals</ENAMEX> Judge <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert G. Ulrich</ENAMEX>, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> attorney at the time, remembers that her letter of application
and resume stood out among the nearly 400 he received during his
eight years as prosecutor.
<p>
   ``It was impressive,'' he said. ``... I suspect the way <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary</ENAMEX>
approaches things, she recognizes and determines a goal; then she
goes and gets it.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> worked for <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ulrich</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for three years</TIMEX> and then joined the
federal <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Organized Crime Strike Force</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for a year</TIMEX>. At time she was
married to lawyer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ed Sterling</ENAMEX>, the chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jackson County
Republican Party</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   She left <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX> to become a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">White House</ENAMEX> fellow and a
special assistant to then-Attorney General <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edwin Meese</ENAMEX>. She
returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Missouri</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1988</TIMEX> to run President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bush</ENAMEX>'s presidential
campaign in the state.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> aggressively sought <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ulrich</ENAMEX>'s post when he left, but she
didn't make the final cut of three candidates. The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> attorney
job eventually went to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jean Paul Bradshaw II</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   She worked for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDowell, Rice &AMP; Smith</ENAMEX> law firm for a while
but returned to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> to work for then-Secretary of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Labor</ENAMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Elizabeth Dole</ENAMEX> as an assistant secretary for labor-management
standards.
<p>
   As inspector general at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation</ENAMEX>, she has been credited by
many for pushing the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> to get tough on the problems of faulty
parts and for beefing up the criminal dimension of her office.
<p>
   Aviation Week &AMP; Space Technology magazine praised her <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>
for winning more than 100 convictions in her investigations. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last
week</TIMEX> the journal complimented her work on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> but also fired a
dart.
<p>
   ``She should stick to what she does best,'' the magazine
editorialized, ``finding problems, not creating them.''
<p>
   She also took criticism after she butted heads with a top <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
official, accusing him of blocking one of her investigations. He
was cleared by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice Department</ENAMEX>, but the episode painted her
in some quarters as someone who acted outside proper channels and
was magnetized by the glare of publicity.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> has shown no indications that it plans
to take any action against <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX>, who was appointed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bush</ENAMEX>
administration. Among some on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION|LOCATION">Capitol Hill</ENAMEX>, however, the mood is
that of a hunter who suddenly finds prey in his sights.
<p>
   Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ted Stevens</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alaska</ENAMEX>, the Republican chairman of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate Governmental Affairs Committee</ENAMEX>, which has oversight over the
inspector generals, was furious at her comments about the safety of
commuter planes.
<p>
   ``That's easily <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">90 percent</NUMEX> of the traffic in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alaska</ENAMEX>,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mitch Rose</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stevens</ENAMEX> aide. ``(<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stevens</ENAMEX>) has never been approached
by her or been given that impression. He thought her statements
were over-broad.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stevens</ENAMEX>' committee plans to review two years' worth of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX>'s
audits and investigative reports to see whether they bear out her
Newsweek comments.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MacLeod</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> and everyone involved in the debate over
airline safety needed a dose of reality.
<p>
   ``We have the safest airline system in the world,'' she said,
``but life comes with no guarantees.''
</TEXT>
