<STORYID cat=w pri=u> A4546 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-30</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FLA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-NYT
DC-9 COCKPIT TAPE CONTAINS NOISE SUPPORTING BLAST THEORY
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW L. WALD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The cockpit voice recorder of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Valujet Airlines</ENAMEX>
DC-9 that crashed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Everglades</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX> recorded ``a brief
unidentified sound'' less than six minutes after takeoff, and
almost immediately, the captain ``stated the need to go back to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> investigators said on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The investigators' brief statement does not say what the sound
was, and, in fact, refers to it four times on a single page as
``unidentified.'' But a chronology in the statement seems to show
that the crew acted properly in response to the noise.
<p>
   The crash killed all 110 people on board, and investigators
found parts of oxygen generators embedded in a fire-damaged tire.
Aviation experts said on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX> that a possible source of
the sound would be the pop of a spare aircraft tire if it had been
heated by a fire in the forward cargo hold. The board has already
said that the plane was carrying oxygen generators, which can start
fires, and that some of these had been stacked on top of an
inflated tire.
<p>
   The flight data recorder, which has already been analyzed, gives
evidence that there might have been an explosion on board. The
statement released on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, describing a preliminary analysis
of the voice recorder, did not state unequivocally that the sound
was related to the crash but gives a partial chronology keyed
around that event: The sound occurred about 5 minutes and 47
seconds after takeoff; the captain ``questioned'' the sound; 17
seconds after hearing it, she said the plane, which was still
climbing on its way to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Atlanta</TIMEX>, must return to <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Miami</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Five seconds later, ``voices were heard from the passenger cabin
reporting fire.'' Eleven seconds after that, the co-pilot radioed
for clearance to return. The crash occurred about seven minutes
later.
<p>
   The sequence, as described by the investigators, indicates that
the crew took prompt action to try to land, which aviation experts
say is the most important step pilots can take in the event of a
fire. An unresolved question is whether the plane could have landed
closer than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Miami</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The statement also said ``the aircraft and systems appear normal
before the unidentified sound.'' Afterwards, the statement said,
there were two apparent interruptions of power to the cockpit voice
recorder. The first began 1 minute and 39 seconds after the sound
and lasted 1 minute and 17 seconds; the second was just before the
end of the tape.
<p>
   Aviation experts say the reason could be fire damage to the
plane's electrical system, or could be the crew, believing that the
problem was an electrical fire, turning off various electrical
systems. Electrical problems have not been ruled out.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">05-30-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2007EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960601.0131 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=r> A6505 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tad-z> BC-HAZARD-PULL-COX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-01</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0543 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-HAZARD-PULL-COX
HISTORY BOX TO GO WITH PBP-HAZARD
c. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   Previous incidents involving the carrying of hazardous air
cargo:
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">NOV. 3, 1973</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   Heavy smoke and fumes cause a crash that kills three crewmen and
destroys a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 707. An improperly packaged container of
nitric acid burst into flames in the cargo compartment. The Clipper
160 cargo plane bound from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX> to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Frankfurt</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, crashed during an emergency landing at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan Airport</ENAMEX>. After the crash, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Line Pilots Association</ENAMEX>
formally recommended to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Safety Board</ENAMEX> that ``all hazardous
materials be banned from interstate air transportation.''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">AUG. 19, 1980</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   A cargo compartment fire spreads through a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Saudi Arabian
Airlines</ENAMEX> L-1011, killing all 301 people aboard. The pilot was able
to successfully land the jet in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Riyadh</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Saudi Arabia</ENAMEX>. But
evacuation attempts failed. Although unable to determine the cause
of the fire, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> used the
incident to push for better methods for containing fires in cargo
holds. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> recommended installation of fiberglass ceiling
liners in lieu of the standard C-2 Nomex fabric liners used in
cargo compartments at the time.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">AUG. 10, 1986</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   Fire consumes an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Trans Air</ENAMEX> DC-10 after passenger and
crew deplane in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>. A jostled oxygen generating canister  &MD; 
similar to the ones carried aboard <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592  &MD;  set off the
fire in the cargo hold.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">FEB. 3, 1988</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   An <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Airlines</ENAMEX> DC-9 makes an emergency landing in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nashville</ENAMEX>, forcing 126 passengers and crew to evacuate after
chemicals illegally shipped from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Austin</ENAMEX> start a fire in the cargo
hold. The floor in the passenger cabin melted and smoke wafted
through the cabin. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> called
for fire detection and extinguishing equipment in Class D cargo
holds. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> rejected the recommendation because it would cost
more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$350 million</NUMEX> to retrofit existing aircraft.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">FEB. 1, 1991</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   Fire breaks out in the cargo hold of a DC-9 bound from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charlotte</ENAMEX>
to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greensboro</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.C.</ENAMEX> No one is injured, but an illegal cache of tear
gas, volatile liquid dichloromethane, lamp oil, witch hazel and
matches are found in the cargo compartment.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">AUG. 20, 1993</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   A leaking package containing blood tainted with the HIV virus
was packed as air freight in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Santa Rosa</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX> Several cargo
loaders handled the unmarked package before someone placed it in a
clear plastic bag. An inspection revealed the package contained
human tissue and blood samples, which laboratory tests revealed
were positive for the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which
causes AIDS.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">APRIL 6, 1994</TIMEX>  &MD; 
<p>
   Mercury seeps out of a mail bag during the loading of a
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> DC-9 Super 80 in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Houston</ENAMEX>. The container lacked
corrosive and hazmat warning labels. The shipper appeared unaware
of proper shipping procedures, claiming he had shipped mercury in
the same manner for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past two decades</TIMEX> without mishap. Compiled
from reports supplied by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>,
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal
Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
