<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A8968 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NY</ENAMEX>-TERROR-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-03</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NY</ENAMEX>-TERROR-TRIAL-NYT
FATAL AIRLINE ATTACK DESCRIBED IN TERROR TRIAL
(bl)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CHRISTOPHER S. WREN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Prosecutors focused <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> on a deadly midair
explosion that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ramzi Yousef</ENAMEX> is accused of carrying out as a
rehearsal for a planned wave of attacks on a dozen American
jetliners, a continuation of a terror campaign that the indictment
says began with the World Trade Center bombing.
<p>
   The bomb exploded aboard <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippines Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 434,
killing one passenger and injuring several others, as the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX>
747 flew from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cebu</ENAMEX> in the southern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philippines</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tokyo</ENAMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Dec. 11,
1994</TIMEX>. The pilot, who testified <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, managed to make an emergency
landing in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Okinawa</ENAMEX> after the blast.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> is accused of planting the bomb himself on the first leg
of the flight from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cebu</ENAMEX> before quietly disembarking. He
and the other two defendants are accused of conspiring to replicate
that tactic in two days of terror they are said to have planned at
airports around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX> to kill several thousand passengers.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX>  &MD;  who has insisted upon conducting his own defense,
against the advice of the judge in the case  &MD;  sought to gain some
advantage from <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>'s testimony, suggesting in his
cross-examination of the witnesses that the bomb had been planted
by someone else, even one of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippine Airlines</ENAMEX>' own maintenance
or cleaning workers.
<p>
   So far, the only witness to place <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> on the flight from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cebu</ENAMEX> has been a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Philippine Airlines</ENAMEX> flight attendant,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Maria De La Cruz</ENAMEX>. She testified <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> that she had seen him
briefly occupy the seat that later exploded. She served him a
beverage and snack before he got off in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cebu</ENAMEX>, she said.
<p>
   When the trial reconvened <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>, the prosecutors,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dietrich L. Snell</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael J. Garcia</ENAMEX>, went on to present three
witnesses: the jetliner's Filipino captain, a Japanese passenger
who was injured in the explosion and a retired Okinawan police
officer who supervised the bombing investigation after the aircraft
landed at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Naha</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Okinawa</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Taking the stand, the aircraft's captain, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eduardo Reyes</ENAMEX>,
testified that the sudden explosion had forced his plane, which had
nearly 300 passengers on board, to bank sharply to the right. ``It
was as if a big rocket exploded right in the room,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reyes</ENAMEX> said.
When he took the controls, he had to use force to make a wide turn.
``The plane responded, but very slowly,'' he said.
<p>
   The captain said he had landed the damaged jumbo jetliner at the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Naha</ENAMEX> airport a half-hour later, after the control tower and another
small plane verified that his landing gear was down.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> cross-examined <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reyes</ENAMEX>, he asked who else, including
mechanics and cleaners, had been given access to the plane's
interior while it was in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Manila</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cebu</ENAMEX>. He also asked why the
flight had departed behind schedule.
<p>
   ``Do you know whether the late arrival of the stairs was
deliberate or not?'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> asked.
<p>
   ``No, sir,'' said the captain, who seemed puzzled by the
questioning. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> asked later whether passengers were required to
show passports before boarding. ``That is not my line, sir,'' the
pilot said. ``My job is to fly the aircraft.''
<p>
   The injured passenger, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yukihiko Ususi</ENAMEX>, said he had been sleeping
in the seat behind the passenger who was killed, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Haruki Ikegami</ENAMEX>.
When the blast occurred, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX> said, he thought that the airliner
had crashed. Speaking through a Japanese interpreter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX> said he
had tried to use the oxygen mask dangling above him, ``but then I
realized the oxygen mask was burned and was useless.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ikegami</ENAMEX> tried to ask for help and then collapsed, said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX>,
who then discovered that his own legs were ``burned and bloody.''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX> said he had looked at <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ikegami</ENAMEX> ``and he looked dead.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX> said he had been hospitalized <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">for 16 days</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Okinawa</ENAMEX>, had
surgery twice and spent four more months in his local hospital in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>. ``My legs occasionally still ache, and also I have a ringing
sensation in my ear,'' he said.
<p>
   In a brief cross-examination of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> asked whether he
was aware of blackmailing and other crimes committed against
Japanese businessmen in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philippines</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December 1994</TIMEX>. ``I
didn't know,'' replied <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ususi</ENAMEX>, looking baffled by the question.
<p>
   The defendant contends that he was being tortured in a Pakistani
prison at the time prosecutors accuse him of being in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philippines</ENAMEX> and plotting to blow up 12 American jetliners with his
co-defendants, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Abdul Hakim Murad</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Wali Khan Amin Shah</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The prosecutors say they can prove that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> was in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philippines</ENAMEX> at that time through <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX>'s computer records and
fingerprints and other evidence.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yousef</ENAMEX> faces a subsequent trial <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">later this year</TIMEX> on charges of
masterminding the bombing of the World Trade Center in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February
1993</TIMEX>, an attack that killed six people and injured hundreds.
</TEXT>
