<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-05</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0989 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NAVY</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JOHNSON</ENAMEX>-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT
LOW-KEY OFFICER IN HIGH-STRESS JOB: ADM. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JAY L. JOHNSON</ENAMEX>
(ART ADV: Photo of Adm. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> has been sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX> photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(kd)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ERIC SCHMITT</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Adm. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jay L. Johnson</ENAMEX>, one of the fastest-rising
stars in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>, faces the most daunting challenge of his 28-year
career in taking command of a service wracked by tragedy and
turmoil.
<p>
   President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>, calling this a ``crucial time'' in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>'s
history, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> tapped <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> to succeed his mentor, Adm.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeremy Boorda</ENAMEX>, who committed suicide <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">three weeks ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Colleagues describe <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>, who became 50 on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, as a
smart, decisive and low-key officer who as the new Chief of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Naval
Operations</ENAMEX> would move quickly to reassure a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> badly shaken by
the death of his popular predecessor. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>, a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1968</TIMEX> graduate of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Naval Academy</ENAMEX>, has been the vice chief of naval operations
since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April 1</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jay</ENAMEX> is a very steady, solid force who gives the impression of
being unflappable,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stanley R. Arthur</ENAMEX>, a retired admiral who
commanded <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> forces in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Persian Gulf</ENAMEX> war. ``He'll present a
soothing image. You won't see a lot of flash and dash from him.''
<p>
   There is little doubt about the admiral's combat credentials. A
fighter pilot with 150 combat missions during the Vietnam War,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> won praise as head of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Second Fleet</ENAMEX> during the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
intervention in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Haiti</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1994</TIMEX>, helping to coordinate the flying of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX> helicopters off a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> aircraft carrier.
<p>
   A larger question is whether <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> can overcome a relative
lack of experience in the crucible of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> politicking and
in-fighting to turn around the military's most troubled service and
win over skeptics in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Although <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Boorda</ENAMEX> did not attend the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX> Tailhook convention, a
gathering of naval aviators in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX> where 83 women were
assaulted, he was dogged by its legacy. Cheating and drugs at the
prestigious <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Naval Academy</ENAMEX> and a series of crashes involving the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>'s fleet of aging F-14 fighter jets combined to create an image
of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> spinning out of control.
<p>
   Now these are <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>'s problems to resolve.
<p>
   ``He's got a very tough job ahead of him,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Barbara Pope</ENAMEX>,
who worked with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> when she was a senior <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> personnel
official in the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bush</ENAMEX> administration.
<p>
   Senior <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> officials expressed hope <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX>,
a tall, striking figure and articulate speaker, would by his sheer
presence and leadership propel the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>, and its 422,000 men and
women, off the shoals of misfortune.
<p>
   But in contrast to the effervescent <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Boorda</ENAMEX>, who openly promoted
his common touch with sailors and his skill as a bureaucratic
infighter, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> is more self-effacing and is not particularly
well known, even within the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``He's not a big headline grabber,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Arthur</ENAMEX>. ``But people
will expect an awful lot out of him. One thing he does need to do
is keep visible.''
<p>
   If the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> confirms his nomination, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Johnson</ENAMEX> would be one of
the youngest men to head the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this century</TIMEX>. He would also
become the first aviator to assume the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>'s top-ranking job since
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1982</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
