<SLUG fv=ttx-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-25</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0826 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-TEX
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> CHIEF SAYS AGENCY SHOULD HAVE DONE MORE TO MONITOR <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>
OPERATIONS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MICHAEL D. TOWLE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fort Worth Star-Telegram</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The government's top regulator of the airline
industry said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that his agency should have done more to
monitor maintenance at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Airlines</ENAMEX>, which ceased operations
after a crash <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last month</TIMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> took 110 lives.
<p>
   ``We should have done a better job helping <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> manage their
infrastructure, especially with respect to maintenance,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David
Hinson</ENAMEX>, chief of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>, told
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Congress</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX> said in testimony before the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House Transportation
Committee</ENAMEX> that the rapid growth of the low-cost, start-up airline
appeared to exceed its ability to perform proper maintenance on its
aircraft.
<p>
   ``<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">A year ago in April</TIMEX> they had about 25 airplanes, and they grew
to 50 by <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX> said. ``In that time frame, we might
have done a better of job of saying, `Why don't you slow down? Your
systems may not be quite capable of helping you manage your
growth.' There are some lessons learned there for us.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX> also told lawmakers that he would be leaving the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> by
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of the year</TIMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> announced <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> that it was
accepting the retirement of the agency's assistant administrator,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anthony Broderick</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> have come under intense
scrutiny since the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX> crash of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> Flight 592. Everyone
aboard was killed when the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas</ENAMEX> DC-9 plunged nose
first into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX> shortly after takeoff from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> halted operations at the request of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, which said
it found a series of maintenance problems during an intense
post-crash review of the carrier's operations.
<p>
   Industry and government experts complain that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> was lax in
overseeing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> and that the airline did not ensure that its
maintenance operations kept pace with the rapid expansion of its
fleet and routes.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mary Schiavo</ENAMEX>, inspector general for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Transportation
Department</ENAMEX>, told lawmakers in the nine-hour hearing that she had
complained to the department about poor performance of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
inspectors and potential problems in the fast-growing airline
industry.
<p>
   ``We believe that there is a culture of unaccountability at the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Schiavo</ENAMEX> said. ``Let's look at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>. They conducted 5,000
inspections before the crash. Only after the crash, after the
public scrutiny, after the media started digging and after some
whistle blowers came forward was there action.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lewis Jordan</ENAMEX> defended his airline.
<p>
   ``Some have suggested that because <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> charges lower fares,
the safety of the airline is also lower,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jordan</ENAMEX> told lawmakers.
``This is patently false. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> is able to offer low fares
because we cut frills. We have not and will never cut corners when
it comes to safety.''
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Stempler</ENAMEX>, an analyst with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AirTrav Advisers</ENAMEX>, an air
travel consulting firm, said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> should ground <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>
permanently, which would keep the carrier's owners and senior
management ``from ever operating an airline in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>
again.''
<p>
   ``This would be a fitting penalty,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stempler</ENAMEX> said, ``for a
group of high-risk, financial entrepreneurs who have brought us
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>, which ... was an accident waiting to happen.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hinson</ENAMEX> told lawmakers that investigators of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> have not found a link between the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida</ENAMEX> crash and sloppy maintenance by outside contractors
discovered by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> in its post-crash review.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> chairman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Hall</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> should have learned of
the potential dangers of outside maintenance contractors <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20 years
ago</TIMEX>.
<p>
   He said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> first cautioned the agency on the matter in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1976</TIMEX>, when a DC-6 operated by a small regional carrier crashed near
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Van Nuys</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calif.</ENAMEX> He said workers for a maintenance contractor had
improperly installed a propeller blade on the plane.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hall</ENAMEX> added that the government must look carefully again at what
he called ``virtual airlines''  &MD;  carriers that provide
transportation but conduct none of their own maintenance or
training.
<p>
   ``We will analyze how carriers that outsource these services are
ensuring the safety of their operations,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hall</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William S. Cohen</ENAMEX>, R-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Maine</ENAMEX>, chairman of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> committee
that oversees government management, said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> told lawmakers <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a
decade ago</TIMEX> that it was troubled by poor maintenance standards at
start-up carriers.
<p>
   ``Perhaps the biggest single problem our inspector work force
has faced is the management of new entrants,'' assistant
administrator <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Broderick</ENAMEX> told a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Senate</ENAMEX> panel in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1986</TIMEX>. ``The
proliferation of contract maintenance has been difficult to deal
with and has caused a large workload.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Cohen</ENAMEX> told the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House</ENAMEX> committee <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>: ``Contract maintenance
is not a new trend, but an old problem that has gone unaddressed
and unsolved.''
</TEXT>
