<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4893 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-ELVIS-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">06-26</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ELVIS</ENAMEX>-DEATH-BOS
EFFECT OF WINDS WEIGHED IN DEATH OF `<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">FLYING ELVIS</ENAMEX>'
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">KATE HUNGER</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Less than 24 hours after a publicity parachute jump
turned tragic, controversy surfaced over the cause  &MD;  whether the
jump should have been made in high winds or if the chutists had
been dropped at the wrong spot  &MD;  and the pilot pointing to wind
shears as a possible explanation.
<p>
   And the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> said it would
investigate whether any regulations had been violated in the
incident that left one of four <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Elvis</ENAMEX> impersonators dead.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Raymond E. Sayles 3d</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX>, one of four parachutists with
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Honeymoon in Vegas Skydiving Exhibition Team</ENAMEX>, died <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> at
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boston City Hospital</ENAMEX> of injuries suffered in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>'s jump
to mark the grand opening of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WaterWorks</ENAMEX>, an entertainment complex
at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Marina Bay</ENAMEX> in nearby <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Quincy</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sayles</ENAMEX>, 41, suffered severe head injuries when he landed on an
embankment by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Savin Hill Yacht Club</ENAMEX> parking lot, a mile short
of the chutists' target across <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dorchester Bay</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   A second chutist, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Bozarth</ENAMEX>, of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Henderson</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Nev.</ENAMEX>, was in
stable condition at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boston City Hospital</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last night</TIMEX>. The other two
 &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Thomas LaRochelle</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Brookline</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.H.</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">George Head</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las
Vegas</ENAMEX>  &MD;  landed unhurt in the water behind the yacht club.
<p>
   The accident left many wondering <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> what went wrong. Some
sources suggested the parachutists had been dropped at the wrong
spot. And the pilot pointed to winds bounced from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>
skyscrapers as a possible explanation.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Randy Komich</ENAMEX>, a club member, who helped pull <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Head</ENAMEX> from the
water, said it was ``definitely too windy'' for the jump and also
said he thinks the parachutists were ``badly dropped''  &MD;  that is,
too far from their destination.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Donald Mayer</ENAMEX>, 49, who piloted the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cessna</ENAMEX> 182A vintage <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1952</TIMEX>
aircraft modified for skydiving, said that from his vantage point
the jump appeared to be ``excellent.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX>, a parachuter with
1,500 jumps who works for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pepperell Skydiving Center</ENAMEX>, said there is
no way he could have confused the marina locations.
<p>
   ``When you are looking from the air, there is no doubt where you
are,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX>, who recalled seeing lights of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Marina Bay</ENAMEX>
parking lot and people gathering for the exhibition. ``It's pretty
precise.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Feeney</ENAMEX>, president and owner of a rival group, The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Flying
Elvi</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Las Vegas</ENAMEX>, said the wind conditions should have stopped the
jump. ``The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Flying Elvi</ENAMEX> would never have jumped in those high wind
conditions,'' he said.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Glenn Bangs</ENAMEX>, director of safety and training with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United
States Parachute Association</ENAMEX>, said weather conditions were ``well
within limits.'' He also said licensed divers are not barred from
jumping in strong winds  &MD;  no matter how high. ``It appears as if it
was safe for them to jump,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bangs</ENAMEX> said, adding that <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sayles</ENAMEX> was the
23d member of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USPA</ENAMEX> to die in an accident <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Weather Service</ENAMEX> said winds were blowing to the
southeast at 15 m.p.h. with gusts up to 23 m.p.h. at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">9 p.m.</TIMEX> A
service spokesman said surface wind measurements do not reflect how
strong winds thousands of feet up might have been.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said the plane left suburban <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norwood Airport</ENAMEX> about <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">8 p.m.</TIMEX>
and hovered over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dorchester Bay</ENAMEX> about <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">8:15 p.m.</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   He said a wind drift indicator  &MD;  a fluorescent yellow crepe
paper 10 inches by 20 feet  &MD;  was dropped from the plane to
determine where the plane should position itself for the chutists
to make the target  &MD;  the parking lot of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Marina Bay</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said the indicator landed within a mile of the target,
making it a good condition for a jump. The plane climbed to 5,000
feet and the chutists prepared to jump, patting each other on the
back, wishing each other a safe jump.
<p>
   ``I looked down at that point and their exit point was exactly
where it should have been,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said. ``I was thinking: `They're
going to have an excellent jump.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said he did not see the jumpers land because he had to
return to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION" MIN="Norwood">Norwood airport</ENAMEX> and was stunned when he learned of the
mishap. He said winds near cities can be unpredictable.
<p>
   ``Windshear could be one of the factors,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mayer</ENAMEX> said. ``If you
were in the ocean, you would have a steady wind ... In <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>, the
wind bounces off skyscrapers and the smoothness of the wind is
disrupted. Even as far as <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Quincy</ENAMEX> wind is disrupted. We judge the
best we can.''
<p>
   Wednesday the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> began its probe. ``They will look at any
violation of regulations,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> spokeswoman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Arlene Salac</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Federal aviation regulations prohibit parachuting between sunset
and sunrise unless the jumper is equipped with a light that is
visible for three miles. The regulations also oversee the packing
of parachutes and whether parachutists can jump over densely
settled areas or in controlled airspace.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Salac</ENAMEX> said the jumpers had obtained appropriate permits to jump
in the restricted airspace, known as the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Terminal Control Area</ENAMEX>, a
20-mile diameter around <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan Airport</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``Everything was fine with the waiver,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Salac</ENAMEX> said, ``so they
will be looking at the chutes.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ed Kane</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Eating Up the Coast</ENAMEX>, the parent company of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WaterWorks</ENAMEX>, said the jumpers were paid <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$8,500</NUMEX> and the contract
allowed them to call it off if they deemed it dangerous for weather
reasons. ``It was their call,'' he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Phil Cocco</ENAMEX>, director of operations for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Eating Up the Coast</ENAMEX>,
added: ``We handled every single possible thing we were supposed
to. We told them: `Don't jump if you don't want to jump.' ''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kelly Smith</ENAMEX>, manager of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Honeymoon</ENAMEX> group, was unavailable for
comment <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Shirley Leung</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Matthew Brelis</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> staff and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX>
Correspondents <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Moira Downes</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Anand Vaishnav</ENAMEX> contributed to this
report.)
</TEXT>
