<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A8727 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-ART-1STLD-W </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-18</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1029 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> 747 EXPLODES IN MID-AIR OFF <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">LONG ISLAND</ENAMEX>; MORE THAN 200 FEARED
LOST
(Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout story. Pls note 4th graf
clarifying issue of number of people on plane.)
(Eds.: The following story is now the lead article on The New York
Times front page)
(ART ADV: Graphic including locator map, description of plane and
list of major fatal airline crashes will be sent as soon as
possible to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX> graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">N.R. KLEINFIELD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World Airlines</ENAMEX> 747 bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York City</ENAMEX> plunged in a fireball into the waters off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> with more than 200 people aboard.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> said there were no survivors, and officials said
there was no immediate indication of what caused the crash.
<p>
   The plane, Flight 800, went down at around <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">8:45 p.m.</TIMEX>, on a
partly cloudy night minutes after taking off from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy
International Airport</ENAMEX>. It crashed about 20 miles from the airport
and sank into the waters off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moriches Inlet</ENAMEX> near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Center Moriches</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Suffolk County</ENAMEX> on the eastern end of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> said there were 249 passengers and a crew of 32
aboard the flight, which was scheduled to leave <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy</ENAMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">7 p.m.</TIMEX>
and was expected to arrive at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charles DeGaulle Airport</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> at
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">8:15</TIMEX> on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>. However, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> said there were 229 people
aboard. The plane had come in from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Athens</ENAMEX> as Flight 881.
<p>
   Witnesses spoke of a light dropping swiftly from the sky and
then either one or two bursts of flame and an enormous black cloud.
As the plane spiraled toward the water, they said they saw pieces
peel off.
<p>
   ``There were two explosions, bright red up in the air,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Keshal</ENAMEX>, who lives right along the shore in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Center Moriches</ENAMEX>.
``There was a lot of flames and redness in the air. And a lot of
smoke. A lot of smoke.''
<p>
   He said he didn't actually see anything resembling an airplane,
but ``two separate red areas coming out of the sky.''
<p>
   Even several hours after the crash, debris from the plane could
be seen burning in the water as rescue boats surrounded it.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jackie Marlow</ENAMEX>, who lives in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">East Moriches</ENAMEX> and had been fishing
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moriches Inlet</ENAMEX>, said, ``There was a great fire, like a fireball.
Eventually the plane just spread apart, and there was a loud thump.
I felt the tremor when it hit the water.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Debbie Walsh</ENAMEX>, who was at a restaurant within view of the crash,
said, ``It looked like a ball of fire falling into the water. It
was a ball of fire and then the plane trailed down and seemed to
break into two pieces.'' She added, ``It was trails of flame going
down to the water.''
<p>
   People on pleasure boats in the general vicinity of the crash
reported seeing bodies bobbing in the water alongside fragments of
the plane still on fire.
<p>
   The plunging ball of fire was apparently visible as far away as
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dune Road</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Westhampton Beach</ENAMEX>, and people said they could feel the
shock wave 10 to 12 miles from the crash.
<p>
   ``We are not finding any survivors,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> Chief Petty
Officer <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steve Sapp</ENAMEX> was quoted by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Associated Press</ENAMEX> as saying.
``We are locating lots of bodies out there.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> planes dropped life rafts in the waters
shortly after the crash. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coaat Guard</ENAMEX> said that six helicopters,
three cutters and a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> P-3 plane were dispatched to the scene.
<p>
   On the beaches fronting the inlet, a temporary morgue was set up
by rescue officials.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> would not confirm that there
was an explosion, saying only that it lost radar contact with the
aircraft at <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">8:45 p.m.</TIMEX> The plane was under the control of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boston
Air Traffic Control Center</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The possibility that there was an explosion aboard the plane
raised the obvious possibility that terrorism was involved, and
federal law-enforcement officials said they were looking into that
possibility. But there are other possible causes for an explosion
as well, such as a problem with an engine, and it may be weeks or
even months before a final determination is made.
<p>
   If terrorism was involved, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> would have jurisdiction over
the investigation into the cause of the blast.
<p>
   But the officials cautioned that they had no definitive evidence
suggesting what caused the downing of the plane, and said that it
would probably be many hours before they got a clear fix on what
happened. One federal official, however, said, ``It doesn't look
good,'' meaning that the circumstances seemed to point to a
terrorist act.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> was mobilizing agents on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> from its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX> field office to help identify victims and to work with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>
to help determine the cause of the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ira Furman</ENAMEX>, a former investigator for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>, urged caution about early reports of
explosions. ``We have found reports of explosions unreliable,'' he
said. ``I can suggest that sometimes an explosion is really
connected with a flameout, like a backfire in a car.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> said that a team from
its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New Jersey</ENAMEX> office was securing the beaches bordering the waters
where the crash occurred. An additional team from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> was
expected to arrive at the site on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The aircraft, a 747 Model 100, is the world's first jumbo jet
and was flown for the first time in 1969. The 100 designation makes
it one of the older 747 models. It is 232 feet long, with a
wingspan of 196 feet. The plane can cruise at 600 miles and hour,
with a range of nearly 760 miles.
<p>
   The aircraft can be configured to carry as many as 516
passengers, although it was unclear how many people the plane that
crashed was set up to contain.
<p>
   The plane had come in from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Athens</ENAMEX> as Flight 881.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> said the plane had climbed to 13,000 feet before it
disappeared from the radar screen.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> sent counterterrorism investigators to the scene, which
is normally done in instances where there is a possibility of an
attack.
</TEXT>
