<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-PROBE-UPDATE1-BLO </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-18</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1095 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-PROBE-UPDATE1-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> CRASH CAUSE PROBED; COMPANY RECEIVED NO THREATS (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Greg Groeller</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Updates with names of crew members, comments from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>
congressman and aviation consultant, details on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pratt &AMP; Whitney</ENAMEX>
engine.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 18</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> investigators continued to
probe what caused a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX> jumbo jet to explode
and plummet into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> with 228 people aboard <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last
night</TIMEX>. There were no reports of survivors. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CNN</ENAMEX> reported that about
100 bodies have been found.
<p>
   Officials said they haven't ruled out terrorism as a cause of
the blast on the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747-100 jet, which came after <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>
heightened security as a precaution ahead of the Olympic Games in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``We have no reason to believe that there was a threat against
the aircraft,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Abels</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> spokesman, said at a press
conference. He also said the company doesn't believe there were any
problems with the aircraft.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Abels</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> wouldn't release a complete list of passengers
until all family members were notified. He said there were 210
passengers on board. The rest were flight attendants and crew.
<p>
   President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> warned Americans not to jump to conclusions
about the cause of the crash.
<p>
   ``We do not know what caused this tragedy,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said.
``Let's wait until we see the evidence. We will find out what
happened.''
<p>
   Eyewitnesses described a series of explosions before the plane
fell.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">navy</ENAMEX> was sending a crew to retrieve the plane's black boxes,
which could be about 100 feet under water, said <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House</ENAMEX> Minority
Leader <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Gephardt</ENAMEX>. The crash site is about 20 miles off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> Representative <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael Forbes</ENAMEX>, speaking near the crash
site, said he was told divers had retrieved one of the two black
boxes.
<p>
   Search teams retrieved passengers' belongings and parts of the
engine, wings and a 30-foot piece of the fuselage.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Bureau of Investigation</ENAMEX> is leading the investigation
into whether the explosion was ``the result of criminal activity,''
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Hall</ENAMEX>, the chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety
Board</ENAMEX>, told <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CNN</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Attorney General <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Janet Reno</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> was looking into two
suspicious telephone calls made after the crash that may have been
related to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800, bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>, disappeared from radar screens
around <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">8:40 p.m. local time</TIMEX> shortly after taking off from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX>. Among the passengers was a party of
16 teenagers from a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pennsylvania</ENAMEX> high school.
<p>
   Experts say the maximum survival period in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> at
65 degrees Fahrenheit is 12 hours.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Abels</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> spokesman, said the plane was delayed about an
hour because of confusion over a passenger's luggage and the
breakdown of a piece of ground equipment that had to be towed from
the runway.
<p>
   The 25-year-old <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> aircraft was bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charles de
Gaulle Airport</ENAMEX>. The plane had flown <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">earlier yesterday</TIMEX> from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Athens</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greece</ENAMEX>, to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Takis Tassopoulous</ENAMEX>, the head of Greek aviation security, told
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CNN</ENAMEX> that his office had no warnings of terrorist activity in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Athens</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> released the names of some crew members. These included
Capt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steve Snyder</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> pilot since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1964</TIMEX>; <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Campell</ENAMEX>, flight
engineer; and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Oliver Krick</ENAMEX>, recently hired by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> and on the plane
as an observer as part of his flight engineer training.
<p>
   The crash comes two months after a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet Inc.</ENAMEX> plane exploded
and crashed in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX>, killing all 110 people
aboard. That plane was a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonnell Douglas Corp.</ENAMEX> DC-9.
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> was grounded by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">the Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX> one month after the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">David Stempler</ENAMEX>, an aviation consultant in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">D.C.</ENAMEX>, said
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX>, already under fire for its monitoring of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX>, will
face tough questions about its safety regulations as a result of
the latest crashes.
<p>
   Passengers will have a ``you better get it right this time''
attitude toward both the airlines and the agency, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Stempler</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   A <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> airliner has never been brought down with a bomb planted
in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> A terrorist bomb that blew up a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> flight over
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lockerbie</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Scotland</ENAMEX>, in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December 1988</TIMEX> originated in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, hidden
in a cassette player.
<p>
   The crash comes less than a year after <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">St. Louis</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>
emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, the airline's second
bankruptcy filing in two years.
<p>
   The carrier has become competitive again by paring costs and
pulling out of money-losing routes. The 72-year-old carrier earlier
on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> reported an almost fivefold increase in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">second-quarter</TIMEX>
net income to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$25.3 million</NUMEX>, or <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">46 cents</NUMEX> a share.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> has had a good safety record, industry analysts say.
<p>
   The plane that crashed was bought in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1971</TIMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> spokesman
said. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> produced that model of the world's largest airliner
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">from 1970 through 1986</TIMEX>. It holds about 360 passengers in three
classes.
<p>
   ``It's too soon to get any hard data on what happened,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Doug Webb</ENAMEX>. ``We will cooperate fully with any
investigation.''
<p>
   All <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747-100 planes use <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pratt &AMP; Whitney</ENAMEX> JT9D engines, said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Sullivan</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pratt &AMP; Whitney</ENAMEX>, which is a unit of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Technologies Corp.</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sullivan</ENAMEX> said the engine, in use since
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1970</TIMEX>, hasn't experienced any problems ``that would be considered
out of the ordinary for airline operations.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pratt &AMP; Whitney</ENAMEX> has sent a crash investigator to the site,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sullivan</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> shares fell 1 to 10 1/4 in <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">midafternoon</TIMEX> trading of 5.2
million shares, far more than the three-month daily average of
885,700 shares.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> shares rose 1 5/8 to 86 7/8, while <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Technologies</ENAMEX>
gained 2 3/4 to 107 3/4.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brian Jenkins</ENAMEX>, vice chairman of the international security firm
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kroll Associates</ENAMEX>, said airport security measures have improved
significantly in recent years, in the wake of terrorist attacks.
<p>
   ``As the result of extraordinary security measures, commercial
aviation, which was once one of the most popular targets of
international terrorism, was made a more difficult target,'' he
said.
<p>
   He said attempts to hijack or plant bombs aboard aircraft have
decreased. Deaths in crashes, however, have increased markedly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this
year</TIMEX>, according to Flight International magazine, to 609 in the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">first six months</TIMEX> from 206 in the same period <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last year</TIMEX>.
<p>
   A toll-free number has been set up for family members of people
on the flight. The number is (800) 438-9892.
</TEXT>
