<STORYID cat=w pri=r> A0100 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttx-z> BC-TWACRASH-CAUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-18</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0891 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-TWACRASH-CAUSE-TEX
AVIATION EXPERTS POINT TO TERRORISM AS LIKELY CAUSE OF CRASH
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MICHAEL D. TOWLE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fort Worth Star-Telegram</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Aviation experts pointed <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> to a terrorist
attack as the most likely cause of the explosion and fiery crash of
a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> jumbo jet into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But they did not rule out mechanical failure, such as the
explosion of one of the four engines on the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747-100, and
President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> warned against snap conclusions.
<p>
   ``I want to caution the American people we have no evidence ...
that would indicate the cause of the accident,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   ``And I want to remind you that when we had the terrible tragedy
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Oklahoma City</ENAMEX>, a lot of people immediately concluded that this
must have been done by some force outside our country, and it
appears that that was not the case now.''
<p>
   But aviation and terrorism experts said eyewitness accounts and
information so far available on the crash of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800 point
to a bomb as the cause.
<p>
   ``It appears to have been an instantaneous, huge explosion,''
said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William Lawrence</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fort Worth</ENAMEX> aviation expert and former
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Marine Corps</ENAMEX> pilot who investigated aviation accidents for the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX>. ``If I had to bet, I would bet it was a bomb.''
<p>
   Among the reasons for that conclusion:
<p>
   Eyewitnesses seem to say unanimously that the Paris-bound plane
plunged into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic</ENAMEX> in a ball of fire.
<p>
   The wreckage, judging from pictures available through the media,
was in small pieces, a sign of the explosive force of a bomb.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747, despite some high-profile mishaps, is considered
one of the world's safest aircraft.
<p>
   The crash came two days before <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">this evening</TIMEX>'s opening of the
Olympic Games in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlanta</ENAMEX>, a factor that might have figured in
terrorists' planning if they were indeed behind the crash.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">MSNBC</ENAMEX>, the new interactive news service from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Microsoft Corp.</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NBC News</ENAMEX>, reported <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late Thursday</TIMEX> on the World Wide Web that
investigators were looking at radar tapes to examine ``possible
activity outside the 747 when it went down.''
<p>
   The tapes may reveal another object, possibly a missile,
collided with the plane, the report said.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawrence</ENAMEX> acknowledged that there could be several possible
causes for the crash.
<p>
   ``If an engine did come apart, it may have sent a hot piece
through a fuel tank,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawrence</ENAMEX> said. ``It could also have been
carrying some kind of hazardous cargo that would have caused an
explosion.''
<p>
   Oxygen generators carried as cargo aboard a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> DC-9 have
been cited as a probable cause of the plane's crash on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX> in
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Florida Everglades</ENAMEX>. All 110 people on board were killed.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawrence</ENAMEX> said it was unusual for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800 to have
disappeared from radar screens with no emergency communications
from the crew.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> officials said the plane left <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7:19 p.m.</TIMEX>
CDT and disappeared by <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">7:48 p.m.</TIMEX> with ``no non-routine
transmissions.''
<p>
   The crash was reminiscent of the downing of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> Flight 103 on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Dec. 21, 1988</TIMEX>. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747 exploded over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lockerbie</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Scotland</ENAMEX>,
less than an hour into its flight from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>. No
distress signals were received from its crew and witnesses reported
seeing fireballs in the sky.
<p>
   Within hours of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> crash, investigators suspected a
bomb. The plane exploded suddenly at 31,000 feet and an Iranian
group claimed responsibility. Federal officials had been cautioned
that a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> flight on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Frankfurt</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> route was a target
for bombing.
<p>
   Investigators later found that the bomb was made of plastic
explosive hidden in a radio-cassette recorder in a suitcase. That
bomb was triggered by a device set for a specific altitude.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Louden</ENAMEX>, a terrorism expert at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">John Jay College</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX>, said several signs point to terrorism in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> crash, but
that so far there is no hard evidence.
<p>
   He noted that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> immediately dispatched members of its
explosives unit to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>. The agents should be able to determine
if an explosive device was used by looking for residue of explosive
material on debris and even on the bodies of victims.
<p>
   ``Because of the possibility of terrorism, you absolutely have
to start looking right away,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Louden</ENAMEX> said. ``If it does turn out
to be that, you haven't lost time or potential evidence.''
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Louden</ENAMEX> said the crash could have been caused by someone
without political motives.
<p>
   ``It could be man-caused, but not terrorist related,'' he said.
``There could be some other motivation for someone wanting to
accomplish the same end. There are any number of motivating
factors: terrorism, suicide, insurance, and it could have been just
one person bent on any of the above.''
<p>
   Attorney General <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Janet Reno</ENAMEX> said two telephone calls from people
claiming responsibility were received after the plane went down.
<p>
   Television station <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WTSP</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tampa</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, received a call at about
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2:45 Thursday morning</TIMEX> from someone whom station officials said
claimed to be a member of a Jihad, or ``holy war.'' The station
notified <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Tampa</ENAMEX> police and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">FBI</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Louden</ENAMEX> said it is not unusual for a group, or pranksters, to
take credit for a deadly event after the fact.
<p>
   ``Often, it is one group trying to get their name in the ring,''
he said.
</TEXT>
