<STORYID cat=f pri=r> A0252 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=kan-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-OVERHAUL-KAN </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-18</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-OVERHAUL-KAN
EXPLOSION OF <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> FLIGHT 800 SPREADS PALL OVER AIRLINE'S OVERHAUL
BASE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JULIUS A. KARASH</ENAMEX>
c. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kansas City Star</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">KANSAS CITY</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Mo.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The deadly explosion of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800 spread
a pall over the airline's <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX> overhaul base <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``We lost a lot of good people on that airplane,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Roger Tyler</ENAMEX>,
a base mechanic, said as he sat at nearby <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Allie's Bar &AMP; Grill</ENAMEX> after
his work shift ended <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX>. ``It's heart saddening.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> records show that the jet that
crashed near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> paid what were considered routine visits to
the base, the airline's primary site for plane maintenance.
<p>
   Base workers said they and their colleagues wore Walkman radios
much of the work day, listening for word of what ignited the 747
explosion.
<p>
   The cause of the crash was unknown, and that uncertainty grated
on the beefy, bearded <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tyler</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``I would hate to think that this was maintenance,'' he said
over the muted babblings of a TV talk show. ``As long as I've
worked at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>, I've never seen bad maintenance. Everybody's so
conscientious. The training takes years. It's not something you go
to night school for.''
<p>
   Other <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> workers at the bar described the mood at the base as
``pretty somber.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Steve Lacy</ENAMEX>, a mechanic who has worked at the base nearly <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">30
years</TIMEX>, was subdued and somewhat stoic about the tragedy.
<p>
   ``I'm sorry for all those people that got killed,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lacy</ENAMEX> said.
``It's just one of those things. It could have been a bomb or
anything. You don't know what happened....There's nothing else I
can do.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kathy Woodward</ENAMEX>, a bartender and waitress at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Final Approach
Pub</ENAMEX> near the base, said she served fewer <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> employees than normal
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``The (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>) people I had <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> were very down,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Woodward</ENAMEX> said
amid the bar's vast collection of airline memorabilia. ``They were
glued to the TV. People were not themselves.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tyler</ENAMEX>, who overhauls pumps that move fuel from the wings to the
engine, said working on aircraft is a high-pressure job, ``probably
right below being a doctor.''
<p>
   ``We take people's lives in our hands,'' he said. ``We don't
take it lightly. I'll stand behind every pump I ever build. When I
go home to sleep <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">tonight</TIMEX>, I'll know that isn't what caused that
crash.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tyler</ENAMEX> insisted that the crash wouldn't impede <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>'s financial
recovery after years of losses: ``We're coming back, and everybody
knows we're coming back.''
<p>
   Mechanics and other rank-and-file workers at the base belong to
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Machinists Local 1650</ENAMEX>, which is overseen by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Machinists District
142</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gary Poos</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">District 142</ENAMEX> official, said the union is ``fully
participating in this investigation.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Poos</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William O'Driscoll</ENAMEX>, president of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">District 142</ENAMEX>, was at
the command post in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Poos</ENAMEX> said the union's ``deepest sympathy goes to the families
and friends of those who perished in this tragedy.''
</TEXT>
