<STORYID cat=w pri=u> A1391 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-MISSILE-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-19</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-MISSILE-HNS
EXPERTS SKEPTICAL THAT A STINGER MISSILE DOWNED <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> JET
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">HOLLY YEAGER</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hearst Newspapers</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Weapons experts said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> it's unlikely that a
Stinger surface-to-air missile brought down <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Paul Beaver</ENAMEX>, a spokesman for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Jane's Information Group Limited</ENAMEX>,
publishers of books on weapons, noted a lack of evidence that any
missile was involved in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> explosion and crash of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beaver</ENAMEX> also expressed skepticism that a hand-held <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-made
Stinger anti-aircraft missile could have downed the jumbo jet.
<p>
   Some eyewitnesses said they saw a bright light moving toward the
jet just before it exploded over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> shortly after
it had taken off from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, leading
to speculation that a missile may have been responsible. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> said
230 passengers and crew were killed in the incident.
<p>
   However, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beaver</ENAMEX> said several factors make him think the weapon
``couldn't possibly have been used.''
<p>
   For one thing, the Stinger's maximum altitude is about 12,400
feet, while the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> jet exploded at an altitude of around 13,700,
he noted.
<p>
   Furthermore, the missile has a maximum range of about 2.8 miles,
while the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> plane was about 10 miles offshore. The missile would
have to have been fired from a boat, a still more difficult
maneuver.
<p>
   In addition, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beaver</ENAMEX> said batteries used in the missiles have
only a 10-year life and may have failed by now.
<p>
   ``You need to be an expert to operate it,'' he said. ``You need
to smuggle it into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> or to have obtained it
illegally in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>,'' he added.
<p>
   Noting that a shoulder-fired Stinger, including its heat-seeking
missile and launcher, weighs about 44 pounds and is 60 inches long,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beaver</ENAMEX> called it ``a conspicuous piece of merchandise.''
<p>
   Arms control experts have been concerned about an estimated
1,000 Stinger missiles the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> shipped to Afghan rebels
in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late 1980s</TIMEX> to help them shoot down Soviet helicopters.
<p>
   After the war, several hundred unused Stingers began spreading
to other countries and terrorist groups. A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CIA</ENAMEX> effort with a
reported budget of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$55 million</NUMEX> to buy back the missiles has been
largely unsuccessful, instead boosting the black-market price of
the <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$30,000</NUMEX> missiles to more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$100,000</NUMEX>, experts say.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">William D. Hartung</ENAMEX>, a specialist in the global arms market at
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New School for Social Research</ENAMEX>, called the spread of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-made Stingers ``a case of unintended consequences.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> provided the weapons to the anti-communist
Afghan <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">mujahedeen</ENAMEX> ``for one purpose, ejecting the Soviets, but they
didn't think about the character of the movement that they were
giving it to, which was a right-wing fundamentalist Islamic
movement which was involved in training Islamic fighters from all
over the world,'' he said.
<p>
   While that helps explain how the Stingers originally shipped to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Afghanistan</ENAMEX> spread to terrorist groups throughout the world,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hartung</ENAMEX> said it's ``unbelievable that someone could park themselves
on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> with a Stinger missile and take out an airliner.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Natalie J. Goldring</ENAMEX>, deputy director of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British American
Security Information Council</ENAMEX>, a non-profit research group, also
expressed skepticism that a Stinger was responsible.
<p>
   ``I think we've been lucky,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Goldring</ENAMEX> said. ``I am one of those
people who has been saying for a long time that this is the sort of
system that can come back to haunt us.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Goldring</ENAMEX> said ``every Stinger that is in another country's hands
is a Stinger that can be used against civilian aircraft.''
<p>
   But she, too, said she thinks it's unlikely that a Stinger was
used to down the jumbo jet. ``The more that advanced technology is
used in a system, the shorter its shelf life tends to be,'' she
said.
<p>
   While pistols from World War I can still be found in working
order, ``advanced portable surface-to-air missiles are a lot more
complicated,'' she said.
<p>
   Terrorism expert <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Neil Livingstone</ENAMEX> said it's too early to rule
out any explanation for the explosion, but he said a missile
appears unlikely. On the other hand, he said, at least a dozen
terrorist groups have surface-to-air missiles.
<p>
   While <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> officials have discounted reports that radar
showed a small object approaching the plane just before it
exploded, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Beaver</ENAMEX> said a missile like the Stinger wouldn't
necessarily show up on radar.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Pike</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federation of American Scientists</ENAMEX> said that
even if the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> plane was outside the range of a Stinger, ``that
would by no means rule out this thing being done by a
surface-to-air missile,'' other than a Stinger, perhaps fired from
a boat.
<p>
   ``There are other man-portable missiles ... that have a
significantly longer range,'' including the Russian SA-7 Grail
anti-aircraft missile, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pike</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Goldring</ENAMEX> said the mere speculation that a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>-made weapon may
have been responsible for the explosion will bring attention to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> arms export policy.
<p>
   ``I think we need to think much more carefully about what kinds
of weapons we are supplying, especially to unstable and
undemocratic regimes,'' she said. ``The risks are just too high.''
</TEXT>
