<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1759 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttj-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-SEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-19</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-SEARCH-HNS
SEAMAN KEEPS THINKING OF STUFFED TWEETIE BIRD FISHED FROM WATER
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients.)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BENNETT ROTH</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Houston Chronicle</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">EAST MORICHES</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.Y.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom Coonan</ENAMEX> had been at sea less than two
days when his <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Coast Guard</ENAMEX> cutter was forced by rough weather
to abandon its search <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> for the remains of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800.
<p>
   On his way back to port, the 19-year-old seaman kept thinking
about the four-foot, stuffed Tweetie Bird he had fished from the
water.
<p>
   ``I thought about a little kid sitting near his mom holding that
bird,'' he said. ``And then, it's over.''
<p>
   For <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Coonan</ENAMEX> and 10 other crew members of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> cutter
Point Wells, the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past two days</TIMEX> have been unsettling. Their vessel,
once a patrol boat in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Vietnam</ENAMEX>, was one of the first to arrive off
eastern <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early Thursday</TIMEX>, just hours after the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>-bound <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747 exploded and plunged into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``You could smell it in the air. You knew something had
happened,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Coonan</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Vermont</ENAMEX> native.
<p>
   ``It was eerie when you know what's out there,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chris
Biswurm</ENAMEX>, 23, another Point Wells crewman. ``We were just out there
steaming through this stuff.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Donald Kreesim</ENAMEX>, a senior chief petty officer, said he had tried
to prepare his young crew for what he knew would be an emotionally
difficult task when the Point Wells left port. He even refused to
let the crew watch television, fearing it might distract them and
make their jobs even harder.
<p>
   ``We had a mission to concentrate on,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kreesim</ENAMEX>, 40.
<p>
   Since <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late Wednesday</TIMEX>, the Point Wells and hundreds of other
vessels have scoured the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic</ENAMEX> off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>, looking for
bodies, plane debris and any possessions of the 230 people who
boarded the plane at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Search and rescue efforts were hampered <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> by rain and heavy
seas.
<p>
   Waves as high as six feet forced the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> to recall some
of its smaller boats. Divers, who had been expected to begin their
search for debris on the ocean floor, were unable to get into the
water.
<p>
   Officials feared the turbulent water was spreading the debris
and moving some of it into deeper water, which would increase the
difficulty of retrieving bodies and wreckage.
<p>
   ``The weather is not playing in our favor,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Blair Thomas</ENAMEX>,
public affairs officer for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> is expected to bring in divers and special
equipment that can be lowered in the water to pick up the
high-pitched signal from the flight data recorders  &MD;  the so-called
black boxes  &MD;  aboard the aircraft.
<p>
   Meanwhile, residents have been reporting pieces of the wreckage
washing ashore.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ed O'Connell</ENAMEX> found a charred tray table, the kind normally
attached to the rear of airplane seats, near his home about 15
miles from the crash site.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">O'Connell</ENAMEX>, who showed reporters his find, said he figured it was
part of the plane when he noticed the wording ``Life Vest under
your seat'' etched on the tray bottom.
<p>
   Meanwhile, those who observed the jumbo jet exploding say they
still have vivid memories. Captain <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Chris Baur</ENAMEX> of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York
International Guard</ENAMEX>, was flying his helicopter when the plane went
down.
<p>
   ``There was an explosion followed by a bigger explosion followed
by a bigger explosion,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Baur</ENAMEX> recalled. ``It spiraled down like a
corkscrew until it hit the ocean.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Baur</ENAMEX> said he became aware of the magnitude of the loss when he
sighted as many as 80 bodies in the water.
</TEXT>
