<SLUG fv=tia-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BLOOM </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-19</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BLOOM
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> HASN'T TAKEN OVER <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> PROBE; CAUSE STILL UNKNOWN (UPDATE1)
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Greg Groeller</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
   (Adds comments from <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>'s <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">9
p.m.</TIMEX> press conference in 5th-8th and 13th paragraphs.)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 19</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation</ENAMEX> official said the agency hasn't taken over the probe
of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>'s crash of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World Airlines Inc.</ENAMEX> jet that killed
230 people.
<p>
   However, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, an investigator with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX>'s
anti-terrorism task force, said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> is treating the crash site
as a crime scene in case it later determines a crime was committed.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> said investigators haven't determined the cause and
are considering all possibilities. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747,
exploded and plunged into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX> off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long
Island</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``If it is a terrorist act, we will find the cowards who did
this,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> said at a press conference near the crash site.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> hasn't delayed blaming the crash on a terrorist act due
to pressure from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> over the timing of the opening of
the Olympic games, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> said in a second press conference held
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX>. ``We're not trying to be cute here. We're not
prepared to say something until we're sure it's absolutely true,''
he said. ``We're not discounting anything.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> added that it took six days before the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December 1988</TIMEX>
crash of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> 747 in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lockerbie</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Scotland</ENAMEX>, was labeled the
result of a bomb.
<p>
   He said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> is working with overseas criminal investigation
agencies in the probe, which he described as ``massive.''
<p>
   The crash is the second-worst in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>, after a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1979</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American
Airlines</ENAMEX> crash in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX> that killed 273.
<p>
   The plane went down shortly after taking off from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>'s
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">John F. Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX> bound for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Charles de Gaulle
Airport</ENAMEX>. It had flown earlier from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Athens</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greece</ENAMEX>, to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Earlier today</TIMEX>, a spokesman for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency</ENAMEX> confirmed it also is investigating the crash, looking for
clues that might suggest a foreign connection.
<p>
   ``We've been involved since the tragedy first occurred,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mark Mansfield</ENAMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CIA</ENAMEX> spokesman. He said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">CIA</ENAMEX> always looks at
incidents where involvement by a foreign person or group is
possible.
<p>
   At the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX> press conference, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, chairman of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX>, said high winds and rough
seas had forced divers away from a spot at the crash site where a
large piece of the aircraft might be located, according to sonar
readings. <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">This evening</TIMEX> he said less than <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">1 percent</NUMEX> of the wreckage
has been recovered so far.
<p>
   Earlier, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> Mayor <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rudolph Giuliani</ENAMEX> again slammed <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> for
taking too long to present victims' families with a list of
confirmed fatalities.
<p>
   ``I heard a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> spokesman say that all the family members had
been notified by <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">noon</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">yesterday</TIMEX>,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Giuliani</ENAMEX> said. ``That's totally
false. They hadn't even compiled a list by <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4 o'clock</TIMEX>.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jeff Erickson</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>'s chief executive, responded to a question
about the delay by saying that the airline's trauma response team
had to be assembled from locations all over the country. He said
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> officials are currently working with family members in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>
and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Erickson</ENAMEX> also said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last night</TIMEX>'s Flight 800 left fully loaded and
that the airline's advance bookings for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">summer</TIMEX> remain strong.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> shares fell 3/4 to close at 9 1/2 on trading of 3.5 million
shares, much more than the three-month average of 997,100, but less
than half the 7.3 million shares traded <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>.
</TEXT>
