<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">YUGO</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSNIA</ENAMEX>-TROOPS-NY </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-21</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0791 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">YUGO</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSNIA</ENAMEX>-TROOPS-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSNIA</ENAMEX> GIs SEE THEMSELVES AS LUCKY AFTER BOMB MISHAP
(th)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MIKE O'CONNOR</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BRCKO</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia-Herzegovina</ENAMEX>  &MD;  While the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> investigated why one
of its aircraft accidentally dropped a 500-pound bomb on the edge
of a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> military base near here, soldiers at the base were asking
similar questions <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX> and counting themselves lucky that there
were no injuries.
<p>
   Aside, that is, from damage to the nerves of the some 800
people, most attached to an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX> cavalry squadron, who were at the
base on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">afternoon</TIMEX> when the bomb struck.
<p>
   ``We thought war was fixing to break out,'' said Pfc. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Carter
Sanders</ENAMEX>, who with his partner in a watchtower at the base, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Camp
McGovern</ENAMEX>, was probably the closest person to the explosion.
<p>
   Pfc. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">John Raile</ENAMEX> said, ``People's eyes were all wide trying to
figure out what happened.''
<p>
   Some soldiers said they thought that they were under artillery
attack. The base commander, Lt. Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tony Cucolo</ENAMEX>, said he thought
at first that it might be an attack by a renegade pilot from one of
the local Bosnian military forces. Others said they had no idea who
was shooting at them or with what.
<p>
   Soldiers said that for about 30 minutes until the situation was
clarified, they dove into bunkers and ran to firing positions
around the base, preparing to fire off mortars and getting ready
for the next step in what was generally thought to be an attack.
<p>
   But even the truth was of only limited comfort. Spc. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ronald Orr</ENAMEX>
said he had thought of soldiers killed by alleid fire during the
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1991</TIMEX> Persian Gulf war. He said: ``It makes you think, `Here we go
again.' ''
<p>
   Military officials said the bomb fell from a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> FA-18 jet,
also known as a Hornet, in which the pilot was practicing bombing
runs near the base so as to be able to protect the troops there in
case they came under attack by ground forces.
<p>
   The drill did not entail dropping a bomb, only practicing
coordination between the aircraft and controllers on the ground.
But as the jet, which was based on the carrier Enterprise in the
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Adriatic</ENAMEX>, flew over the base, the bomb fell, exploding on a remote
section of a large mound of dirt that runs around most of the base.
<p>
   It missed three large freight containers holding ammunition by
about 200 feet.
<p>
   About half of the bomb's weight was the metal casing, so 250
pounds of explosive shook the ground, sending concussion waves
against the soldiers and 250 pounds of metal fragments through part
of the base. An <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Army</ENAMEX> spokesman said, however, that there was almost
no damage from either the explosion or shrapnel.
<p>
   There have been no fatalities as a result of hostile action
among the 16,500 American peacekeepers in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX> since they began
arriving in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The base, just southwest of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Brcko</ENAMEX>, is in a particularly tense
area of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX>, in the three-mile wide strip of land that separates
Bosnian government and Bosnia Serb territory.
<p>
   There has been fairly constant friction between the Muslim and
Serbian authorities here. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Last week</TIMEX>, three war-damaged houses that
were being rebuilt by their Muslim owners on the Serbian side were
dynamited, presumably by Serbs who did not want the Muslims to
return.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Four nights ago</TIMEX>, base officers said, three men tried to sneak
into the base, prompting a search around the base and the shooting
off of illumination shells. Although the officers said the
intruders probably were only looking for something to steal, the
incident raised anxieties here.
<p>
   Sgt. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Peter Walker</ENAMEX> said that on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX>, while he was trying to
figure out who was behind the explosion, he thought of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last month</TIMEX>'s
bomb attack on the American base in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Saudi Arabia</ENAMEX> and <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX>'s
crash of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> airliner off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   As he watched the smoke rise from what he described as a very
impressive explosion, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Walker</ENAMEX> said he thought: ``If something like
that hits real near us, we're dead. There's no question.''
<p>
   The base is built around a large group of buildings from an
abandoned farm cooperative. The nearest civilian houses are more
than a mile away in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bosnia</ENAMEX> Serb side of the dividing line. But
these too are abandoned for the most part. The owners are Muslims
who were expelled during the war, and the homes are too badly
damaged to be habitable.
<p>
   But some of the owners are repairing their homes. <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Sunday</TIMEX>, while
the American soldiers were still shaken, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hamdija Mujic</ENAMEX> leaned
against the bumper of his burned car, which remains in the ruins of
the garage where it was sitting <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two years ago</TIMEX> when an artillery
barrage destroyed his house.
<p>
   ``Yeah, we heard the explosion,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Mujic</ENAMEX> said, ``but we didn't
think much of it. It was just one bomb. The Americans should
relax.''
</TEXT>
