CRASH INQUIRY FAILS TO FIND EVIDENCE OF EXPLOSIVE(ART ADV: Map of
debris found by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Coast Guard</ENAMEX> has been sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX> graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW PURDY</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Investigators examining the small amount of wreckage
recovered so far from the crash of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 800
said on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that they had not yet found any concrete evidence
that the plane was destroyed by an explosive device.
<p>
   Speaking to reporters on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX>, President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> said
investigators were making progress, but he added: ``We must not
draw conclusions until we're sure the conclusion is supported by
the facts. And I cannot say that I've learned anything <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> which
enables me to give you a definite conclusion about the cause of the
accident.''
<p>
   Law enforcement officials on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> continued to maintain
that circumstantial evidence suggested that the 747 jetliner
crashed because of an act of either political terrorism or
sabotage. And they said they expected to have a clearer sense of
what caused the plane to explode <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last Wednesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> when they
begin recovering large sections of the wreckage, possibly as early
as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Gov. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">George Pataki</ENAMEX> said the first priority was to recover the
``dozens and dozens'' of bodies that divers had found trapped in
large sections of the fuselage resting on the bottom of the ocean.
He estimated that the divers had found 60 to 100 bodies, which
could account for most of the 122 bodies that have not been
recovered.
<p>
   Despite <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pataki</ENAMEX>'s announcement, there were conflicting statements
from other officials on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, the vice-chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation
Safety Board</ENAMEX>, said there were no bodies in the wreckage that had
not been recovered.
<p>
   But despite <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX>' comments, a federal official in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">East
Moriches</ENAMEX>, on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
confirmed that there were dozens of bodies still on the ocean
floor.
<p>
   And <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">early on Wednesday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, assistant <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> director
for the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> office, said: ``Given the fact that a portion of
the fuselage has been discovered, and that the search team has
apparently located a large debris field in the same area, we have
every hope and expectation of finding and recovering a significant
number of victims soon.''
<p>
   The accounts angered family members staying at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ramada Plaza
Hotel</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy International Airport</ENAMEX>, who told reporters late on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> that they were frustrated by the conflicting
accounts.
<p>
   So far, the remains of 108 of the 230 people on board the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New
York</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> flight have been recovered, and 77 bodies have been
identified.
<p>
   At the crash site off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Suffolk County</ENAMEX> on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long
Island</ENAMEX>, recovery workers brought up three more bodies on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>
and continued sonar mapping of the ocean floor in preparation for
the enormous task of disentangling bodies from the wreckage,
bringing them to the surface and then raising the pieces of the
airplane.
<p>
   ``Raising the remains, identifying the bodies is a top
priority,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Pataki</ENAMEX> said. ``We believe there will be dozens and
dozens of bodies that will be identified and returned to their
families.''
<p>
   The governor said the second task would be to recover the large
pieces of the plane, which he said would help solve the mystery of
what made the airplane explode at an altitude of 13,700 feet
shortly after it took off for <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Law enforcement officials, who from the beginning suspected that
the plane had been destroyed by an explosive device, said on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that further tests for traces of explosives from a piece of
the airplane's wing had not yet produced any evidence of such
traces. On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>, when law enforcement agents on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>
tested a residue found on the underside of the wing segment, they
first found traces of an explosive, but in a later test with
different equipment, no traces were detected.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesdayy</TIMEX>, when the residue was tested with more sophisticated
equipment at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> laboratory in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Quantico</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Va.</ENAMEX>, once again no
explosive traces were found on this or any other piece of wreckage
that had been retrieved.
<p>
   ``Right now,'' a senior law enforcement official said, ``we just
don't have enough pieces of metal to make a judgment about the
cause of the crash. Not today and maybe not tomorrow.''
<p>
   Even as the crash inquiry remains classified as an accident
investigation, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> is investigating various criminal theories.
And <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Zachary Carter</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> attorney for the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eastern District of
New York</ENAMEX>, has assigned prosecutors and investigators, led by
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Valerie Caproni</ENAMEX>, head of the criminal division, to monitor the
case.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, said on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX> that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> had already conducted
1,300 interviews on the crash. ``We're looking at everybody that
touched that aircraft,'' he said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> said that two working criminal theories were that the
plane was destroyed by a bomb or a missile and that ``there's
circumstantial evidence pointing in those directions.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kenneth Bacon</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense Department</ENAMEX>'s chief spokesman, cast
some doubt on the possibility of a missile. He said that satellite
photographs and radar data offered no evidence of a missile strike
on the plane. He said that apart from the accounts of eyewitnesses
who described a streak of light near the 747 before the explosion,
there was ``precious else'' to suggest that a missile had hit the
plane.
<p>
   But he told reporters that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense Department</ENAMEX> and other
federal agencies had left open the possibility of a missile,
possibly fired from a boat. ``Could it have been fired from the
water?'' he said. ``That is the question that they're looking
into.''
</TEXT>
