<DOCID> nyt960730.0633 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A5187 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-EVIDENCE-2T </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-30</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0846 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-EVIDENCE-2TAKES-NYT
INVESTIGATORS SEE `EERIE SIMILARITIES' WITH OTHER AIRLINERS THAT
BLEW UP
(With <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH)
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DON VAN NATTA JR.</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>  &MD;  When an explosion ripped through a French airliner
flying over the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Sahara</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1989</TIMEX>, the blast severed the DC-10's front
end from the rest of the plane, which stayed aloft for about 20
seconds before plunging into the ground. The black boxes showed
that everything on board was normal until a jarring, split-second
noise was followed by silence.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Two days later</TIMEX>, investigators said the crash was caused by a
bomb.
<p>
   When <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> Flight 103 blew up over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lockerbie</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Scotland</ENAMEX>, in
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">December 1988</TIMEX>, the nose of the aircraft broke away from the rest of
the plane, scattering debris over 80 square miles of Scottish
countryside. The black boxes showed everything on board was normal,
until a split-second noise, followed by silence.
<p>
   Within three days, investigators said the probable cause was a
bomb.
<p>
   In both cases, investigators based their pronouncements that the
airplanes were destroyed by bombs not on forensic evidence found in
a laboratory, but instead on early examinations of wreckage and the
circumstances of the crashes.
<p>
   In some ways, the circumstances surrounding the explosion of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 800 on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 17</TIMEX> are strikingly similar
to the bombings of the other two. An explosion caused Flight 800's
front end to break away from the rest of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747, which
continued to fly for about 20 seconds before becoming engulfed by a
fireball. Flight 800's black boxes show that everything on board
was normal until a split-second sound was followed by silence.
<p>
   Yet <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks after Flight 800 exploded off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long
Island</ENAMEX></TIMEX>, federal officials have not determined the cause of the
crash, or even publicly declared their strong, private suspicions
that a bomb, possibly hidden in the forward cargo hold, destroyed
the aircraft. The investigators on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> also have something
the investigators of the other two bombings did not have: dozens of
eyewitness accounts that the plane exploded in midair.
<p>
   Investigators explain their caution by saying they do not want
to leap to conclusions that might later be proved wrong. Several
officials in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX> said that some <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> officials
appeared eager to respond aggressively to the crash with
condemnations of terrorism. But, the officials said, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Justice
Department</ENAMEX> officials did not want to exaggerate the threat of
terrorism, and were wary of offering conclusions without clear-cut
evidence.
<p>
   In addition, some officials said, the wariness goes beyond the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> flight itself. They said federal security officials,
preoccupied by terror concerns at the Olympics, have wanted to
avoid declaring the crash a terrorist act because of fears that
such a determination would provoke domestic and foreign extremists.
<p>
   At each daily briefing, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, the assistant director
of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX>, says, ``The investigation is continuing,''
and he refuses to say a bomb is the most likely cause of the
explosion. Officials said they would not declare the crash to be a
result of a bomb until they had found traces of bomb materials on
wreckage from the crash.
<p>
   On both the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lockerbie</ENAMEX> jet and the French airliner, a bomb was
hidden in a piece of luggage stored in the front cargo hold. The
force of the blast caused the front of both planes to split off in
midair.
<p>
   Because Flight 800 broke apart in a similar way, investigators
have privately speculated that the front cargo hold was the most
likely place a bomb was hidden.
<p>
   ``There are so many similarities, it's almost eerie,'' said one
federal official, who insisted on anonymity. ``It would be a major
surprise if this turned out to be some mechanical failure.''
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">In the 14 days since the crash of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> jet</TIMEX>, a powerful
dynamic has settled over the inquiry. Federal investigators refuse
to say publicly what they overwhelmingly agree on in private: a
powerful explosive destroyed the plane.
<p>
   Investigators are always reluctant to declare the official cause
of an airplane crash until there is conclusive physical evidence.
In the investigations of the downings of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Union de Transports Ariens</ENAMEX>
Flight 772, the one that crashed in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Africa</ENAMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX> Flight 103,
investigators had the distinct advantage of recovering airplane
wreckage over land. Some pieces clearly showed characteristics
consistent with an explosive.
<p>
   But Flight 800 investigators have had to retrieve pieces of
potential evidence from the bottom of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic Ocean</ENAMEX>, 120 feet
below the surface, which has made the hunt for conclusive evidence
that much more difficult.
<p>
   Those same challenges faced officials more than <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a decade ago</TIMEX>
when they investigated the crash of an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air-India</ENAMEX> 747, which was
bombed off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ireland</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 1985</TIMEX>. The wreckage settled
6,700 feet below the surface of the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Irish Sea</ENAMEX>, and it took more
than six months before officials declared it to be a bomb.
<p>
   (MORE)
<p>
   nn
</TEXT>
