<DOCID> nyt960807.0656 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A4827 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-07</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-BOS
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> PROBERS SEE LITTLE CHANCE OF MORE BODIES RECOVERED
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">FRED KAPLAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SMITHTOWN</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.Y.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Investigators said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> that they have
given up hope of finding the remaining 35 victims from the wreckage
of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800.
<p>
   In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the three weeks since the crash</TIMEX>, divers have brought up 195
of the 230 passengers and crew who were aboard the jumbo jet on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 17</TIMEX>. But as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> salvage ships continue to bring up large
pieces of wreckage from the plane, it is becoming less likely that
many more bodies remain hidden.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert Francis</ENAMEX>, vice chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation
Safety Board</ENAMEX>, said finding victims remains the top priority. But
``there's just not the kind of wreckage out there anymore where
we'd expect to find bodies,'' he said.
<p>
   He said that families have been told and that they are ``pretty
understanding.''
<p>
   In another development, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX> is
expected to announce <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tjirdau</TIMEX> that it will requiring testing of fuel
pumps on 747s for electrical resistance.
<p>
   There are 14 pumps on the jumbo jet's wings, and low resistance
indicates they could develop arcing that might lead to a fuel leak
and a possible fire. In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 1995</TIMEX>, a fire related to a fuel pump
leak broke out in the wheelwell of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Japan Airlines</ENAMEX> plane. It was
extinguished before the plane took off.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> jet experienced a power loss and its cockpit-voice and
flight data recorders ended abruptly, which investigators say would
not have happened in the case of an engine failure or explosion.
<p>
   In the past few days, as fewer and fewer victims have been
found, investigators have shifted their attention to recovering
pieces of the plane that could be crucial to solving the mystery of
what caused the 747 to explode in midair on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 17</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The salvage ship USS Grasp pulled up a 75-foot-long section of
the plane's right wing <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX>, with a chunk of the fuselage
attached to it. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said he saw burn marks on the wing, but he
warned against drawing conclusions from that, noting that the
ocean's surface was on fire when the plane crashed and the wing
could have been burned when it hit the water.
<p>
   Technicians onboard the Grasp were working on cutting the wing
in two, so that it would fit onto the tugboat bringing pieces of
the wreckage back to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Grumman</ENAMEX> aircraft hangar on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>,
where they are being analyzed.
<p>
   Investigators are also now interested in bringing up the plane's
engines as quickily as possible. Two of the four engines  &MD;  and a
piece of the third  &MD;  have been found by sonar detectors.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said the engines are key evidence, mainly because they
might show where the explosion came from  &MD;  a missile from outside
the plane or a bomb from within, and, if the latter, where in the
plane.
<p>
   He said a ``rub strip'' is inside the engine, surrounding its
fan blades. When the blades rotate, the strip keeps them from
damaging the engine's shell.
<p>
   ``In an accident, you can sometimes tell from the rub strip what
kind of forces have come to bear on the aircraft,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
``You can end up with the fan clipping part of the rub strip. An
engineer can figure out where that force came from.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> assistant director involved in the
investigation, said, ``We're very pleased with the speed of the
recovery of parts of the aircraft.''
<p>
   When asked if it might be a few weeks or more before they figure
out what caused the explosion, he replied: ``It could very well be.
I would hope it won't be that long ... Whether it's a week or two
weeks or four days, I don't know.''
</TEXT>
