<STORYID cat=t pri=u> A7083 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-BIZTRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-20</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-BIZTRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS
(f and t coding)
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">LOGAN AIRPORT</ENAMEX> BEEFING UP SECURITY
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">JERRY ACKERMAN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan Airport</ENAMEX> expects by the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">end of next week</TIMEX> to have
two explosives-detection units ready to roll out at a moment's
notice to sniff out dangerous objects in luggage and cargo
compartments, or even at check-in gates.
<p>
   Each weighing about 45 pounds, the units are made by <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>-area
companies, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ion Track Instruments Inc.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wilmington</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thermedics
Inc.</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Woburn</ENAMEX>. Airport security director <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Joseph Lawless</ENAMEX> said that
along with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX>'s five trained bomb-sniffing dogs, the units will
provide another level of assurance for a flying public deeply
worried about in-flight safety.
<p>
   Three out of four corporate travel managers polled by the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Business Travel Association</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last month</TIMEX>, after the crash of
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800, said they would be willing to pay a premium on
airline tickets to improve airport security.
<p>
   Respondents to the poll also chided the government and airlines
for failing to take security seriously enough. Many of those who
opposed paying more said they were concerned that government would
only waste the money.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawless</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX> is still working out whether to lease or buy
the explosives-detection devices. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Ion Track</ENAMEX>'s version lists for
more than <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$50,000</NUMEX>, and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Thermedics</ENAMEX>' for over <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$150,000</NUMEX>. The two
designs also function differently, he said, but having both will
provide a testing ground for their effectiveness.
<p>
   Other security procedures put into force after Flight 800 went
down already are complicating the lives of passengers who book
trips ``electronically,'' without traditional tickets.
<p>
   Electronic ticketing eliminates paperwork and boosts airline
profit margins. Passengers get a confirmation number when they
reserve their flights. At the gate, they get a boarding pass by
repeating their number and showing a photo identification card.
<p>
   The system didn't work, though, when airports, including <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX>,
tightened up who can get to the gates. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lawless</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX> took this
step because its higher number of overseas travelers could make the
airport more vulnerable to terrorism.
<p>
   Now, airlines that don't issue paper tickets must send agents to
meet their passengers at the metal detectors. With passenger lists
in hand, they check in each person individually.
--- &QC; 
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JetTrain</ENAMEX>, the start-up low-fare airline that was going to fly
from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Newark</ENAMEX> beginning <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this month</TIMEX>, has shifted gears and
now will fly a triangular route between <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philadelphia</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pittsburgh</ENAMEX>, starting in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">mid-September</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">JetTrain</ENAMEX> has been flying
from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pittsburgh</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Orlando</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, for the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past year</TIMEX>. Airline
spokesman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Carmine Cardillo</ENAMEX> said the latest change is aimed at
filling the void left when two other low-cost carriers, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> and
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Nation's Air</ENAMEX>, ended <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Philadelphia</ENAMEX> service.
--- &QC; 
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Wednesday</TIMEX> is the launch date for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Korean Air</ENAMEX>'s new <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Seoul</ENAMEX>
service, three days a week via <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New York</ENAMEX> with a stop to refuel in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Anchorage</ENAMEX>. The first plane lands at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Logan</ENAMEX> at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">9 p.m.</TIMEX> A ceremonial
ribbon-cutting is scheduled at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">British Airways</ENAMEX> gates at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">10</TIMEX>.
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Korean Air</ENAMEX> says this is the first same-plane service ever from
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Massport</ENAMEX> says it's going to hold a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">New England</ENAMEX>
Lobster Festival in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Seoul</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX> to promote this region as a
tourist and business destination.
--- &QC; 
<p>
   About those antlers you might want to bring home as a trophy
from your hunting trip: <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> has revised its entire fee schedule for
unusual baggage since details, compiled by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Best Fares</ENAMEX> magazine, ran
in this column. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> has lifted its ban on antlers and now accepts
them at the discretion of airport agents. Also, skis, golf clubs
and fishing gear are now checked without charge versus the fees of
<NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$45</NUMEX> to <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$75</NUMEX> that were previously posted. Surfboards still cost <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$50</NUMEX>
extra, as do bicycles, pet kennels and scuba gear.
<p>
   But, according to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Best Fares</ENAMEX> researcher <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Elaine Hewlett</ENAMEX>, cyclists
can ship their wheels free now on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Airlines</ENAMEX>  &MD;  although <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United</ENAMEX>
now says it charges <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$50</NUMEX> for scuba equipment.
--- &QC; 
<p>
   Two national luxury hotel chains, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fairmont</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Loew's</ENAMEX>, are
offering a luxury upgrade on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Airlines</ENAMEX> flights and 1,000
frequent flier points on <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American</ENAMEX> if the room booking is charged to
a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Visa</ENAMEX> card. You have to ask for this deal when you reserve ...
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAir</ENAMEX> has authorized its pilots to disconnect the seat-back phone
system in the event of an emergency. Pilots <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last week</TIMEX> got a memo
declaring that the airline ``prefers to furnish press releases for
in-flight anomalies instead of having this information reported
live via telephone from the aircraft.'' A <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">USAir</ENAMEX> spokesman later
said that language ``has been rescinded'' but defended the policy.
<p>
   (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jerry Ackerman</ENAMEX> is a member of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Globe</ENAMEX> staff. He can be
reached by mail at The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boston Globe</ENAMEX>, Box 2378, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Boston</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">MA</ENAMEX>
02107-2378, or by e-mail at <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ackerman</ENAMEX>(AT)<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">globe</ENAMEX>.com)
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-20-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">1354EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
