<STORYID cat=k pri=r> A7503 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tab-z> BC-C-130-CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>-P </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-20</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0998 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-C-130-CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>-PLANE-NYTSF
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CLINTON</ENAMEX>'S C-130 CRASH HAS A CHILLING MESSAGE
   (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
 the rate is not prohibitive  from one of these <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times
Syndicate</ENAMEX> sales representatives:
   (--<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Canada</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pacific</ENAMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">CONNIE WHITE</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kansas City</ENAMEX> at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
   (--<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Europe</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asia</ENAMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">KARL HORWITZ</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Paris</ENAMEX> at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
   (--<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Latin America</ENAMEX>: <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">PAUL FINCH</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Los Angeles</ENAMEX>, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089.
(PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice  into the
``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">TOM WICKER</ENAMEX>
(Distributed by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times Special Features</ENAMEX>)
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   The crash of an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> C-130 carrying equipment for use by
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bill Clinton</ENAMEX> is fair if gruesome warning that some day an American
president may be killed in an air crash.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX> family had departed <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jackson Hole</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Wyo.</ENAMEX>, in another
plane only hours before the C-130 slammed into a mountainside
shortly after takeoff. All nine persons aboard, including a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Secret
Service</ENAMEX> agent, were killed.
<p>
   The death of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ron Brown</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">April</TIMEX> in a somewhat
similar plane crash in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Croatia</ENAMEX> offered the same warning.
<p>
   The destruction of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight 800 off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this summer</TIMEX>,
perhaps by a bomb or even a missile, adds the chilling possibility
of terrorist assault.
<p>
   All these incidents, plus others  &MD;  three fatal C-130 crashes
have occurred <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">in 15 months</TIMEX>  &MD;  should suggest at least two common
sense developments.
<p>
    &MD;  1) As do many husbands and wives and some top business
executives, presidents and vice presidents should follow the
practice of never flying together. Candidates for those offices
should take the same precaution, even if it hinders their ability
to campaign together.
<p>
    &MD;  2) The historic custom of presidential nominees choosing their
vice presidential running mates without regard to their experience
or ability to take over the presidency, if necessary, must no
longer be accepted.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Bob Dole</ENAMEX>, the recent Republican president nominee, appears to
have pondered his choice carefully and named a qualified man in
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jack Kemp</ENAMEX>, the former congressman and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cabinet</ENAMEX> member. So did
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Clinton</ENAMEX>, when he chose Sen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Al Gore</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1992</TIMEX>.
<p>
   As recently as <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1988</TIMEX>, however, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">George Bush</ENAMEX> made an apparently
quixotic choice in <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">J. Danforth Quayle</ENAMEX> In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1952</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Nixon</ENAMEX> was
chosen by Republican leaders  &MD;  not by the nominee, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Dwight
Eisenhower</ENAMEX>  &MD;  less for his presidential qualifications than for his
anti-Communist fame and acceptability to the party's ``old guard.''
<p>
   A constitutional amendment is not necessary to improve the
chances that a qualified vice presidential nominee will be chosen.
And, anyway, such an amendment probably would be hard to write and
impossible to enforce. What is really needed is for American voters
to turn their backs on a presidential nominee who makes a blatantly
political or otherwise unsuitable choice for vice president.
<p>
   Or perhaps presidential nominees should run alone and, if
elected, use provisions of the 22nd Amendment to nominate someone
for vice president.
<p>
   That person then would have to undergo extensive congressional
investigation and confirmation  &MD;  as did <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nelson Rockefeller</ENAMEX>, when he
was nominated for vice president by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gerald Ford</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1974</TIMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ford</ENAMEX> had
been chosen by President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Nixon</ENAMEX> when the sitting vice president,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Spiro T. Agnew</ENAMEX>, had been forced to resign.
<p>
   Proponents of air travel will protest, no doubt accurately, that
it is safer than any form of ground transportation. That
statistical argument overlooks the fact that an air crash is far
more likely to be fatal to all involved than are other forms of
accident.
<p>
   And presidents now travel almost exclusively by air  &MD;  including
helicopters for short hauls.
<p>
   It will be argued, too, that no aircraft could be more carefully
maintained or skillfully operated than those used by a president.
Thousands of commercial passengers can testify to being held up in
scheduled takeoffs or landings because right-of-way was being
cleared for Air Force One.
<p>
   If safe air travel can be guaranteed, it certainly is for the
occupant of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Still, no amount of precaution or skill can preclude the
unexpected or predict the unpredictable. And if terrorism is a
threat, as <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> 800 investigators may conclude, what juicier target
could there be than a plane carrying a president and his entourage?
<p>
   When I was The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> correspondent during
the <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kennedy</ENAMEX> administration, a small group of us termed ourselves
``<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX> regulars''  &MD;  meaning we went on every presidential
trip, no matter how insignificant or unlikely to produce news. We
did so to keep a ``death watch'' on the president  &MD;  though none of
us really believed, until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Nov. 22, 1963</TIMEX>, that it was necessary.
<p>
   President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kennedy</ENAMEX>, of course, was murdered on the ground. That
does not alter the rising odds that some day or some night,
somewhere in an unaccountable world, sometime in the uncharted
future, a high-flying president will be brought to earth by chance,
or by malevolent design.
<p>
    &UR; c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom Wicker</ENAMEX> &LR; 
<p>
    &UR; (<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom Wicker</ENAMEX>, the former <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times</ENAMEX> political columnist, is
the author, most recently, of ``Tragic Failure: Racial Integration
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">America</ENAMEX>.'') &LR; 
<p>
   --------------- &QC; 
