<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1611 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-TERRORISTS- </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-23</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 1711 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-TERRORISTS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT
(ATTN: <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.Y.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Va.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fla.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">R.I.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Hawaii</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Brazil</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>., <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Israel</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Japan</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Libya</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.K.</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Egypt</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Lebanon</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Italy</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Greece</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>)
AUTHORITIES EYE TERRORISTS WHO TARGET PLANES
(lh)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">DOUGLAS FRANTZ</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>  &MD;  In <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June</TIMEX>, a few weeks before the crash of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World
Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 800 off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>, leaders of several Middle
Eastern terrorist organizations backed by the Iranian government
met in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Teheran</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX>, to plan terrorist acts, intelligence
officials said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Among them was the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command</ENAMEX>, an organization that has been linked to
airplane bombings in the past, according to the officials. And its
leader, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ahmed Jabril</ENAMEX>, came to the meeting to ask for permission to
carry out terrorist attacks against American interests, one
intelligence official said.
<p>
   The organizations that attended the meeting, and the session
itself, are among a number of avenues that federal investigators
are following in their inquiry into the crash of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> jet,
according to the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
<p>
   Although the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> has not declared that the plane crashed as the
result of a criminal act, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> crime lab has found traces of
PETN, a component of plastic explosives, on a piece of wreckage
from the cabin of the plane. Investigators noted that PETN was a
component of bombs used in past terrorist bombings of airplanes.
<p>
   The intelligence officials cautioned that they had no evidence
linking the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June</TIMEX> meeting in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Teheran</ENAMEX> to the crash on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 17</TIMEX>. They
note that <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Iran</ENAMEX> is not known to have targeted Americans in recent
years and that the time span between the meeting and the crash may
have been too short to execute a complex operation.
<p>
   But a senior federal investigator working on the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> case said
investigators were interested in learning more about the meeting.
At the same time, though, investigators say they are examining many
other individuals and organizations in their inquiry.
<p>
   If Flight 800 is proved to have been brought down by a bomb, as
most investigators strongly believe, it remains possible that no
foreign terrorists were involved. The crash could have been the
result of a domestic criminal act. Still, if the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> crash is
eventually blamed on a terrorist attack, the investigators said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jabril</ENAMEX> and the others who were in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Teheran</ENAMEX> would be high on a short
list of suspects.
<p>
   Other terrorist groups identified as present at the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Teheran</ENAMEX>
meeting included leaders of the Lebanese-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Hezbollah</ENAMEX>, which has
been linked to the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1983</TIMEX> bomb blast in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Beirut</ENAMEX> that killed 241 <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX>
Marines, and the Egyptian branch of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Islamic Jihad</ENAMEX>, which is loyal
to Sheik <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Omar Abdel Rahman</ENAMEX>. He was convicted of plotting to blow up
the United Nations, and his followers were convicted of the bomb
attack on the World Trade Center.
<p>
   In recent years, a small number of terrorist organizations have
demonstrated the capability of bombing an airplane. While
investigators have not ruled out the possibility of a previously
unknown group, investigators say evidence amassed about the bombs
and methods used in previous attacks may yield important clues in
the investigation of Flight 800.
<p>
   ``If it was a bomb, determining the kind of bomb and the way it
got on the plane will narrow down the universe of suspects,'' said
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vincent Cannistraro</ENAMEX>, a private security consultant and former chief
of counterterrorism at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Central Intelligence Agency</ENAMEX>.
</TEXT>
<TRAILER>
NYT-<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-23-96</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">2135EDT</TIMEX>
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960824.0094 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A1918 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-PROBE-8THTA </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-24</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0844 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-PROBE-8THTAKE-NYT
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NEW YORK</ENAMEX>: early on.
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   To some experts in terrorism and airline security, the notion
that a missile had blown the aircraft out of the sky was
far-fetched, and several expressed amazement at the ``shelf life of
the missile theory.'' The plane was out of range, they said.
<p>
   But others, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> included, had a resilient fealty to the
rocket theory. He and others could not ignore the dozens of
eyewitness accounts testifying to a streaking light intersecting
with the aircraft. The details matched in many ways.
<p>
   In addition, the notion that Stinger missiles from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Afghanistan</ENAMEX>
might have made their way into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> was a longstanding
assumption within law enforcement circles.
<p>
   The presence on the crash scene of officials with the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National
Security Agency</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Defense Intelligence Agency</ENAMEX> reinforced in
some minds that there might have been some intercepted intelligence
regarding a missile attack.
<p>
   And so the viability of the missile theory  &MD;  which seemed to
carry a dread greater than a bomb  &MD;  rose and sank daily, in the
minds of <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> and other investigators. Yet, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX>, early
on, refused to acknowledge publicly how seriously investigators had
taken the possibility of a missile attack.
<p>
   ``I don't want to scare people,'' he said in front of his
agents.
<p>
   Investigators ran down reports of stolen boats on <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX>,
and senior investigators three days into the investigation broke
down the likelihood of the three causes this way: <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">45 percent</NUMEX>
missile, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">45 percent</NUMEX> bomb, <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">10 percent</NUMEX> malfunction.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> ordered his agents to research the Mistral, a
French-made missile that could be launched from a tripod and that
would have had the range capability. Other experts offered the
possibility that a small-engine Cessna might have been equipped to
fire a Sidewinder missile.
<p>
   The missile theory did not go away. Agents spent chunks of their
days rereading the eyewitness interviews. A kind of missile cult
emerged within the ranks of the agents. The group was never more
enthusiastic than when one of the first preliminary positive
results registered at the hangar in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calverton</ENAMEX> showed evidence of
PETN, a component found in some missiles.
<p>
   Meanwhile, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of Defense</ENAMEX>, asked to provide
investigators with a full accounting of military activity that
might have been going on in the area of the crash, launched such a
diligent inquiry that it took days to come up with complete
information, according to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> officials.
<p>
   Public records showed that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> had issued a warning to
mariners that it might be conducting ``firing tests'' in a section
of the sea roughly 80 nautical miles northeast of the crash scene.
The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> also had an aircraft near the crash site. It briefly
helped recover information.
<p>
   By <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">late July</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kallstrom</ENAMEX> had doubts about the missile theory, but
he never completely let go. And despite the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX>'s assurances,
he refused to rule out a ``friendly fire'' mishap, saying only that
``it's not in the crosshairs of my radar.''
<p>
   Then, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">two weeks ago</TIMEX>, came the most dramatic moment, which took
place in a cramped third-floor laboratory in the J. Edgar Hoover
Building in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>. The endless frustration was snapped. The
string of inconclusive results had ended: A positive finding for
the explosives was confirmed with the most sophisticated detection
machinery in the world.
<p>
   The revelation of the finding  &MD;  which investigators insist does
not rule out a missile  &MD;  sharpened the details of the remaining
hunt: find the blast site, and with it the metal wreckage that
could be brought before the cameras.
<p>
   Study the ``sick jewel'' for its signatures that could produce
suspects: what contained the bomb, the exact type of explosive
used, any available fragment of the detonating device. Microscopic
clues had produced breakthroughs for investigators in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pan Am</ENAMEX>
103 bombing, a tiny sliver of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Toshiba</ENAMEX> stereo sending agents to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">North Africa</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   ``It doesn't get us all the way where we need to be,'' a senior
investigator said of the lab finding.
<p>
   But if the mystery had not been completely solved, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> and
others believed something strongly. A wonder had been worked.
<p>
   Yes, it might take a full dredging of the ocean floor before the
right hunk of plane was recovered. Yes, things could have gone more
smoothly. Yes, the safety board investigators would spend the
coming months examining everything and one day recommending a range
of thoughts on industry policies on aircraft construction, perhaps
even on how the safety board and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FBI</ENAMEX> might conduct a similar,
subsequent investigation.
<p>
   ``What an incredible feat is being accomplished,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said
of the entire effort. ``People say <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jacques Cousteau</ENAMEX> does this all
the time, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jacques Cousteau</ENAMEX> makes it look easy. Well, he's working
off <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bimini</ENAMEX> where you can see 94 miles through the water, and he's
picking up shellfish, not jagged pieces of aluminum.''
<p>
   ``There is no <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">McDonald's</ENAMEX> of air safety investigation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
