HIJACKED SUDANESE AIRLINER LANDS IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BRITAIN</ENAMEX>
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">LOUIS J. SALOME</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Cox News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">STANSTED</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">England</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Police negotiated <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> with several
hijackers believed to be Iraqis who seized a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sudan Airways</ENAMEX> plane
with 199 people aboard and demanded that it be flown to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Britain</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   After nearly five hours of negotiations, 160 passengers, most of
them women and children, were allowed to leave the plane. But the
other 26 passengers along with 13 crew remained on board along with
``six or seven'' hijackers claiming to be carrying grenades and
explosives, police said.
<p>
   Police said the hijackers were accompanied by their families and
had asked to see a member of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Iraqi Community Association</ENAMEX> in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX>, an organization that helps Iraqis seeking aslyum.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Essex County</ENAMEX> police said the passengers were mostly Sudanese,
but included Syrians, Saudis, Jordanians and Palestinians. None of
the released passengers were mistreated, although three were sick
and had been taken to a hospital, police said. Their illnesses were
unrelated to the ordeal.
<p>
   Police were questioning the released hostages at a nearby
terminal as negotations with the hijackers, conducted by radio,
continued.
<p>
   ``Everyone seems calm and collected. My understanding is that no
one has been hurt,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Essex</ENAMEX> police spokeswoman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kim White</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sudan Airways</ENAMEX> Flight 150 was hijacked <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">evening</TIMEX> about 25
minutes after it left the Sudanese capital of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Khartoum</ENAMEX> heading for
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Amman</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Jordan</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Airbus</ENAMEX> 310 jetliner landed at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Larnaca International Airport</ENAMEX>
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cyprus</ENAMEX> to refuel before being forced on to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cyprus</ENAMEX>
aviation officials quoted one hijacker as saying he wanted
political asylum in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Britain</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The plane arrived at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Stansted</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">London</ENAMEX>'s third airport 30 miles
to the northeast, at <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">4:30 a.m.</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> (<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">11:30 p.m., Eastern time</TIMEX>,
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Monday</TIMEX>). Armed and masked <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Essex</ENAMEX> police officers surrounded the
aircraft as it stood in an isolated spot on the tarmac two miles
from the terminal.
<p>
   In hijack situations, British authorities usually direct planes
to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Stansted</ENAMEX>, which is especially prepared for such events and is
located in a rural area, rather than to the busier <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Heathrow</ENAMEX> or
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Gatwick</ENAMEX> airports.
<p>
   It has been <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">14 years since a hijacked airplane has landed in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Britain</ENAMEX></TIMEX>.
<p>
   About a dozen police, fire and rescue vehicles were arrayed far
from the plane in case of an accident or if the negotiations turned
sour.
<p>
   Police said the hijackers were releasing the passengers in
groups of 10 or so at a time and that they hoped more would be
freed.
<p>
   It was the second hijacking <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">this year</TIMEX> involving a Sudanese
airliner.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 24</TIMEX>, a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sudan Airways</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Airbus</ENAMEX> A320 plane carrying 40
passengers and crew on an internal flight was hijacked to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Asmara</ENAMEX>,
the Eritrean capital, where the two Sudanese hijackers surrendered
and sought political asylum.
</TEXT>
