<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">NORWAY</ENAMEX>-CRASH-ART-NYT
MORE THAN 140 FEARED DEAD IN RUSSIAN AIRLINER CRASH IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">ARCTIC</ENAMEX>
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYT</ENAMEX> graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(bl)
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX> 
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">OSLO</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norway</ENAMEX>  &MD;  A Russian jetliner carrying more than 140 people
 &MD;  mostly coal miners and their families  &MD;  crashed into a mountain
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> on the remote <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Arctic</ENAMEX> island of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Spitsbergen</ENAMEX> in Norwegian
territory. There appeared to be no survivors, Norwegian authorities
said.
<p>
   The three-engine <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Tupolev</ENAMEX> Tu-154 owned by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Vnukovo Airlines</ENAMEX> was
nearing the end of a flight from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moscow</ENAMEX> when it went off course
amid low clouds and struck <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Opera Mountain</ENAMEX>, a 3,000-foot peak six
miles east of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Svalbard Airport</ENAMEX> at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Longyearbyen</ENAMEX>, the island's main
settlement.
<p>
   The passengers were described as Russians and Ukrainians, most
of them workers for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trust Arktik Ugol</ENAMEX> mining company. They were
a relief force for an equal number of miners and family members who
had been waiting at the airport to take the same jet back to
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moscow</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Russia</ENAMEX>'s ambassador to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norway</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yuri Fokine</ENAMEX>, said that up to 20
children were aboard the jet, but Norwegian authorities in touch
with the airline maintained that the passenger list comprised 125
adults and 4 children, in addition to either 12 or 14 crew members.
<p>
   Flight controllers reported losing radio contact with the jet at
<TIMEX TYPE="TIME">10:15 a.m.</TIMEX> At <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">12:06 p.m.</TIMEX> a Norwegian search party in two
helicopters and a light plane found most of the wreckage on a snowy
plateau, officials said. The rear section of the jet had tumbled
down a cliff, causing a small avalanche.
<p>
   Five rescue workers who landed at the scene determined that
there were no survivors, then left <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">three and a half hours later</TIMEX>
because of thickening fog, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norway</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rescue Coordination Center</ENAMEX>
said. It said the temperature was in the high 30s.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Fokine</ENAMEX> praised the rescue effort in an interview with Norwegian
television and added, ``There was no sign of life when the
helicopters arrived.''
<p>
   A Norwegian minister, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jan Hoifoedt</ENAMEX>, informed the group waiting
at the airport of the crash.
<p>
   ``The tears flowed,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Hoifoedt</ENAMEX> told a radio interviewer. ``Many
had friends, work acquaintances and even some family members
aboard. It is a huge tragedy for so small a community.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Spitsbergen</ENAMEX> is the largest island in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Svalbard</ENAMEX> archipelago,
about 350 miles north of the Norwegian mainland. A <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1920</TIMEX> treaty gave
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norway</ENAMEX> ownership of the archipelago, but the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Soviet Union</ENAMEX> acquired
mining rights in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1935</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Svalbard</ENAMEX>'s population of 2,500, almost two-thirds are
citizens of former Soviet republics. They operate two mines  &MD;  in
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Pyramiden</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Barentsburg</ENAMEX>  &MD;  extracting some 600,000 tons of coal a
year, about twice the output of Norwegian mines.
<p>
   Investigators from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Oslo</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moscow</ENAMEX> are not expected to reach the
crash site until <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>, when removal of the bodies is to
begin. The Norwegian government was also sending criminal
investigators, though officials said there was no immediate sign of
foul play.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">Early this evening</TIMEX> a Norwegian helicopter crew managed to lift
two prefabricated cabins onto the plateau near the wreckage. From
there, two or three sentries were to make sure the site is not
disturbed during the <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>.
<p>
   ``There are about 2,000 polar bears on this island,'' said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rune
B. Hansen</ENAMEX>, the acting governor. ``We haven't seen any around here
lately but they are unpredictable and can suddenly be anywhere.''
<p>
   Though the number of air fatalities in the former <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Soviet Union</ENAMEX>
has declined in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">last two years</TIMEX>, it remains alarmingly high
compared to what it was during the Soviet era.
<p>
   When the Soviet airline <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Aeroflot</ENAMEX> was broken up <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">five years ago</TIMEX>,
many new air companies were created. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Vnukovo Airlines</ENAMEX> is one of
dozens of these so-called ``babyflots,'' which have been plagued by
lack of cash and poor maintenance. Many if not most of the aircraft
in the Russian fleets are long past retirement age.
<p>
   An official at <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Vnukova Airlines</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Moscow</ENAMEX> refused to comment
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX> on the crash.
</TEXT>
