<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A6992 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=taf-z> BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<DATE> &LR; </DATE>
<NWORDS> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">09-05</TIMEX> </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>-CRASH-NYT
ROUGH SEAS PARALYZE SEARCH FOR PLANE WRECKAGE
(sw)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">ANDREW C. REVKIN</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">SMITHTOWN</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">N.Y.</ENAMEX>  &MD;  On the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">50th day after the crash of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Trans World
Airlines</ENAMEX> Flight 800</TIMEX>, senior investigators said that persistent
rough seas off the coast of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> had paralyzed efforts to
collect the remaining wreckage of the shattered jumbo jet.
<p>
   The only activity by divers in the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past seven days</TIMEX> was one
six-hour mission completed early on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Robert
Francis</ENAMEX>, the vice chairman of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety
Board</ENAMEX>, said. The divers, from the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> ship Grapple, were able to
reach the last remaining large field of debris, but rising seas on
the surface and storm-stirred silt on the bottom reduced visibility
to almost zero and limited them to one haul of only a dozen small
pieces of wreckage, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Even those pieces remained on the stern of the ship as seas grew
rougher on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, leaving investigators ashore with no new flow
of potential clues to the cause of the explosion that split the jet
on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">July 17</TIMEX>, killing all 230 people aboard.
<p>
   With one hurricane recently departed and another one stirring
the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Atlantic</ENAMEX> anew, conditions were so bad on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">morning</TIMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said, that a wave knocked him into the water as it swept
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> speedboat carrying him and several other investigators to
the Grapple.
<p>
   ``Fortunately, the admiral was kind enough to come back and get
me,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said of Rear Adm. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Edward Kristensen</ENAMEX>, the pilot of the
speedboat and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Navy</ENAMEX> officer in charge of the salvage effort.
<p>
   Even though more than two-thirds of the aircraft had been
recovered as of <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">a week ago</TIMEX>, and much of that debris has been
closely scrutinized, criminal and transportation investigators say
they still lack sufficient evidence to show that the explosion was
caused by a bomb or missile rather than a mechanical failure.
<p>
   In a new sign that investigators still lacked many of the pieces
shed by the airplane in the earliest moments of its disintegration,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> said that as soon as weather permitted a sonar sweep of the
bottom would be extended west and south of the areas that had
already been searched.
<p>
   The decision to backtrack another half mile along the ill-fated
plane's path from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy International Airport</ENAMEX> was made after a
new analysis of the last radar traces of pieces falling from the
airplane, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kristensen</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   Despite the lack of new wreckage pulled from the ocean, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX>
said, investigative teams at a complex of hangars in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Calverton</ENAMEX>,
were still busy working with what they already had. He said new
pieces were added on <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX> to a growing reconstruction of the
cabin between the wings.
<p>
   But some of the most coveted pieces of wreckage were still
missing, he said, including many parts of the center fuel tank,
which sat under a group of seats that many investigators say were
the likely center of the explosion.
<p>
   On <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Thursday</TIMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Francis</ENAMEX> confirmed previous reports that two seats
at the right end of row 23 had large holes ripped in their metal
backs. ``They may turn out to be significant,'' he said, but he
cautioned that ``there are a lot of ways things can get holes in
them after an airplane accident.''
</TEXT>
